(88, 2, '2012-03-30 09:22:09', '2012-03-30 09:22:09', '<p>Bennett Kayser, a member of the Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) board recently announced that he intends to vote against all charter-related items. He needs to hear from parents!\nBennett Kayser, a member of the Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) board recently announced that he intends to vote against all charter-related items due to the district\'s financial difficulties. He needs to hear from school leaders, teachers and parents in his district today!\n<a href="http://action.familiesthatcan.org/Core/core.aspx?Screen=Alert&amp;APP=GAC&amp;AID=1321&amp;IssueID=28079&amp;SiteID=-1&amp;VV_CULTURE=en-us">Send him an email.</a>\n<strong>Bennett Kayser</strong>\nLAUSD Board District 5\nRepresenting East, Northeast, and Southeast Los Angeles\nPhone: (213) 241-5555\nBoardDistrict5@lausd.net\nFax: 213-241-8467\nPrintable handouts: <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/members/Bennett_Kayser_charter_attacks_handout.pdf">English</a> / <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/members/Bennett_Kayser_charter_attacks_handout_espanol.pdf">Spanish</a>\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/members/2012/03/lausd-bennett-kayser-action-kit.html">School leaders can also use our bilingual action kit to get out the word.</a></p>\n', 'Action Alert: Tell Bennett Kayser to Stop Attacking Charters', 'Bennett Kayser, a member of the Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) board recently announced that he intends to vote against all charter-related items. He needs to hear from parents!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'action_alert_tell_bennett_kayser_to_stop_attacking_charters', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/action_alert_tell_bennett_kayser_to_stop_attacking_charters/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(89, 2, '2012-03-30 09:43:40', '2012-03-30 09:43:40', '<p><a href="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/members/Bennett_Kayser_charter_attacks_handout_espanol.pdf">Folleto para compartir</a>\nEl 13 de marzo, Bennett Kayser de la Junta Directiva Escolar de Los Angeles (LAUSD), anunci√≥ que planea votar "NO" a todo relacionado con las escuelas ch√°rter, no le importa si nuestras escuelas est√°n haciendo un gran trabajo para los ni√±os!\nEso quiere decir que no aprobar√° que las escuelas ch√°rter reciban los edificios que necesitan. Esto significa que cuando las escuelas ch√°rter est√°n por renovar, que votar√° a cerrarlas, no  importa sus  los resultados acad√©micos de nuestras escuelas!\nEl Honorable Bennet Kayser necesita o√≠r de usted hoy!\nDile a Bennett Kayser por qu√© usted ha elegido una escuela ch√°rter y lo que nuestra escuela significa para su familia. D√≠gale:\n- Las escuelas ch√°rter son escuelas p√∫blicas y queremos que usted represente y defienda a TODOS los estudiantes, incluyendo estudiantes de escuelas ch√°rter.\n- Nuestra escuela sirve a todos los estudiantes, incluyendo estudiantes de educaci√≥n especial y estudiantes que est√°n aprendiendo Ingl√©s.\n- Quiero que ponga a los estudiantes, no la pol√≠tica en primero! Apoye escuelas de alta calidad como la nuestra y deje de atacar a las escuelas ch√°rter!\n<strong>Bennett Kayser</strong>\nDistrito 5 del LAUSD\nRepresenta de este, noreste y sureste de Los √Ångeles\nTel√©fono: (213) 241-5555\nBoardDistrict5@lausd.net\nFax: 213-241-8467\nTambi√©n puede <a href="http://action.familiesthatcan.org/Core/core.aspx?Screen=Alert&amp;APP=GAC&amp;AID=1321&amp;IssueID=28079&amp;SiteID=-1&amp;VV_CULTURE=en-us">enviar un correo electr√≥nico</a> f√°cilmente usando nuestro sistema.</p>\n', '¬°Dile a Bennett Kayser "Dejen de atacar a las escuelas ch√°rter"!', 'El 13 de marzo, Bennett Kayser de la Junta Directiva Escolar de Los Angeles (LAUSD), anunci√≥ que planea votar "NO" a todo relacionado con las escuelas ch√°rter, no le importa si nuestras escuelas est√°n haciendo un gran trabajo para los ni√±os! ¬°Necesita o√≠r de usted hoy!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'dile_a_bennett_kayser_dejen_de_atacar_a_las_escuelas_charter', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/dile_a_bennett_kayser_dejen_de_atacar_a_las_escuelas_charter/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(90, 2, '2012-04-03 10:59:28', '2012-04-03 10:59:28', '<div class="figure embedded-image right"><a rel="lightbox" href="/assets_c/2012/04/vincent_oakland_family_pic-thumb-612xauto-2978.jpg" title="vincent_oakland_family_pic.jpg"><img alt="vincent_oakland_family_pic.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/04/vincent_oakland_family_pic-thumb-220x286-2978.jpg" width="220" height="286" class="mt-image-right" /></a></div>\n\n<p>When politicians talk about school reform, the changes they propose can sometimes take years to go into effect or make a difference.  But parents with young children don\'t have time to wait. Their child\'s time is NOW!\nLatonya and John Hughes are not waiting.  They are parents at <a href="http://www.vincentacademy.org/">Vincent Academy</a> in Oakland, a new charter public school where their son is now a kindergartner.  They sent their son to a well-known private school in Oakland for preschool, but weren\'t sure that it was necessarily the best fit for their gifted son, who was not being challenged. The Hughes did extensive research to find the best match for their son, eventually finding Vincent Academy through the <a href="http://parents.berkeley.edu/">Berkeley Parents Network</a>.\n"If kids aren\'t challenged and aren\'t learning, they get bored and then all of a sudden there are \'disciplinary\' issues in the classroom" said Hughes.   Latonya credits the practice of differentiated instruction for her son\'s academic growth.  Spending lots of time with their son at home, Latonya and John want a school that is able to push their kid, even though he\'s bright and advanced. "We could notice a difference by October."\nThe new charter school, Vincent Academy, is the first charter school in West Oakland to be approved by the Oakland Unified School District (OUSD) since the district was put in state receivership (2003 - 2009).  After being approved by the OUSD Board of Education in 2010, Vincent Academy opened its doors this school year with three classrooms - two kindergarten classes and one first grade class. The bright new school is tucked away on Union and 19th Streets, next door to Ralph Bunche High School.\nMany in West Oakland, a community that has a long strong history of activism and engagement, have resisted the concept of charter public schools for many years.  Long-time West Oakland resident and community leader, Ron Muhammad, credits the resistance to the perception of charter schools as private entities that are being operated by "outsiders" coming in and taking up community land, space and resources.   However, the purpose of the Charter Schools Act passed in 1992 was the exact opposite - its purpose was to empower parents, teachers, and community leaders to create the schools that the children within that community needed - not over years, but TODAY.\nVincent Academy\'s principal, Sandra Phillips, is able to relate well to the West Oakland community - having ties to the East Bay since her time at UC Berkeley as an undergrad.  Ms. Phillips\' connection to community and her desire to empower parents has made Vincent Academy an immediate West Oakland fixture.\nOn March 27, Vincent Academy signed our <a href="/2012/03/sign-on-to-partner-with-families-that-can.html">Commitment Pledge</a> to partner with Families that Can. Vincent Academy parents are excited about sharing the success they\'ve found at this small school in just eight  short months, and are even more excited about the great work ahead as Vincent Academy continues to grow.\nJohn Hughes, an active member of Vincent Academy\'s PTAC (Parent Teacher Advisory Council), shared that his parent activism is not just for his child, but for all kids.\nEvery little bit that each of us contributes, will have a lasting impact on the future of California.\nWhat little bit can you give?  Encourage your school community to <a href="/join">sign up to FTC</a> to not only access resources, but to also offer themselves as a resource and inspiration for other California public school parents.</p>\n', 'Oakland Parents Found New Charter School', 'Meet Latonya and John Hughes, proud parents of a kindergartner at the new Vincent Academy charter school in Oakland!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'oakland_parents_found_new_charter_school', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/oakland_parents_found_new_charter_school/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(91, 2, '2012-04-02 11:13:26', '2012-04-02 11:13:26', '<p>Alliance Gertz-Ressler High School, a public charter school serving a traditionally underserved community of Latino and African-American students in Los Angeles, celebrated its recognition this week as a National Blue Ribbon School.  State Senator Kevin de Le√≥n and LAUSD Board President M√≥nica Garc√≠a joined <a href="http://www.laalliance.org/">Alliance College-Ready Public Schools</a> Executive Director Judy Burton and Alliance Gertz-Ressler High School for the ceremony.\nThe National Blue Ribbon Award is presented by the U.S. Department of Education and recognizes schools across the nation that have demonstrated continued growth in student achievement based upon various criteria. This year, Alliance Gertz-Ressler is one of only two high schools in California and the only school in LAUSD to receive the prestigious award.  A total of 93% of students at the school are eligible for free and reduced lunch.</p>\n\n<div class="pkg has-caption embedded-image left" style="width: 530px"><a rel="lightbox" href="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/assets_c/2012/04/alliance_blue_ribbon_school_2012-thumb-640xauto-2968.jpg" title="alliance_blue_ribbon_school_2012.jpg"><img alt="alliance_blue_ribbon_school_2012.jpg" src="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/assets_c/2012/04/alliance_blue_ribbon_school_2012-thumb-530x397-2968.jpg" width="530" height="397" class="mt-image-left" /></a><p class="caption">Senator Kevin de Leon congratulates Judy Burton on the school\'s honor.</p></div>\n\n<p>"I congratulate Alliance Gertz-Ressler High School for being a recipient of The National Blue Ribbon award.   It\'s an honor to have such a high-achieving school in my district which serves the community and prepares students for college," said State Senator Kevin de Le√≥n.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="530" height="389" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/KDFRCCyi3XU" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>"The National Blue Ribbon Award is a reflection of the diligent and dedicated students and staff at Alliance Gertz-Ressler High School.  I am extremely proud of them and of this honor," said James Waller, Alliance Gertz-Ressler Principal.  Alliance College-Ready Public Schools President and CEO Judy Ivie Burton echoed his comments, "I am so proud of the students and staff of Alliance Gertz-Ressler High School for achieving this tremendous honor.  All children can learn and achieve at high levels given the opportunity to do so, and Alliance Gertz-Ressler High School is proof."\nFounded in 2004, with the simple conviction that every student can graduate from high school and succeed in college, Alliance College-Ready Public Schools has grown to 20 public charter middle and high schools serving more than 8,500 students from Los Angeles\' poorest communities with historically underperforming schools.  This past year, four Alliance schools ranked in the top 10% of all LAUSD high schools and 95% of Alliance students have gone on to college.\nThe Alliance was one of the networks of charter schools that helped found Families That Can in 2007. Congratulations on this incredible success!</p>\n', 'Alliance\'s Gertz-Ressler HS Honored With National Blue Ribbon Award', 'Congratulations on this huge accomplishment!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'alliances_gertz-ressler_hs_honored_with_national_blue_ribbon_award', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/alliances_gertz-ressler_hs_honored_with_national_blue_ribbon_award/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(92, 2, '2012-04-05 13:48:54', '2012-04-05 13:48:54', '<p>On February 4, 2012, more than 5,000 parents from more than 100 charter schools rallied at Exposition Park in Los Angeles to demand high-quality public schools in every community and fair funding and facilities for all public school students. Los Angeles Mayor Antonio Villaraigosa addressed parents at the <a href="/2012/01/join-us-feb-4.html">"Schools We Can Believe In" rally</a>.\n"I can\'t tell you how inspiring it is to see thousands of parents here speaking with one voice, saying \'Failure is not an option,\' families that are demanding change, that are demanding the best possible schools for their kids."</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="530" height="299" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/videoseries?index=14&amp;list=PLC7F71762C4202382&amp;hl=en_US" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>"You are the key. Without dedicated moms and dads, we will never turn around our school system," said Mayor Villaraigosa, who shared some of his own story. He said that when he attended Roosevelt High School in East Los Angeles in the 1960s, the school had a 75 percent drop-out rate.\n"I got the feeling that the school had given up on me and I could have given up on myself. My story could have ended there. I could have been a statistic, but my mother didn\'t give up on me and you\'re not giving up on your kids either," said Villaraigosa.\nHe pointed out that the number of charter schools in Los Angeles has doubled since 2005.\n"When parents can vote with their feet, they don\'t have to accept failing schools anymore," he said. "Because you have options, the number of schools in LA Unified meeting the state goal on the academic performance index has also doubled."\nHe pointed out that parents need tools to have an impact - information like school report cards and levers for change like the <a href="http://parentrevolution.org/content/basic-overview">Parent Trigger</a>.\n"Knowledge is power. When parents have good information, they can make good choices," he said.\nHe also emphasized that all our public schools need more funding and that parents need to convey that to their elected officials and hold schools accountable for serving students well.\n"Parents, I believe in you. I believe in your kids. The future of education in Los Angeles depends on you," said Villaraigosa.</p>\n', 'LA Mayor Tells Parents: "You are the key"', '"Without dedicated moms and dads, we will never turn around our school system," Mayor Villaraigosa told 5,000+ parents in LA at the "Schools We Can Believe In" rally.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'la_mayor_tells_parents_you_are_the_key', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/la_mayor_tells_parents_you_are_the_key/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(93, 2, '2012-04-05 14:34:42', '2012-04-05 14:34:42', '<p>On March 13, Bennett Kayser, who serves on the Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) board, announced that he plans to vote "NO" on everything related to charter schools.\nFamilies That Can immediately [sent out an action alert](Parents Tell Boardmember: "Stop Attacking Charters!") to parents in Kayser\'s district. Parents and students were infuriated that despite their schools\' success and strong commitment to serve the students in their communities, their own school board member was discrediting all their efforts.\nBoardmember Kayser thought we weren\'t paying attention, but I\'m sure that changed once he starting receiving emails and phone calls from his constituents.  To date, <strong>302 emails</strong> have been sent to Bennett Kayser and they will continue arriving to his office as long as he continues attacking charter schools!\n- Teachers reacted because this meant that all the hours they spent on lesson planning, graded homework assignments, reviewing tests, tutoring their students and all their other activities school related are not being appreciated by their School Board Member Bennett Kayser.\n- Students reacted because this meant to them that all the hours spent on studying at home, researching for their projects, paying attention in class, having the desire to excel in their school work to get into college did not matter their School Board Member Bennett Kayser.\n- Parents reacted to this because it meant that their participation in their child\'s school, those early school drop offs, those long night hours helping their child with their book reports or collages are not appreciated by their School Board Member Bennett Kayser.\nThe question that parents and students keep asking themselves is: How is it that their school board member Bennett Kayser is not supporting their successful charter schools? Below are some of the high-performing charter schools located in the district Boardmember Kayser represents. The state\'s goal is for all schools is an API score of 800+.</p>\n\n<h3>Charter School API Scores (as of 2010-11)</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Alliance Environmental Science and Technology High School -  881</li>\n<li>Academia Moderna - 717</li>\n<li>Aspire Antonio Maria Lugo Academy - 847</li>\n<li>California Academy for Liberal Studies (CALS) - 861</li>\n<li>Celerity Troika Charter School - 970</li>\n<li>Futuro College Prep - 795</li>\n<li>KIPP Comienza Community Prep - 963</li>\n<li>Renaissance Arts Academy - 877\nData was obtained from <a href="http://reportcard.lausd.net">reportcard.lausd.net</a>.\nIt\'s worth noting that Academic Moderna has had a 65 point growth from 2009 - 2012 and Futuro College Prep hit 795 in the first year it opened!\nPlease <a href="/2012/03/action-alert-tell-bennett-kayser-to-stop-attacking-charters.html">contact Boardmember Bennett Kayser</a> today and tell him to put students first, NOT politics!</li>\n</ul>\n', 'Parents Tell Boardmember: "Stop Attacking Charters!"', 'When LAUSD Boardmember Bennett Kayser said he planned to vote no on everything related to charter schools, parents and students spoke up!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'parents_tell_boardmember_stop_attacking_charters', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/parents_tell_boardmember_stop_attacking_charters/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(94, 2, '2012-04-09 09:48:44', '2012-04-09 09:48:44', '<p>We are super excited to announce that we have relaunched the Families That Can website to be an even better source of news and training for parent advocates like you.\nBesides having a great new look, the improvements include:</p>\n\n<h4>MORE TRAINING</h4>\n\n<p>Our new "<a href="/training/">Train for Action</a>" section has everything from how to find your legislator to videos on grassroots advocacy.</p>\n\n<h4>BILINGUAL</h4>\n\n<p>All key web content is now available in both English and <a href="/index_es.html">Spanish</a>.</p>\n\n<h4>EASY</h4>\n\n<p>With a sign-up box on every page, it\'s easy to <a href="/join/">sign up for our free e-newsletter</a> and keep in touch.</p>\n\n<h4>SCHOOL LEADERS SECTION</h4>\n\n<p>In this <a href="/for-school-leaders/">new section</a>, school leaders can learn more about FTC and sign up to partner with us.</p>\n\n<h4>PARENT VOICES</h4>\n\n<p>Your stories are powerful! That\'s why we\'re excited to be able to <a href="/news/parent-voices/">highlight your voices</a> as inspiration for other parents.</p>\n\n<h4>INTERACTIVE</h4>\n\n<p>We want to hear from you! Facebook comments now makes it easy to post and share. If you have a Facebook account, you\'ll can post right at the bottom of this page, no additional log-in required!\nSo tell us: What do you think of our website? What kinds of news stories, information or new training materials would you like to see? We want to hear from you! You can also send ideas to <a href="mailto:contact@familiesthatcan.org">contact@familiesthatcan.org</a>.</p>\n', 'What do you think of our new website?', 'We want to hear from you. What kinds of news stories, information or new training materials would you like to see?\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'what_do_you_think_of_our_new_website', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '2016-01-13 04:19:58', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/what_do_you_think_of_our_new_website/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
