(149, 2, '2012-09-12 09:07:22', '2012-09-12 09:07:22', '<p>Families That Can recognizes that the best advocates a school can have are their parents! Parents do not have any political special interest nor do they have self-interest...the only interest a parent has is their child.  Parents are always looking for ways to get involved and support their child\'s school and we want to make sure we channel that energy and excitement to support all the wonderful things our public charter schools are doing!\nOn Thursday, September 6, 47 Parent Leaders representing different charter schools from across Los Angeles convened at Santa Monica Blvd Community Charter, a Fenton Charter School, for their Los Angeles Regional meeting.  Now you may ask yourself, what is a Parent Leader?\n"Parent Leader" isn\'t a job title; it\'s what you do. Parent Leaders are the people who have that direct contact with ALL the parents --- whether you are an Executive Director, Assistant Principal, Parent Director, Parent Coordinator,  Parent Liaison, Parent Outreach Coordinator, Dean of Students,  or a parent volunteer or head of your school\'s parent committee... titles vary across all schools, but these Parent Leaders are the gatekeepers to engaging families in school activities.\nFamilies That Can continues to empower these Parent Leaders with all the resources and tools needed to engage their families on a wide range of activities. This past meeting highlighted:\n- LAUSD Board Member Steve Zimmer\'s introduction of a resolution that wanted to limit public charter growth and parent choice\n- CIVICS - <a href="/2012/07/families-that-can-launches-the-civics-campaign.html">California Informed Voters In Charter Schools</a>\n- Families That Can\'s Partnership with <a href="http://nationalvoterregistrationday.org/">National Voter Registration Day</a> on September 25: A representative from the Los Angeles County Registrar\'s Office provided a training at the meeting to certify Parent Leaders as Deputy Registrars\n- Families That Can\'s Annual Parent Summit in San Diego, a one-day event that is part of the <a href="http://charterconference.org/2013/">California Charter Schools Association\'s annual conference</a>. This year, we will be celebrating the <a href="http://anniversary.ccsa.org">20th anniversary of California charter schools</a>!</p>\n\n<h3>Power of the Parents</h3>\n\n<p>We are amazed what Parent Leaders are capable of doing when given the knowledge and tools. On Thursday, September 8, we shared the urgency and need for the parent voice to be heard at Tuesday, September 11 school board meeting where Board Member Steve Zimmer was introducing a resolution limiting parent choice.\nWithin just a three-day turnaround, each representative went back to their school communities and hundreds of calls, emails and petitions went to all LAUSD school board members letting them know that parents will not accept limited choices for their child\'s education! Two hundred parents came to the meeting and packed the board room and they\'re ready to do it again on October 9, when this resolution comes up for a vote.\n- <a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.401017803297678.94829.102530249813103&amp;type=3">See photos from the meeting on Facebook.</a>\nLeaving the board meeting definitely reassured parents of one thing - that their voice is powerful.</p>\n\n<h4>Register to vote!</h4>\n\n<p>We\'re also gearing up for National Voter Registration Day on September 25 - a great chance to let all elected officials know that charter school parents, teachers, 18 year old high school students and all community supporters will come out to vote in all upcoming elections. Families That Can has partnered with National Voter Registration Day - a nation-wide campaign to register 100,000 voters across our nation.  In Los Angeles, 50 charter schools have already committed to registering 20 new voters each! As these new partnerships and campaigns are introduced to schools, we want to make sure that they are successful and each Parent Leader feels confident and equipped to present and share out all the information with their families.</p>\n\n<h4>Save the date - December 5</h4>\n\n<p>We are eager to continue educating and empowering parents and look forward to our next Regional Charter School Parent Leader meeting on December 5 to celebrate our continued successes and prepare for upcoming LAUSD Board Member elections, Mayoral elections and City Council elections in Los Angeles.\nParents do have a voice and choice!\n<a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.400475086685283.94704.102530249813103&amp;type=1">Check out our pictures from the Sept. 8 Parent Leader meeting.</a></p>\n', '47 LA Parent Leaders Come Together to Kick Off the School Year', 'From rallying at the school board meeting to registering voters, a lot is planned for this fall!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '47_la_parent_leaders_come_together_to_kick_off_the_school_year', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/47_la_parent_leaders_come_together_to_kick_off_the_school_year/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(150, 2, '2012-09-12 14:36:20', '2012-09-12 14:36:20', '<p>Hay veces que una victoria para una escuela ch√°rter tarda a√±os en convertirse en realidad.  Tal es el caso de la escuela preparatoria Sacramento Ch√°rter High, la cual fue otorgada un acuerdo para el uso de un edificio por un plazo de cinco a√±os por la Junta del Distrito Unificado de la Ciudad de Sacramento en la primavera del 2012.  Sacramento Ch√°rter High se convirti√≥ en una escuela ch√°rter en el 2003, y desde entonces, hab√≠a tenido que renovar el uso de su edificio anualmente.\nAinye Long, Directora de Integraci√≥n de Familias y la Comunidad de Las Familias S√≠ Pueden, trabaj√≥ arduamente para movilizar a padres y estudiantes el a√±o pasado, cuando se present√≥ una propuesta para intercambiar los planteles escolares de Sacramento Ch√°rter High y la escuela West Campus High, lo cual hubiera limitado el espacio disponible para actividades atl√©ticas para estudiantes.  Ainye atribuye el acuerdo plasmado a un n√∫mero de factores que han estado en desarrollo durante la √∫ltima d√©cada.\nSacramento Ch√°rter High ha estado en discusiones para el uso de su plantel por varios anos.  La Junta Escolar del Distrito Unificado de la Ciudad de Sacramento hab√≠a considerado cerrar el plantel para ahorrar fondos en declive.  El intercambio de planteles entre Sacramento Ch√°rter High y West Campus fue uno de los planes propuestos para ahorrar fondos.  Al igual que otras escuelas ch√°rter, Sacramento Ch√°rter High no cuenta con la misma matriculaci√≥n de estudiantes que otras escuelas preparatorias de la regi√≥n.  Opositores se han negado a decir que Sacramento Ch√°rter High no contaba con el permiso para reclutar a estudiantes de escuelas secundarias hasta el a√±o escolar del 2011-12.\nAl poco tiempo de convertirse en una escuela ch√°rter, un grupo de padres del √°rea de East Sacramento unieron sus fuerzas para formar el grupo "Where\'s My High School?", o "?D√≥nde Est√° Mi Preparatoria?  Estos padres aseveraron que al convertirse en una escuela ch√°rter, Sacramento Ch√°rter High dej√≥ a estudiantes sin una preparatoria.  De hecho, varios presentaron una demanda contra el distrito, y una corte decidi√≥ que una nueva preparatoria ser√≠a construida.  Desafortunadamente, el √°rea de East Sacramento est√° abarrotada, y existen muy pocas √°reas para construir una nueva escuela preparatoria.  Durante los √∫ltimos ocho a√±os, la comunidad y varios miembros de la junta escolar han propuesto planteles para la nueva escuela, pero ninguno se ha dado sin retos.  Actualmente, el enfoque para abrir una nueva preparatoria en East Sacramento contin√∫a, y el plantel donde actualmente reside la escuela Sacramento Ch√°rter High sigue siendo de gran inter√©s.\nCuando la Junta Escolar de la Ciudad de Sacramento propuso intercambiar los planteles de Sacramento Ch√°rter High y West Campus el a√±o pasado, los padres de ambas escuelas lucharon para detener dicho plan.  Esta fue la √∫ltima la gota que derram√≥ el vaso de agua para la comunidad, con padres, estudiantes, maestros y miembros de la junta escolar cansados de tratar de despojar a la escuela Sacramento Ch√°rter High de su plantel por casi una d√©cada.  Muchos estuvieron dispuestos a poner punto final a este asunto.  En diciembre del 2011, el miembro de la junta escolar que originalmente propuso el intercambio de planteles, retir√≥ su propuesta.  Para la primavera del 2012, miembros de la Junta Escolar por fin reconocieron que la matriculaci√≥n en Sacramento Ch√°rter High estaba creciendo, y la comunidad quer√≠a que la escuela permaneciera en la hist√≥rica √°rea de Oak Park, uno de los suburbios m√°s antiguos de la ciudad.\nEl liderazgo de los padres realmente tuvo un impacto esencial para Sacramento Ch√°rter High.  Varias familias invitaron a miembros de la Junta Escolar a visitar la escuela, otras escribieron cartas, y muchas m√°s asistieron a las juntas de la directiva escolar.  Los padres jam√°s se dieron por vencidos.  Ahora, pueden sentirse orgullosos de que sus hijos podr√°n permanecer en el mismo plantel por los pr√≥ximos cinco anos.</p>\n', 'Acuerdo de Cinco A√±os Para el Uso de Un Edificio para la Escuela Preparatoria Sacramento Ch√°rter', 'Los esfuerzos de los padres de familia tuvieron impacto\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'acuerdo_de_cinco_anos_para_el_uso_de_un_edificio_para_la_escuela_preparatoria_sacramento_charter', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/acuerdo_de_cinco_anos_para_el_uso_de_un_edificio_para_la_escuela_preparatoria_sacramento_charter/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(151, 2, '2012-09-12 14:39:06', '2012-09-12 14:39:06', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="Sac High Rally Protesters Dec 2011 (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/01/Rally and end of the year 062-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>Sometimes it takes years of advocacy before a school can claim victory on a challenging issue. Such was the case with Sacramento Charter High School which was just granted its first 5-year facility use agreement from the Sacramento City Unified School District Board of Education in the spring of 2012. Sac High became a charter in 2003 and has been struggling with year-to-year facility renewals from the beginning.\nAinye Long, Director of Family and Community Engagement for Families That Can, worked to mobilize parents and students last fall when a proposed facility swap would have forced Sacramento Charter High School to move to a smaller site at West Campus High School with insufficient space for athletics. She attributes the facility use agreement victory to a number of factors that have developed over the last decade.\nSacramento Charter High School has been the subject of facility-use discussions for years. Citing their declining budget, the Sacramento City Unified School District Board considered saving money by closing schools that were operating at low capacity. A West Campus/Sac High swap proposal was intended to be part of those cost-saving measures.  Like many charters, the school doesn\'t have the same high enrollment numbers as the other traditional high schools in similar sized facilities in the region. Opponents have rarely noted that Sac High was not allowed to recruit students at district middle schools until the 2011-12 school year.\nNot long after Sacramento High School was converted from a traditional high school to a charter, a small group of parents from East Sacramento joined together to form "Where\'s My High School?" WMHS leaders believed that the students in East Sacramento were left without a comprehensive high school when Sac High became a charter school. Some parents sued the district over the lack of high school options and a court agreed that a new high school would have to be built. Unfortunately, the East Sacramento area is densely populated and few locations exist that would be big enough for a new high school. Over the past eight years, many locations have been proposed by the community and school board members, but each has been challenged. To this day, an East Sacramento high school continues to be a major focus of school politics in Sacramento with a continued focus on the Sacramento Charter High Campus.\nWhen the SCUSD Board proposed the facility swap last fall, parents at both Sac High and West Campus High School fought to prevent it. It was the final straw for the community, with parents, students, teachers and board members tired of the wrestling over the Sacramento Charter High School campus for almost a decade. Many were ready to put the long-standing issue to rest. The board member who proposed the swap responded to the outcry from parents and took the proposal off the table in December 2011. By the Spring of 2012, the SCUSD board members seemed to recognize that Sac High\'s enrollment was growing and the community wanted to keep Sac High in its historic location in Oak Park, the oldest suburb of Sacramento. Parent leadership made the difference at Sac High. Families invited their board trustee to visit the school. They wrote letters. They attended board meetings. They never gave up. And in the end, they can now rest knowing that Sac High will be able to stay put for the next five years.</p>\n', '5-Year Facility Use Agreement for Sacramento Charter High School', 'Victory comes after years of work by parents\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '5-year_facility_use_agreement_for_sacramento_charter_high_school', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/5-year_facility_use_agreement_for_sacramento_charter_high_school/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(152, 2, '2012-09-12 15:09:19', '2012-09-12 15:09:19', '<p>Ay√∫denos a difundir informaci√≥n mediante la inclusi√≥n de nuestras noticias en su bolet√≠n escolar o en su p√°gina web. Nosotros incluiremos un breve art√≠culo en nuestra p√°gina de web todos los meses para hacer este proceso mucho m√°s f√°cil para usted.</p>\n\n<h3>El 25 de Septiembre es el D√≠a Nacional de Inscripci√≥n Electoral</h3>\n\n<p>Nuestros funcionarios electos toman decisiones importantes diariamente que afectan a nuestras escuelas y nuestros ni√±os. Ejercer el derecho al voto es la base de nuestro sistema democr√°tico, y un s√≠mbolo de la fortaleza de nuestras comunidades. Sea un ejemplo para sus hijos, y haga que su voz sea escuchada votando en las elecciones del 6 de noviembre.\n¬øTodav√≠a no se ha registrado?\nNuestra escuela [NOMBRE DE LA ESCUELA] est√° orgullosa de unirse a m√°s de 700 grupos comunitarios de todo el pa√≠s que participar√°n en el D√≠a Nacional de Inscripci√≥n Electoral el 25 de septiembre. El tema de este evento nacional no-partidista es sencillo: Reg√≠strese en septiembre, vote en noviembre.\n[Put details about how parents can participate at your school -forms in the school office, a table in front of school on Sept. 25, etc.]\nUsted puede registrarse para votar en l√≠nea o puede tambi√©n recoger un formulario en la oficina electoral de su condado, bibliotecas locales, u oficinas de correo. Las elecciones son administradas por la Secretar√≠a del Estado de California. Visite su p√°gina web en www.sos.ca.gov/elections/new-voter/spanish/ para obtener m√°s informaci√≥n o para averiguar si ya est√° registrado.\nLos votantes pueden obtener ayuda adicional en espa√±ol llamando gratis a la l√≠nea especial de la Secretar√≠a del Estado al (800) 232-VOTA (8682)</p>\n', 'Art√≠culo para el Septiembre: El 25 de Septiembre es el D√≠a Nacional de Inscripci√≥n Electoral', '¬°Ay√∫denos correr la voz con este articulo para su bolet√≠n informativo para padres!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '',