ool is run - special education, budget and more.\nWe encourage everyone to get informed about this important election and to vote on May 21!\n**May 6 is the deadline to register to vote.** If you aren\'t already registered, we have forms in our school office. You can also easily register to vote online at www.sos.ca.gov or by picking up a form at your county elections office, library, or U.S. Post Office.\nLearn more at [www.ccsafamilies.org/la2013](/la2013).\n', 'TEMPLATE For Your Newsletter:', 'Ay√∫denos a difundir informaci√≥n mediante la inclusi√≥n de nuestras noticias en su bolet√≠n escolar o en su p√°gina web.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'template_for_your_newsletter', '', '', '2013-04-03 15:18:25', '2013-04-03 15:18:25', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/?p=224', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(225, 2, '2013-04-09 09:50:28', '2013-04-09 09:50:28', '<p>You are cordially invited to attend the first in a series of FREE parent engagement workshops, hosted by the California State University, African American Initiative - in partnership with Educate California.\nThese workshops are designed to provide families with the most current and effective tools and resources for preparing students for college, careers and life after high school. Each family will receive materials and information to empower them to advocate for the child(rens) K-12 education.\n- <a href="https://events.r20.constantcontact.com/register/eventReg?llr=gjasvrn6&amp;oeidk=a07e79mwfngc669ad3c&amp;oseq=a02asngll5xgez">Register Now!</a></p>\n\n<h3>Event Details</h3>\n\n<p>Saturday May 25, 2013 from 10:00 AM to 1:00 PM PDT\nREGISTRATION: 9:00 AM\nCalifornia State University, Los Angeles\n5151 State University Drive\nUniversity Student Union Theater\nLos Angeles, CA 90032\nLimited space is available and families will be served on a first-come basis. Please register early and encourage others to do the same.</p>\n', 'May 25: Free LifePrep Academy Workshop for Parents in Los Angeles', 'You are cordially invited to attend the first in a series of FREE parent engagement workshops, hosted by the California State University, African American Initiative - in partnership with Educate California.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'may_25_free_lifeprep_academy_workshop_for_parents_in_los_angeles', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/may_25_free_lifeprep_academy_workshop_for_parents_in_los_angeles/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(226, 2, '2013-04-09 10:01:28', '2013-04-09 10:01:28', '<p>This interactive training session will brief parents on the basics of charter schools and the charter school movement in California.  Parents will also learn and practice sharing their personal story and experience with charter schools. This is a great intro for charter parents to encourage and enhance their advocacy skills. This session will also build their confidence when speaking in the community and media regarding their school and the charter movement.\n- <a href="/FTC_IE_parent_workshop_flyer.pdf">Printable flyer to spread the word at your school</a></p>\n\n<h3>Date</h3>\n\n<p>Wednesday, April 24th, 2013</p>\n\n<h3>Time</h3>\n\n<p>6:00pm to 7:00 p.m.</p>\n\n<h3>Location</h3>\n\n<p>Excel Prep Charter School\n23750 Alessandro Blvd., Moreno Valley CA, 92553\n<a href="mailto:vkoss@calcharters.org">RSVP to Valieria Koss.</a>\n<em>Refreshments Provided</em></p>\n', 'April 24: Free Inland Empire Parent Workshop', 'Parents are invited to a great training including Charter Schools 101 & Sharing Your Story\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'april_24_free_inland_empire_parent_workshop', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/april_24_free_inland_empire_parent_workshop/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(227, 2, '2013-04-29 11:04:55', '2013-04-29 11:04:55', '<p>Did you know that you can vote by mail? In California, you can register to vote by mail for just one election or you can sign up as a Permanent Absentee Voter and always receive your ballot in the mail automatically.\nHere are 4 great reasons to vote by mail:</p>\n\n<h3>1. It\'s easy.</h3>\n\n<p>You can register as a Permanent Absentee Voter just by <a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/vote-by-mail/pdf/fill-in-vote-by-mail-app-instruct.pdf">filling out this simple form</a>.\nLos Angeles County voters should mail the completed form to:\nDean Logan, Registrar - Recorder/County Clerk\nP.O. Box 1024\nNorwalk, CA 90651-1024\nThose in other counties should send them to their respective registrar.</p>\n\n<h3>2. It\'s convenient.</h3>\n\n<p>You don\'t even have to get dressed or figure out where to go to vote. Just fill out your ballot in the comfort of your own home, at the time that is convenient for you.</p>\n\n<h3>3. Never forget an election.</h3>\n\n<p>Your voter guide and ballot will automatically arrive in the mail a couple of weeks before the election.</p>\n\n<h3>4. Life happens!</h3>\n\n<p>Don\'t let it prevent your vote from counting. By voting early, nothing can keep you from the polls - whether an emergency at work or a sick child. Don\'t worry - if you forget to mail your ballot before election day, you can always take it in to your polling place and submit it in person.\nMake sure your vote counts! Vote early! Vote by mail!</p>\n', '4 Great Reasons to Vote By Mail', 'Did you know that you can vote by mail? In California, you can register to vote by mail for just one election or you can sign up as a Permanent Absentee Voter and always receive your ballot in the mail automatically.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '4_reasons_to_vote_by_mail', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/4_reasons_to_vote_by_mail/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(228, 2, '2013-04-29 11:03:52', '2013-04-29 11:03:52', '<p>¬øSab√≠a que se puede votar por correo? En California, se puede registrar para recibir su boleta para la pr√≥xima elecci√≥n por correo o se puede registrarse como Votante Permanente por Correo para recibir sus boletas para todas elecciones por correo autom√°ticamente.</p>\n\n<h3>1. Es f√°cil.</h3>\n\n<p>Se puede registrar como Votante Permanente por Correo <a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/vote-by-mail/pdf/fill-in-vote-by-mail-app-instruct.pdf">llenando esta sencilla forma</a>.\nLos votantes del condado de Los √Ångeles deben enviar por correo la forma debidamente llenada a:\nDean Logan, Registrar - Recorder/County Clerk\nP.O. Box 1024\nNorwalk, CA 90651-1024</p>\n\n<h3>2. Es conveniente.</h3>\n\n<p>Usted no tiene que arreglarse para salir o buscar d√≥nde est√° la casilla para votar. S√≥lo tiene que llenar la boleta en la tranquilidad de su casa a la hora que sea m√°s conveniente para usted.</p>\n\n<h3>3. Nunca olvidar√° una elecci√≥n.</h3>\n\n<p>Su gu√≠a de votante y su boleta electoral llegar√°n autom√°ticamente por correo un par de semanas antes de la elecci√≥n.</p>\n\n<h3>4.¬°En la vida pasan cosas inesperadas!</h3>\n\n<p>No deje que esto le impida que su voto cuente. Al votar de manera temprana, usted puede prevenir que una emergencia en el trabajo o un hijo enfermo le impida ir a las urnas el d√≠a de la votaci√≥n. ¬°Aseg√∫rese de que su voto cuente! ¬°Vote antes! ¬°Vote por correo! No se preocupe, si usted olvida enviar por correo su boleta antes del d√≠a de la elecci√≥n, puede llevarla a la casilla de votaci√≥n y entregarla en persona.</p>\n', '4 Grandes razones para votar por correo', '¬øSab√≠a que se puede votar por correo? En California, se puede registrar para recibir su boleta para la pr√≥xima elecci√≥n por correo o se puede registrarse como Votante Permanente por Correo para recibir sus boletas para todas elecciones por correo autom√°ticamente.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '4_grandes_razones_para_votar_por_correo', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/4_grandes_razones_para_votar_por_correo/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(229, 2, '2013-04-29 16:01:38', '2013-04-29 16:01:38', '<p>In 2007, Jose Morales was just a frustrated parent -- his son\'s school, Desert Trails Elementary, had been failing for years with no change in sight. So he joined with fellow parents at the school and they became the first parents in the state of California to successfully use the new parent trigger law to turn around the school. In fall 2013, the school is opening as a charter school.\nHe shared his advice for other parents at our Parent Summit in March 2013. <a href="http://parentrevolution.org/">Learn more about the parent trigger.</a></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/5zRvJ8DAe-U" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'VIDEO: Parent Trigger - Advice from a Parent Advocate', 'In 2007, Jose Morales was just a frustrated parent -- his son\'s school, Desert Trails Elementary, had been failing for years with no change in sight. So he joined with fellow parents at the school and they became the first parents in the state of California to successfully use the new parent trigger law to turn around the school.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'video_parent_trigger_-_advice_from_a_parent_advocate', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '2016-01-13 04:22:16', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/video_parent_trigger_-_advice_from_a_parent_advocate/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(230, 4, '2013-04-29 23:14:46', '2013-04-29 23:14:46', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="rachel_minnick_sacramento.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/08/rachel_minnick_sacramento-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>Congratulations to Families That Can\'s Rachel Minnick who was recently appointed as a parent representative on the Sacramento City Unified School District\'s Bond Oversight Committee. Parents bring an important perspective and voice when they serve on advisory committees and commissions - learn more!\nBonds are used by local school districts to raise money for major expenditures like upgrading facilities. Facilities are a major challenge for charter schools, which is why it is so important for us to make sure that charter public schools are included in local bonds. One of the recent bonds passed in Sacramento does include charter schools.\n"There are several parents on the bond oversight committee, but I am the only one with a child in a charter school. Serving on the bond committee is an opportunity for me to help the committee understand the unique challenges charter schools face and advocate for the equitable use of these bonds funds so that charter schools receive the facilities upgrades they need to ensure a high quality education for all kids,," said Rachel.\nAs a member of the 11-person oversight committee, Rachel will monitor the use of bond funds and make sure that tax-payer dollars are being spent responsibly, effectively and efficiently. Rachel was appointed to the committee by the Sac City Unified school board.\n"As charter parents, there are lots of ways to raise our voices," said Rachel. "I encourage other parents to consider serving on local advisory boards or committees, because it gives them the chance to meet other community leaders and learn how our government works. When charter parents are part of these local groups, they raise awareness of charter schools and help challenge many of the myths about school choice." Every city, county and school board offers a variety of boards and commissions on topics ranging from mental health to city planning to public safety to disability rights. Check out your city, county or school board website to find out what is available in your community.\nIf you aren\'t sure where to begin, <a href="http://www.cawomenlead.org">California Women Lead</a> provides free trainings with tips and information on how to get appointed to a local board or commission a few times a year. If you can\'t find training near you, check out their <a href="http://www.cawomenlead.org">helpful guide</a>, which takes you step-by-step through the process. Parents just like you are making a difference in their communities. Your voice matters!</p>\n', 'Rachel Minnick Appointed to Sacramento Bond Oversight Committee', 'Congratulations to Families that Can\'s Rachel Minnick who was recently appointed as a parent representative on the Sacramento City Unified School District\'s Bond Oversight Committee.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'rachel_minnick_appointed_to_sacramento_bond_oversight_committee', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/rachel_minnick_appointed_to_sacramento_bond_oversight_committee/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(231, 4, '2013-04-29 23:26:27', '2013-04-29 23:26:27', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="rachel_minnick_sacramento.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/08/rachel_minnick_sacramento-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>Felicitaciones a Rachel Minnick, de Families that Can,  quien recientemente fue nombrada como representante de padres de familia en el Comit√© de Supervisi√≥n de Bonos del Distrito Escolar Unificado de la Ciudad de Sacramento. Los padres ofrecen una importante perspectiva y voz cuando sirven en los comit√©s y comisiones de consejeros. ¬°Aqu√≠ hay m√°s informaci√≥n!\nLos bonos son usados por los distritos escolares locales para recaudar fondos para gastos mayores como la mejora de sus instalaciones. √âstas son un gran desaf√≠o para las escuelas ch√°rter por lo que es muy importante para nosotros asegurarnos de que las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter se incluyan en los bonos locales. Uno de las m√°s recientes bonos que se aprobaron en Sacramento incluy√≥ a las escuelas ch√°rter.\n"Hay varios padres que sirven en el comit√© de supervisi√≥n de bonos, pero yo soy la √∫nica con un hijo en una escuela ch√°rter. El servir en el comit√© de bonos es una oportunidad para ayudar al comit√© a entender los retos √∫nicos que enfrentan las escuelas ch√°rter y para defender el uso equitativo de estos fondos con el  fin de que las escuelas ch√°rter puedan hacer las mejoras que necesitan sus instalaciones y asegurar una alta calidad de educaci√≥n para todos los ni√±os", dijo Rachel.\nComo miembro de los 11 integrantes que supervisan el comit√©, Rachel vigilar√° el uso que se dar√° a los fondos de los bonos y se asegurar√° de que los d√≥lares de los contribuyentes de impuestos sean gastados de manera responsable, efectiva y eficiente. Rachel fue nombrada al comit√© por la Junta Escolar del Distrito Unificado de Sac City.\n"Como padres de escuelas ch√°rter, hay muchas formas de expresar nuestras voces", dijo Rachel. "Yo animo a otros padres  a que consideren servir en las juntas locales o comit√©s de asesores porque eso les da la oportunidad de conocer a otros l√≠deres comunitarios y aprender c√≥mo funciona nuestro gobierno. Cuando los padres de las escuelas ch√°rter son parte de estos grupos locales, ellos despiertan la conciencia sobre las escuelas ch√°rter y ayudan a poner en duda muchos de los mitos acerca de las opciones que hay para elegir una escuela". Todas las ciudades, condados y juntas escolares cuentan con una gran variedad de juntas y comisiones sobre t√≥picos que van desde salud mental y planificaci√≥n de la ciudad hasta derechos para los discapacitados. Verifique en la p√°gina web de su ciudad, condado o junta escolar qu√© es lo que est√° disponible en su comunidad.\nSi usted no est√° segura de d√≥nde puede empezar, la organizaci√≥n <a href="http://www.cawomenlead.org">California Women Lead</a> ofrece varias veces al a√±o entrenamientos gratuitos con consejos e informaci√≥n sobre c√≥mo ser nombrada para una junta local o una comisi√≥n. Si no puede encontrar entrenamiento cerca de usted, consulte la √∫til gu√≠a  que tiene esa organizaci√≥n, la cual le lleva paso a paso a trav√©s del proceso. Los padres como usted hacen una diferencia en sus comunidades. ¬°Su voz cuenta!</p>\n', 'Nombran a Rachel Minnick para ser parte del Comit√© de Supervisi√≥n de Bonos en Sacramento', 'Felicitaciones  a Rachel Minnick, de Families that Can,  quien recientemente fue nombrada como representante de padres de familia en el Comit√© de Supervisi√≥n de Bonos del Distrito Escolar Unificado de la Ciudad de Sacramento.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'nombran_a_rachel_minnick_para_ser_parte_del_comite_de_supervision_de_bonos_en_sacramento', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/nombran_a_rachel_minnick_para_ser_parte_del_comite_de_supervision_de_bonos_en_sacramento/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(232, 4, '2013-04-29 23:31:38', '2013-04-29 23:31:38', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="Inland_empire_parent_training (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2013/04/FTC IE pic 2-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>April 24 was an exciting evening at Excel Prep Charter Academy in San Bernardino as they hosted charter families from across the Inland Empire to participate in the first ever cross-charter Families That Can training in the region.  Alejandro Gomez from Excel gave a great intro to kick off the event and soon parents and grandparents dived right into learning the ins and outs of charter schools and the history of the charter movement.  No question was off limits and these families along with several students in attendance engaged in a thought provoking-discussion.\nThen participants shared their own inspiring stories about how they connected to the charter movement.  The enthusiasm of the parents was electrifying as they realized that they would have the opportunity to have a real impact in an important upcoming election. This November, three seats are up for election on the San Bernardino City Unified School District board.\n"Parents are already their child\'s best advocate the minute they make the decision to enroll them in a charter school," said Fatima Cristerna-Adame, Inland Empire Regional Director for the California Charter Schools Association. "These workshops now help them with the tools to be advocates with elected officials and have a voice in determining who is elected to represent their community. In San Bernardino, a small group of parents played a great role in the last two elections, making a big impact in a small amount of time. Now we need those parents and more parents to be even more active early on in the campaign and election process."\nWe, at Families That Can, look forward to continuing our work with these charter families and others like them as we continue to partner with schools in the Inland Empire!</p>\n', 'Training Brings Together Inland Empire Parents', 'April 24 was an exciting evening at Excel Prep Charter Academy in San Bernardino as they hosted charter families from across the Inland Empire to participate in the first ever cross-charter Families That Can training in the region.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'training_brings_together_inland_empire_parents', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/training_brings_together_inland_empire_parents/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(233, 4, '2013-04-29 23:39:07', '2013-04-29 23:39:07', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="Inland_empire_parent_training (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2013/04/FTC IE pic 2-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>El 24 de abril fue una emocionante tarde en Excel Prep Charter Academy en San Bernardino donde se llev√≥ a cabo una reuni√≥n de familias de escuelas ch√°rter de Inland Empire para participar en el primer entrenamiento de toda la regi√≥n que organiza Families That Can.  Alejandro G√≥mez, de Excel, pronunci√≥ un gran discurso para inaugurar el evento y pronto los padres y abuelos se sumergieron en el aprendizaje de las escuelas ch√°rter y en la historia del movimiento ch√°rter. No hubo l√≠mites en las preguntas y las familias y los estudiantes que asistieron participaron en una interesante discusi√≥n.\nDespu√©s los participantes compartieron sus propias historias acerca de c√≥mo se conectaron con el movimiento ch√°rter. El entusiasmo de los padres fue electrizante cuando se dieron cuenta que tendr√≠an la oportunidad de tener un impacto real en la importante elecci√≥n que se aproxima. Este noviembre est√°n en juego tres asientos en la elecci√≥n de la Junta del Distrito Escolar Unificado de la Ciudad de San Bernardino.\n"Los padres ya son los principales defensores de sus hijos desde el momento que toman la decisi√≥n de inscribirlos en una escuela ch√°rter", dijo  Fatima Cristerna-Adame, directora  regional de Inland Empire para  California Charter Schools Association. "Estos talleres les ayudar√°n ahora con las herramientas que necesitan para ser defensores ante los funcionarios electos y para tener voz para determinar a qui√©nes elegir para representar a su comunidad. En San Bernardino, un peque√±o grupo de padres desempe√±√≥ un gran papel en las √∫ltimas dos elecciones y tuvo un enorme impacto en poco tiempo. Ahora necesitamos a esos padres y a m√°s padres para que est√©n m√°s activos en las primeras etapas de la campa√±a y del proceso de elecci√≥n".\n¬°En Families That Can esperamos seguir nuestro trabajo con estas familias ch√°rter y otras como ellas para continuar como aliados en las escuelas de Inland Empire!</p>\n', 'El entrenamiento une a padres de Inland Empire', 'El 24 de abril fue una emocionante tarde en Excel Prep Charter Academy en San Bernardino donde se llev√≥ a cabo una reuni√≥n de familias de escuelas ch√°rter de Inland Empire para participar en el primer entrenamiento de toda la regi√≥n que organiza Families That Can.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'el_entrenamiento_une_a_padres_de_inland_empire', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/el_entrenamiento_une_a_padres_de_inland_empire/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(234, 4, '2013-05-02 10:47:39', '2013-05-02 10:47:39', '<p>Telling your charter school story will enable you to connect your personal experience with current issues. With this, you can become an effective advocate for high quality education in California.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/jEouCCjhVNI" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'VIDEO: Three steps to tell your charter story for powerful advocacy', 'Telling your charter school story will enable you to connect your personal experience with current issues. With this, you can become an effective advocate for high quality education in California.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'video_three_steps_to_tell_your_charter_story_for_powerful_advocacy', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/video_three_steps_to_tell_your_charter_story_for_powerful_advocacy/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(235, 3, '2013-05-09 14:15:10', '2013-05-09 14:15:10', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="Adv_Day_Reps_Magnolia_Schools.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2013/05/Adv_Day_Reps_Magnolia_Schools-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p><em>Representatives from Magnolia Science Academy met with the staff at Senator Fran Pavley\'s office during Advocacy Day on May 8, 2013.</em>\nMore than 170 parents, charter school leaders and students made their voices heard at CCSA\'s 20th Anniversary Advocacy Day held at the State Capitol in Sacramento on Wednesday, May 8.\nAdvocacy Day provides an opportunity to help legislators become more familiar with charter schools as well as advocate for funding equity, expand facilities access, and to oppose bills which would reduce charter school autonomy and flexibility. Proposed bills that parents and school leaders discussed with elected officials included, CCSA\'s sponsored legislation <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/advocacy/statewide/ab948.html">AB 948</a>, which allows more charter public schools to access state facilities and <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/advocacy/statewide/ab-913-oppose.html">AB 913</a>, which participants urged legislators to reject because it imposes new conflict of interest requirements for charter schools.\n"I was overwhelmed by the representation of parents that traveled from around the state to meet with their legislator and their willingness to take a day out of their busy schedules to come to Sacramento," said\nSenior Vice President, Statewide Advocacy, Allison Bajracharya. "It reinforces to me the transformative impact charter schools are having on our parents and communities."\nAssemblymembers and Assembly Education Committee Chair Joan Buchanan and Education Committee Vice Chair Kristin Olsen opened the day\'s program. "Today, it\'s more important than ever that every child receives a high quality education," said Assemblymember Buchanan. "We need to make a deeper commitment to our children. We need to find that common ground because our children need us. Let\'s figure out a way to join hands for the benefit of our children."\nAssemblymember Kristin Olsen commented, "Charter schools prove the impossible possible...as we work together you are part of the solution. We can turn the state of education around in California."\nCharter leaders and parents met with their local legislators to discuss both the impact of charter schools on student achievement and on public policy proposals that supports the success of charter schools. Some charter leaders also attended the Assembly Education Committee meeting to express their opposition to AB 913.\nMonica Jones, a parent of a 12th grade student at Sacramento Charter High School visited Assemblymember Roger Dickinson\'s office with students from Heritage Peak Charter School said, "We are stakeholders in our children\'s education. I was impressed by the students sharing their touching stories to make sure their voices are also heard." Jones continued, "I really believe in participating in legislative visits and it\'s also important that children also learn to advocate for themselves."\nCalifornia boasts 1,063 schools that serve 484,000 students. Advocacy Day was also held during National Charter Schools Week, May 5-11.</p>\n', 'Celebrating CCSA\'s 20th Anniversary Advocacy Day on May 8', 'Parents, charter school leaders and students made their voices heard at CCSA\'s 20th Anniversary Advocacy Day held at the State Capitol in Sacramento on Wednesday, May 8.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'celebrating_ccsas_20th_anniversary_advocacy_day_on_may_8', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/celebrating_ccsas_20th_anniversary_advocacy_day_on_may_8/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(236, 3, '2013-05-10 09:04:18', '2013-05-10 09:04:18', '<p>M√°s de 170 padres, l√≠deres y estudiantes de las escuelas ch√°rter hicieron o√≠r sus voces durante el 20¬∞ Aniversario del D√≠a de la Promoci√≥n de CCSA en el Capitolio Estatal en Sacramento el mi√©rcoles 8 de mayo.\nEl D√≠a de Promoci√≥n es una oportunidad para ayudar a los legisladores a familiarizarse con las escuelas ch√°rter, apoyar la igualdad de fondos y un mayor acceso a instalaciones, y oponerse a proyectos de ley que reducir√≠an la autonom√≠a y flexibilidad de las escuelas ch√°rter.  Los proyectos de ley sobre los cuales los padres y l√≠deres de las escuelas ch√°rter conversaron con los funcionarios p√∫blicos incluyeron la legislaci√≥n patrocinada por CCSA, <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/advocacy/statewide/ab948.html">AB 948</a>, que les permite a m√°s escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter tener acceso a instalaciones del estado, y <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/advocacy/statewide/ab-913-oppose.html">AB 913</a>, que los participantes instaron a los legisladores a oponerse porque impone nuevos requisitos de conflicto de inter√©s para las escuelas ch√°rter.\n"Estuve abrumada por la representaci√≥n de padres que viajaron desde todo el estado para hablar con su legislador y por la voluntad de sacar un d√≠a de sus obligaciones para venir a Sacramento", dijo la Vicepresidenta de Promoci√≥n Estatal, Allison Bajracharya.  "Me confirma el impacto transformativo que est√°n teniendo las escuelas ch√°rter en nuestros padres y nuestras comunidades".\nLa presidenta del Comisi√≥n de Educaci√≥n de la Asamblea Joan Buchanan, y la vicepresidenta de la Comisi√≥n de Educaci√≥n, Kristin Olsen, iniciaron el programa del d√≠a. "Hoy es m√°s importante que nunca que todos los ni√±os reciban una educaci√≥n de alta calidad", dijo la asamble√≠sta Buchanan. "Debemos comprometernos m√°s con nuestros hijos. Debemos encontrar lo que tenemos en com√∫n porque nuestros hijos nos necesitan. Tratemos de encontrar una forma de unirnos por el bien de nuestros hijos".\nLa asamble√≠sta Kristin Olsen dijo que "las escuelas ch√°rter prueban que lo imposible es posible... mientras trabajemos juntos ustedes son parte de la soluci√≥n.  Podemos cambiar el estado de la educaci√≥n en California"\nLos padres y l√≠deres de las escuelas ch√°rter se reunieron con sus legisladores locales para hablar sobre el impacto de las escuelas ch√°rter en el logro acad√©mico de los estudiantes y sobre propuestas legislativas que apoyen el √©xito de las escuelas ch√°rter. Algunos l√≠deres de las escuelas ch√°rter tambi√©n asistieron a la reuni√≥n de la Comisi√≥n de Educaci√≥n para expresar su oposici√≥n a AB 913.\nMonica Jones, madre un estudiante de 12¬∞ grado en <em>Sacramento Charter High School</em>, visit√≥ la oficina del  asamble√≠sta Roger Dickinson con estudiantes de <em>Heritage Peak Charter School</em> y dijo: "Somos promotores de la educaci√≥n de nuestros hijos. Me gust√≥ ver a los estudiantes compartir sus conmovedoras historias para ser escuchados. Realmente creo en el valor de las visitas legislativas y es importante que los ni√±os tambi√©n aprendan a hacer valer sus derechos", agreg√≥ Jones.\nCalifornia tiene 1,063 escuelas con 484,000 estudiantes. El D√≠a de la Promoci√≥n tambi√©n se celebr√≥ durante la Semana Nacional de Escuelas Ch√°rter, del 5 al 11 de mayo.</p>\n', 'Celebrando el 20¬∞ aniversario del D√≠a de la Promoci√≥n de CCSA el 8 de mayo', 'Padres, l√≠deres y estudiantes de las escuelas ch√°rter hicieron o√≠r sus voces durante el 20¬∞ Aniversario del D√≠a de la Promoci√≥n de CCSA en el Capitolio Estatal en Sacramento el mi√©rcoles 8 de mayo.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'celebrando_el_20_aniversario_del_dia_de_la_promocion_de_ccsa_el_8_de_mayo', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/celebrando_el_20_aniversario_del_dia_de_la_promocion_de_ccsa_el_8_de_mayo/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(237, 4, '2013-05-16 13:17:02', '2013-05-16 13:17:02', '<p>"Shelby is 13 and she\'s in 6th grade, and up until last year, she was never in any grade," says her mom. Thanks to Aspire Alexander Twilight College Preparatory Academy, that\'s no longer the case. Learn how one California charter school is using an innovative approach to special education to benefit all students.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/y8Wnq_ouyWs" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'VIDEO: Shelby\'s Story: "Paving the Way for Other Kids"', '"Shelby is 13 and she\'s in 6th grade, and up until last year, she was never in any grade," says her mom. Thanks to Aspire Alexander Twilight College Preparatory Academy, that\'s no longer the case.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'video_shelbys_story_paving_the_way_for_other_kids_1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/video_shelbys_story_paving_the_way_for_other_kids_1/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(238, 4, '2013-05-16 13:38:29', '2013-05-16 13:38:29', '<p>A team of parents and educators in Redwood City recently came together to create their dream school - Connect Community Charter School -- which was approved in 2013. It\'s not easy, but you can do it, says Kathryn Hopkins, a mom, educator and member of the school\'s founding team, who shares her story.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/cb-_I3mpnTs?list=PLC7F71762C4202382" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'VIDEO: You Really Can Start a Charter School', 'A team of parents and educators in Redwood City recently came together to create their dream school - Connect Community Charter School -- which was approved in 2013. It\'s not easy, but you can do it, says Kathryn Hopkins, a mom, educator and member of the school\'s founding team, who shares her story.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'video_you_really_can_start_a_charter_school', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '2016-01-13 04:22:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/video_you_really_can_start_a_charter_school/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
