(633, 1, '2016-01-08 19:42:34', '2016-01-08 19:42:34', '<h1>Test</h1>\n\n<p><figure class="figure-full figure-border"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BG775rz1HJ4"><img alt="Redwood_City_parents_celebrate_new_charters.png" src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/Redwood%20parents%20celebrate.png" width="491" height="323" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></a></figure> Last month, after two years of working to bring new charter school options to their community, parents celebrated the approval of two new charter schools by the Redwood City School Board. The school board unanimously voted to allow Rocketship Education and KIPP Bay Area Schools to establish new charter schools, which together expect to enroll 1,500 students. It\'s the latest example of parent power fueling the charter school movement. The parents in Redwood City are part of Innovate Public Schools, a school reform organization focused on making sure that low-income students and children of color in the greater Silicon Valley region receive an excellent education that will prepare them for success in life. Learn more at &#91;www.innovateschools.org&#93;(http://www.innovateschools.org). &#91;Watch this touching video of parents realizing that their hard work has finally paid off&#93;(https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BG775rz1HJ4).</p>\n', 'Parents Celebrate Two New Charters', 'A two-year journey brings great schools to Redwood City.\r\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '297-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-08 19:42:34', '2016-01-08 19:42:34', '', 297, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/297-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(634, 1, '2016-01-08 19:42:59', '2016-01-08 19:42:59', '<p><figure class="figure-full figure-border"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BG775rz1HJ4"><img alt="Redwood_City_parents_celebrate_new_charters.png" src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/Redwood%20parents%20celebrate.png" width="491" height="323" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></a></figure> Last month, after two years of working to bring new charter school options to their community, parents celebrated the approval of two new charter schools by the Redwood City School Board. The school board unanimously voted to allow Rocketship Education and KIPP Bay Area Schools to establish new charter schools, which together expect to enroll 1,500 students. It\'s the latest example of parent power fueling the charter school movement. The parents in Redwood City are part of Innovate Public Schools, a school reform organization focused on making sure that low-income students and children of color in the greater Silicon Valley region receive an excellent education that will prepare them for success in life. Learn more at &#91;www.innovateschools.org&#93;(http://www.innovateschools.org). &#91;Watch this touching video of parents realizing that their hard work has finally paid off&#93;(https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BG775rz1HJ4).</p>\n', 'Parents Celebrate Two New Charters', 'A two-year journey brings great schools to Redwood City.\r\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '297-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-08 19:42:59', '2016-01-08 19:42:59', '', 297, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/297-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(635, 3, '2016-01-08 23:14:56', '2016-01-08 23:14:56', '<p><em>"My daughter went to college... but only because she went to a charter school first."</em>\n- Karen Robinson, Charter School Mom</p>\n\n<div class="figure embedded-image right"><a rel="lightbox" href="/assets_c/2012/03/robinson_family-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___home_slideshow-thumb-612xauto-2586.jpg" title="robinson_family.jpg (Homepage Slideshow)"><img alt="robinson_family.jpg (Homepage Slideshow)" src="/assets_c/2012/03/robinson_family-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___home_slideshow-thumb-241x129-2586.jpg" width="241" height="129" class="mt-image-right" /></a></div>\n\n<p>Up until 8th grade, Christina Robinson was one of those students who did just enough to get by at school.  It wasn\'t her fault; the school bureaucracy just couldn\'t give kids the individual attention they needed.\nThen Christina\'s mom heard about a new charter school.  She went to their open house, and decided it was the right place for Christina.  What a difference!  The school challenged and inspired Christina, and soon she made the honor roll.  Now Christina\'s about to graduate from college, and she wants to become a teacher at a charter school, so she can help other kids succeed as well.</p>\n', 'Karen Robinson, Animo Inglewood in Los Angeles', 'Karen Robinson shares why she chose to enroll her daughter in a charter school and what a difference it has made for her family.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-08 23:14:56', '2016-01-08 23:14:56', '', 16, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/16-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(636, 3, '2016-01-08 23:15:23', '2016-01-08 23:15:23', '<p>Get to know some of our amazing charter schools here in Los Angeles! ###Renaissance Arts Academy ###Our Community ###The Watts Learning Center ###Synergy Charter Academy \n<strong><a href="http://app.ccsa.org/apps/mapapp/map.aspx?Zip=&Distance=10&County=" target="_blank">Click here for a map of all of the charter schools in Los Angeles.</a></strong></p>\n', 'Get to know LA\'s charter schools', 'There are many unique and wonderful charter schools serving diverse communities throughout Los Angeles. Some focus on science or engineering, others offer a focus on the arts or a bilingual program. Find out more about some of the public school options for parents in Los Angeles with these videos.\r\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '11-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-08 23:15:23', '2016-01-08 23:15:23', '', 11, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/11-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(637, 3, '2016-01-08 23:15:29', '2016-01-08 23:15:29', '<div class="figure embedded-image right">\n  <a rel="lightbox" href="/assets_c/2012/03/ainye_long-thumb-612xauto-2433.jpg" title="ainye_long.jpg"><img alt="ainye_long.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/03/ainye_long-thumb-150x225-2433.jpg" width="150" height="225" class="mt-image-right" /></a>\n</div>\n\n<p><em>Ainye Long is a Parent and Community Engagement Director for Families That Can.</em> A 3rd generation native of the Bay Area, this is home for me. Attending Berkeley High School, said to be one of the most diverse high schools in the country at the time, I saw and lived the achievement gap first-hand. The school was really a microcosm of what\'s going on in education across the state and the country. I got involved in the community early on. My mother co-founded Parents of Children of African Descent (PCAD). PCAD was created by Berkeley High parents who fought for educational equity for their students by highlighting the inequities their children were experiencing to other parents, administrators, and the school board. I carried that spark for education and community involvement with me when I enrolled at UC Santa Cruz, where I had the opportunity to network with students of color across the state (and country) and volunteered my time to mentor local high school students. I majored in Economics and American Studies and was on track to a "safe job" as an accountant, but I knew my true passion was education, so I became a teacher. My first job following undergrad was teaching middle school at an Oakland charter school. This was hard work, but the school was nominated as a California Distinguished School and received the National Blue Ribbon Award during my tenure. The average school with our demographics didn\'t do nearly as well. The positive results yielded in my first years in this position showed me what is possible, what can work. I\'m passionate about youth. I\'m equally passionate about education and feel a responsibility to reach back to my community. I am so excited to bring Families That Can to Oakland - this is exactly what I want to be doing - engaging parents and community members in our children\'s educational process. There are so many amazing things going on in education in Oakland, but too many people are missing out; not everyone has had a seat at the table. If we change the conversations around what is going on in public education and change who is a part of those conversations, we can see real change here in Oakland.</p>\n', 'Meet Ainye Long', 'Meet Ainye Long, a Parent and Community Engagement Director for Families That Can, working with charter school parents in Oakland and the Bay Area.\r\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '12-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-08 23:15:29', '2016-01-08 23:15:29', '', 12, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/12-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(638, 3, '2016-01-08 23:15:50', '2016-01-08 23:15:50', '<p>La promesa Americana de oportunidades para toda persona depende de la calidad de nuestras escuelas p√∫blicas. Desafortunadamente, la burocracia abunda en muchas de nuestras escuelas convencionales a tal grado que no pueden sostener las necesidades de una poblaci√≥n cambiante. Necesitamos algo mejor. Las escuelas ch√°rter son escuelas p√∫blicas que permiten a padres de familia, organizaciones, y grupos comunitarios restaurar, reinventar, y revitalizar nuestro sistema de educaci√≥n p√∫blica. - Las escuelas ch√°rter son estructuradas para adaptarse a las necesidades individuales de cada comunidad, en vez de seguir un patr√≥n burocr√°tico. - Siendo escuelas p√∫blicas, las escuelas ch√°rter est√°n comprometidas a que todo ni√±o reciba una educaci√≥n de alta-calidad, incluyendo aquellos con necesidades especiales o aprendices del Ingl√©s. - A comparaci√≥n de otras escuelas p√∫blicas, los maestros de las escuelas ch√°rter gozan de m√°s flexibilidad dentro de sus aulas, lo cual les permite dar atenci√≥n individual a todo estudiante, y fomentar la participaci√≥n de padres de familia. - Siendo escuelas p√∫blicas, las escuelas ch√°rter son gratuitas. - Las escuelas ch√°rter invierten m√°s financiamiento en las aulas escolares a comparaci√≥n de otras escuelas, y tienen que rendir cuentas a padres de familia y contribuyentes. - Al igual que otras escuelas p√∫blicas, las escuelas ch√°rter contratan √∫nicamente a maestros certificados para las materias principales. Varios estudios demuestran que los estudiantes de las escuelas ch√°rter tienen un mejor rendimiento acad√©mico que estudiantes de escuelas p√∫blicas convencionales. Un 64% de las escuelas ch√°rter de California cumplieron con sus metas acad√©micas para estudiantes en los ex√°menes estatales del a√±o escolar 2008-09, comparado con un 58% de las escuelas tradicionales. En 1992, California se convirti√≥ en el segundo estado en la naci√≥n en adoptar una ley promulgando las escuelas ch√°rter. Desde entonces, la matriculaci√≥n y el rendimiento acad√©mico de las ch√°rters han crecido de manera constante. En el 2009, el n√∫mero de estudiantes en las escuelas ch√°rter creci√≥ en un 20%, y todo indica que esa tendencia continuar√°. Para el 2017-18, se espera que m√°s de un mill√≥n de estudiantes asistir√°n a escuelas ch√°rter a trav√©s de California, y por consiguiente, recibir√°n una educaci√≥n innovadora y avanzada. ##Datos Resumidos Existen m√°s de 5,000 escuelas ch√°rter en la naci√≥n, con m√°s de 1.5 millones de estudiantes matriculados. En California, hay m√°s de 800 escuelas ch√°rter. <strong>Cuerpo Estudiantil de las Escuelas Ch√°rter de California:</strong> Hispanos/Latinos - 41% Anglos - 35% Afro-Americanos - 12% Asi√°ticos - 4% Otras Etnias - 8% Estudiantes con necesidades especiales - 7% Aprendices del Ingl√©s - 18%</p>\n', 'Las Escuelas Ch√°rter: Una Opci√≥n Para Su Hijo', '¬øQue es una escuela ch√°rter? Las escuelas ch√°rter son escuelas p√∫blicas gratuitas que ofrecen otra opci√≥n de educaci√≥n p√∫blica para los padres y los estudiantes.\r\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '13-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-08 23:15:50', '2016-01-08 23:15:50', '', 13, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/13-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(639, 3, '2016-01-08 23:15:57', '2016-01-08 23:15:57', '<p>The American promise of opportunity for all depends on the quality of our public schools. Unfortunately, too many traditional public schools are mired in bureaucracy and unable to meet the needs of an increasingly diverse population. We need to do better. Charter schools are public schools that allow parents, organizations, or community groups to restore, reinvent, and re-energize our public school system. Charter schools are designed and tailored to each local community, rather than by a central bureaucracy. As public schools, charter schools are committed to providing a quality education to all our kids, including those with special needs and English language learners. - Compared with other public schools, charter schools give teachers more freedom to provide individual attention for their children, and encourage parents to be more involved. - Since they are public schools, charter schools charge no tuition. - Charter schools are more accountable to parents and taxpayers. - Charter schools hire only credentialed teachers, just like traditional schools, for core subjects. Studies show that charter school students make greater academic progress than students in traditional public schools. Sixty-four (64) percent of California\'s charter schools met student achievement targets on state tests in the 2008-09 school year, compared to just 58% of non-charter schools. In 1992, California became the second state in the country to enact charter school legislation. Since then, enrollment and performance have steadily grown. In 2009 alone, the number of students in charters schools grew by 20% and that trend is expected to continue. In fall of 2010, 115 new charter schools opened their doors, the largest single-year increase in the nation. By 2017-18, more than one million students are expected to attend California charter schools, giving hundreds of thousands more students the opportunity to learn in an innovative, cutting-edge environment. ###Quick Facts There are more than 5,000 charter schools in the United States, serving more than 1.5 million students. In California, there are 913 charter schools, with 115 new charters opening their doors this fall. ###California\'s Charter School Student population: - Hispanic/Latino -- 41% - White -- 35% - African American -- 12% - Asian -- 4% - Other Ethnicities -- 8% - Special Education Students -- 7% - English Language Learner Students -- 18% <em>(Figures from 2009)</em></p>\n', 'Charter Schools: Public School Reinvented', 'What is a charter school? Charter schools are innovative schools of choice that allow parents and community groups to create schools in their neighborhoods that tailor to the needs of students in that community, providing individualized instruction.\r\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '64-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-08 23:15:57', '2016-01-08 23:15:57', '', 64, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/64-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(640, 3, '2016-01-08 23:16:10', '2016-01-08 23:16:10', '<h3>Charter schools. The best way to reinvent LAUSD. In January 2012, the L.A. School Board will decide who will run 13 new or existing schools. Instead of automatically handing the schools to the same old broken bureaucratic system, the district is considering whether to allow charter schools or other organizations to run the schools. The process is called Public School Choice. This is our chance to help improve the quality of our children\'s education, by telling the School Board we want them to choose charters, because charter schools do a better job of teaching kids than other public schools. As public schools, charter schools are committed to providing a quality education to all our kids, including those with special needs and English language learners. Charter schools never charge tuition.</h3>\n\n<div class="video-container">\n  <iframe title="YouTube video player" width="640" height="390" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/HgDClkztZJw" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div>\n\n<p>###What can I do? You have the ability to help make sure the School Board chooses charters. Here\'s what you can do: - <strong>Write to the School Board</strong>, telling them that you want them to vote for charter schools in Public School Choice this March. Los Angeles Unified School District Board of Education 333 South Beaudry Avenue, 24th Floor Los Angeles, CA 90017 - <strong>Call the School Board</strong>, and tell them that you want them to approve more charter schools. Call them at (213) 241-6389. - &#91;<strong>Join us in supporting charter schools</strong>&#93;(/join.html). We\'ll send you information and keep you up-to date on what you what you can do to help. ###Find out more - &#91;Learn about Public School Choice and see the affected schools in your neighborhood.&#93;(/2011/02/a-parents-guide-to-public-school-choice.html) - &#91;Why are charter schools so great?&#93;(/2010/12/charter-schools-public-school-reinvented.html) - &#91;Get to know LA\'s Charter Schools&#93;(/2010/12/get-to-know-las-charter-schools.html) - Hear from parents whose kids go to charter schools (&#91;English &#93;(/2010/12/why-i-chose-a-charter-school-for-my-daughter.html)/ &#91;Spanish&#93;(/2010/12/porque-elije-una-escuela-charter-para-mi-hija.html)) - &#91;What is Families That Can?&#93;(/) - &#91;<strong>Yes, I\'d like to be kept up-to-date on what I can do to help charter schools.</strong>&#93;(/join.html) -</p>\n', 'LAUSD Public School Choice', 'In January 2012, the L.A. School Board voted on who will run 13 new or existing schools.  Instead of automatically handing the schools to the same old broken bureaucratic system, the district allowed charter schools or other non-profit organizations to run the schools through a process is called Public School Choice.\r\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '14-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-08 23:16:10', '2016-01-08 23:16:10', '', 14, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/14-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(641, 3, '2016-01-08 23:16:16', '2016-01-08 23:16:16', '<p><em>"La escuela ch√°rter a la que asiste Armida est√° a s√≥lo una cuadra de su escuela anterior. Pero es un mundo aparte."</em> - Ra√∫l Barrera (padre de Armida, estudiante en Synergy Charter Academy) <img alt="armida_family.jpg" src="/armida_family.jpg" width="250" height="412" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0 0 20px 20px;" /> A todo padre le preocupa cuando su hijo no recibe atenci√≥n personalizada en sus clases. Eso es exactamente lo que Armida Barrera estaba viviendo en su escuela p√∫blica tradicional. Cuando una nueva escuela ch√°rter abri√≥ en su comunidad, sus padres decidieron visitarla. Ah√≠ descubrieron que las escuelas ch√°rter son escuelas p√∫blicas gratuitas donde los ni√±os reciben m√°s atenci√≥n individual, y los padres pueden participar directamente en la educaci√≥n de sus hijos. Armida ahora es una estudiante sobresaliente en el 8¬∫ grado. A ella le encanta su escuela ch√°rter. A sus padres tambi√©n. Al punto de que cuando su hijo menor, Daniel, cumpli√≥ la edad para entrar al k√≠nder, lo inscribieron inmediatamente en una escuela ch√°rter. Las escuelas ch√°rter ofrecen una mejor opci√≥n educativa en Los √Ångeles. Y es exactamente por esta raz√≥n que en enero, la familia Barrera emitir√° su voto para decirles a los miembros de la Junta Directiva Escolar que necesitamos m√°s escuelas ch√°rter. &#91;Inf√≥rmese sobre la Iniciativa de Opci√≥n de Escuela P√∫blica y como se puede involucrarse.&#93;(/2010/12/lausd-public-school-choice.html)</p>\n', 'La Familia Barrera: Porque eleg√≠ una escuela ch√°rter para mi hija', 'La familia Barrera comparte su historia de buscar las mejores opciones educativas para su hija y porque eligieron una escuela ch√°rter\r\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '15-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-08 23:16:16', '2016-01-08 23:16:16', '', 15, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/15-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
