(776, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '<p><a href="/cn_parent_before_lausd.jpg"><img alt="cn_parent_before_lausd.jpg" src="/assets_c/2011/03/cn_parent_before_lausd-thumb-271x364-1396.jpg" width="271" height="364" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0 0 20px 20px;" /></a>\nAbout 4,750 students in Los Angeles will be attending high-quality charter schools this fall, thanks to a massive effort from charter school families and the bold actions of the Los Angeles Unified School District Board to put kids first in the second round of <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/advocacy/public-school-choice-in-los-angeles.html">Public School Choice</a>.\nMembers of Families That Can camped out all night leading up to the board meeting on March 15 to make sure that charter school parents would have an opportunity to address the board and to get a seat in the meeting.\n<a href="http://www.facebook.com/album.php?id=102530249813103&amp;aid=30338">See our photo album on Facebook.</a>\nPublic School Choice is a unique reform initiative that LAUSD passed in 2009 that allows non-district school operators - like charter schools, teacher teams, and other organizations - the opportunity to run new and low-performing schools.\nMany of Los Angeles\' highest-performing charter public schools applied to operate schools through the second round of the initiative, which included 10 new schools and three low-performing schools.\nCharter school parents came out in force to tell the board: "Put our kids first - vote for charter schools!" Charter parents worked hard over several months leading up to the vote - sharing their personal stories with district parents, raising awareness in the community about what charter schools can offer and working to engage parents and the community to support charter school applicants. <a href="/2011/03/families-that-can-delivers-5300-parent-letters-to-the-lausd-school-board.html">On March 8, Families That Can delivered 5,300 letters to the LAUSD board, asking them to support charter schools.</a>\nThe LAUSD board heard us! They approved seven new charter schools to open this fall, serving almost 5,000 students throughout Los Angeles. Six charter applicants had successful applications: Alliance College-Ready Public Schools, Aspire Public Schools, Camino Nuevo, Green Dot, Partnerships to Uplift Communities (PUC), and Synergy which was awarded parts of both a middle school and a high school in South LA.\nWe were especially excited about the board\'s decisive action to turn around Clay Middle School in south LA by turning it over to Green Dot charter schools. At 538, Clay has the lowest state API score of any middle school in LAUSD, and just 18 percent of its students are proficient in English-language Arts and 10 percent in math.\nChan McCreary, a Clay alum who has had several of her children go through the school and has children attending Green Dot high schools, asked the board to support Green Dot.\n""I grew up in the community and I want to see a change for our area. I want to see Henry Clay become a better school," said McCreary. "Let\'s turn it over, let\'s do something, let\'s remodel education for Henry Clay because we have some young scholars out there. I want Henry Clay to be turned around."\nNot 100% of charter applications were approved, as there were strong applications submitted by Green Dot Public Schools for Central Region Middle School #7, Partnerships to Uplift Communities for Valley Region High School #5, and Granada Charter High School for Valley Region High School #4 that were not approved by the School Board.\nThe third round of PSC has already kicked off, with 42 schools, 16 of them new and the majority focus schools. Families That Can will be working hard again this year to make sure parent voices are heard and the LAUSD board puts kids first!</p>\n\n<h1>Summary of results</h1>\n\n<p><strong>Northeast Los Angeles</strong>\n<em>Central Region High School #13 (2050 San Fernando Rd., Los Angeles, CA 90065)</em>\nThe high school will be comprised of five academies - one of which will be run by Alliance College Ready Public Schools and one which will be run by Partnership to Uplift Communities (PUC) Schools, with the three additional academies run by district/teacher teams.\n<em>Central Region Elementary School #14 (1018 Mohawk Street, Los Angeles, CA 90026)</em>\nEntire campus was awarded to Camino Nuevo Charter Academy.\n<strong>South Los Angeles</strong>\n<em>South Region Elementary School #6 (8919 Main Street, Los Angeles, CA)</em>\nEntire campus was awarded to Aspire Public Schools\n<em>Clay Middle School (12226 S. Western Avenue, Los Angeles, CA 90047)</em>\nEntire campus was awarded to Green Dot Public Schools\n<em>Central Region Middle School #7 (1420 E. Adams Blvd., Los Angeles, CA 90011)</em>\nSynergy Academies was awarded one of the three academies at the school. It applied for just one, applying in collaboration with two teacher teams, all parties proposing to work together collaboratively.\n<em>Central Region High School #16 (300 E. 53rd Street, Los Angeles, CA 90011)</em>\nSynergy Academies was awarded one of the three academies at the school. It applied for just one, applying in collaboration with two teacher teams, all parties proposing to work together collaboratively.</p>\n', 'LAUSD Approves New Charters Under Public School Choice Reform', 'About 4,750 students in Los Angeles will be attending high-quality charter schools this fall, thanks to a massive effort from charter school families and the bold actions of the Los Angeles Unified School District Board.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '21-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '', 21, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/21-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(777, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '<p><img alt="capitol.jpg" src="/capitol.jpg" width="250" height="172" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0 0 20px 20px;" />\nOn May 4, Families That Can and the California Charter Schools Association (CCSA) will celebrate National Charter Schools Week with our annual Advocacy Day in Sacramento.  Please join us on Wednesday, May 4, 2011!\nEvery year, charter school leaders, parents and supporters head to the Capitol for a day of meetings with your local Legislators on the issues facing charter schools. You bring your stories, information on your school and student artwork; CCSA will provide information on the critical legislation affecting charter schools, and tools to have an effective meeting.  There will also be time to network with parents from other schools, and tour the Capitol if you haven\'t been before.\nIt\'s more important than ever to present a unified voice to our state elected officials, and the more charter school supporters they see in the halls of the Capitol on Advocacy Day, the more powerful our message will be. Make your voice heard!\nSigning up is easy - just <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/advocacy/statewide/advocacyday">click here</a> and fill out the form. CCSA\'s Government Affairs team will give you a schedule and all the information you need to have a great day in the Capitol. If you have additional questions on Advocacy Day, email <a href="mailto:thoffman@calcharters.org">Tanya Hoffman</a>.</p>\n', 'May 4 is Charter School Advocacy Day', 'On May 4, Families That Can and the California Charter Schools Association (CCSA) will celebrate National Charter Schools Week with our annual Advocacy Day in Sacramento.  Please join us on Wednesday, May 4, 2011!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '20-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '', 20, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/20-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(778, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '<p>Dozens of parents went to the Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) board meeting on Tuesday to deliver 5,300 letters from public school parents across the city, asking the board to support charter school applicants when they vote on the second round of the Public School Choice initiative.</p>\n\n<div class="pkg embedded-image none" style="width: 400px"><a rel="lightbox" href="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/assets_c/2011/03/LAUSD Board Letter Delivery 3-1-11 009-thumb-640xauto-1332.jpg" title="LAUSD Board Letter Delivery 3-1-11 009.JPG"><img alt="LAUSD Board Letter Delivery 3-1-11 009.JPG" src="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/LAUSD%20Board%20Letter%20Delivery%203-1-11%20009.JPG" width="400" height="300" class="mt-image-none" /></a></div>\n\n<p>Public School Choice is a historic reform initiative passed by LAUSD in August 2009, that allows other school operators - like charter schools, teacher teams, and community groups- the opportunity to apply to run both new schools and existing schools that are chronically underperforming.  Four out of the 13 charter applicants were selected in the first round last year and their schools are now serving an estimated 2,000 students.\nThis second round includes 10 new schools and three existing schools, with the Board set to make a final decision on March 15, 2011.\n"It\'s very simple - these parents want the best for their children and ask the members of the LAUSD board to pick the applicants with the strongest track record and the best ability to implement an ambitious plan to boost student achievement," said Antwaune Goode, Executive Director of Families That Can, during Tuesday\'s board meeting.\nThree LAUSD parents- Chan McCreary, Eugenia Henriquez and Claudia Clemens - shared their own stories and perspectives and asked the board to support charter school applicants.\nThis round of Public School Choice included Clay Middle School, which has had low test scores over many years. Chan McCreary, a parent of eight who herself graduated from Henry Clay Middle School, has had several of her children go through the school. Her oldest are currently attending a Green Dot charter high school and her three youngest attend an LAUSD elementary school that feeds into Clay.\n"I grew up in the community and I want to see a change for our area. I want to see Henry Clay become a better school," McCreary told the board, asking them to support Green Dot\'s application to run the school.  "Let\'s turn it over, let\'s do something, let\'s remodel education for Henry Clay because we have some young scholars out there. I want Henry Clay to be turned around."\nEugenia Henriquez is a parent who lives near Central Region Elementary School #14, a new K-8 that will open in Echo Park this fall. Two of her children currently attend an LAUSD pilot school.\n"We need more middle and high schools that have strong academic results, that really involve the parents in their children\'s education," said Henriquez. "Please support Camino Nuevo to be the school operator - I\'ve heard great things, that 97% of students graduate and that they prepare them for the university. I want the best for my kids."\nClaudia Clemens, a parent from the Eagle Rock area, has two children, one in an LAUSD middle school and the other in a charter high school run by Alliance College-Ready Public Schools.\n"Alliance has proven themselves to be an academically high-scoring school. Our children deserve an award-winning school. We don\'t want to limit the success of our kids," said Clemens. "I\'m here as a concerned parent, not just for my kids, but for all the children in our neighborhood.  Please elect Alliance - it really would make a huge difference for our community."\nSeven high-performing charter schools have applied to operate eight different school sites as part of Round Two of the Public School Choice initiative. The charter applicants are: Aspire Public Schools, Alliance College-Ready Public Schools, Camino Nuevo, Granada Hills Charter High School, Green Dot, Partnerships to Uplift Communities and Synergy Charter.\nClick <a href="/2010/12/lausd-public-school-choice">here </a>to find out more about Public School Choice.</p>\n', 'FTC delivers 5,300 parent letters to the LAUSD school board', 'Parents delivered 5,300 letters from Los Angeles parents in support of charter schools for the Public School Choice initiative to the Los Angeles Unified School District board in March 2011\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '19-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '', 19, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/19-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(779, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '<p>I was born in Peru. My family moved to the US when I was 5. My parents immigrated here with one goal in mind - for my sister and I to have a better education and better opportunities. I\'ve lived in Downey for almost my entire life and I\'ve always attended public schools, up through completing my B.A. in marketing at California State University, Los Angeles in 2008.\nI\'ve always enjoyed helping other people. When I graduated from high school, I heard a local non-profit called Crystal Stairs needed a hand over the holidays. I went on to work there for the next eight years, as an outreach and enrollment specialist, bilingual resource and referral specialist and a case manager. I connected people with state and federal programs that could help them with their most critical needs like childcare services and healthcare.\nIt was a bitter sweet journey. I had the opportunity to interact one on one with parents, which was very rewarding. At the same time, I saw first-hand the challenges people were facing and how critical these social programs were for families, especially when someone loses a job. With the state crisis, a lot of those programs were getting shut down. We focused on providing childcare services, but families came to us with a wide variety of needs. It took a lot of cooperation and trust between me and the community.</p>\n\n<div class="figure embedded-image left"><a rel="lightbox" href="/assets_c/2012/03/fiorella_del_carpio-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___home_featured_primary-thumb-223x165-2526.jpg" title="fiorella_del_carpio.jpg (Homepage Featured Primary)"><img alt="fiorella_del_carpio.jpg (Homepage Featured Primary)" src="/assets_c/2012/03/fiorella_del_carpio-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___home_featured_primary-thumb-223x165-2526.jpg" width="223" height="165" class="mt-image-left" /></a></div>\n\n<p>The first time I ever heard of a charter school was several years ago when a co-worker told me she was taking her children to a charter school over in Culver City, far from where she was living in South Gate. I was curious and went online to find out more. Charter schools remind me of what my elementary school was like - small classes, a lot of support from the teachers and a lot of parental involvement.\nMy mom was always really involved in my school and kept on me about school and my grades. She would wake me up early to do my homework. I see the opportunities that I was given as a child, with my parents leaving behind everything in Peru. I can relate to people - that they migrate here for their children to have a better opportunity. As an adult, I\'m able to appreciate it. If it wasn\'t for my parents, with all their support, I wouldn\'t be where I am today. They taught me that if you are determined, you can do anything.</p>\n', 'Meet Fiorella Del Carpio', 'Meet Fiorella Del Carpio, a Parent and Community Engagement Director for Families That Can, based out of Los Angeles. She shares her personal experiences and why she is committed to working with charter school parents to improve public school options.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '18-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '', 18, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/18-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(780, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '<div class="figure embedded-image right"><a rel="lightbox" href="/assets_c/2012/03/kw_tulloss-thumb-170x258-2654.jpg" title="kw_tulloss.jpg"><img alt="kw_tulloss.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/03/kw_tulloss-thumb-170x258-2654.jpg" width="170" height="258" class="mt-image-right" /></a></div>\n\n<p><em>Rev.  K.W. Tulloss is a Parent and Community Engagement Director for Families That Can based out of Los Angeles and the Pastor of the Weller Street Missionary Baptist Church in Boyle Heights.</em>\nFor the past five years, I\'ve been a strong and vocal supporter of the growing charter school movement in Los Angeles. Many people have questioned me saying, "How is it that one of the most visible young Pastors/Civil rights leaders in Los Angeles is in support of one of this city\'s most controversial movements? Why isn\'t he afraid to speak out when it comes to reforming our school system?" Well, the answer to all those questions and critics is simply this - my children call me "Daddy" not "Reverend."\nAs of today, I have been preaching for the last 13 years. In those years, I have officiated a total of 58 funerals for children under the age of 18. Many of these children had the same profile- they were young, African-American, and had dropped out of school.   How does one eulogize a child who has never reached his potential or attained his dreams? What can you say to the parents?\nI have been blessed with two children of my own, ages 9 and 4, and I also pastor many children in Los Angeles. I love them all as they are my own. Five years ago, I had an epiphany and decided that I was tired of going to funerals; I wanted to go to more graduations.\nI\'ve been an active parent at the Watt\'s Learning Center, the charter school that my 9-year old daughter attends. I\'ve spoken with parents and teachers about this burning issue, seeking the remedies needed to improve our schools. I have even gone to Sacramento to hold our elected representatives accountable and to support the Charter School Movement that has helped educate thousands, including my daughter. A movement that strives to help all children become college-prepared and career-ready.  A movement that emphasizes holding parents and teachers and leaders accountable for our children\'s educational success.\nSo when you see me speaking at rallies, before lawmakers and the people of my community about the importance of a decent education and marching in the streets, just understand that I do this because my children call me "Daddy" and not "Reverend."\nThrough my work at Families That Can, I hope to educate and empower all parents to be Charter Champions so that someday, we will see all children grow up to realize their potential and live their dreams.</p>\n', 'Meet KW Tulloss', 'Reverend KW Tulloss shares about the experiences that led him to get involved in education reform and why he is committed to working with charter school parents for change\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '2016-01-13 04:14:46', '', 17, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(781, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:16', '2016-01-13 04:18:16', '<p>Dr. David Patterson, Superintendent/Executive Director of Rocklin Academies, answers questions from students about the importance for charter schools of grassroots advocacy.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/wviBtAxB-7Y" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Video: The Importance of Grassroots Advocacy', 'Dr. David Patterson, Superintendent/Executive Director of Rocklin Academies, answers questions from students about the importance for charter schools of grassroots advocacy.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '75-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:16', '2016-01-13 04:18:16', '', 75, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/75-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(782, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '<h3>Prepar√°ndose para la reuni√≥n</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Para planificar la junta con su legislador, llame a Families That Can al (213)244- 1446 ext. 255. El equipo de FTC le ayudar√° a trav√©s de todo el proceso y le asistir√° para programar la junta, si es necesario.</li>\n<li>Ent√©rese de los problemas actuales que enfrentan las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter y de los asuntos espec√≠ficos de su escuela. CCSA le ayudar√° a investigar acerca de las leyes y le ofrecer√° una agenda con los puntos que debe discutir durante la reuni√≥n.</li>\n<li>Conozca a su audiencia. Investigue a su funcionario electo. Por ejemplo, ¬øha recibido premios recientemente? ¬øQu√© asuntos enfrenta su distrito?</li>\n<li>Tenga en mente un objetivo espec√≠fico y enf√≥quese en √©l. ¬øQu√© quiere que su representante haga? Si un grupo asistir√° a la reuni√≥n, aclare qui√©n conducir√° la conversaci√≥n. Families That Can y CCSA le ayudar√°n a bosquejar una agenda para la reuni√≥n.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Qu√© hacer y qu√© no hacer en las reuniones legislativas</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Empiece por presentarse a usted mismo y agradezca a la persona por su tiempo. Despu√©s explique por qu√© est√° usted ah√≠ y qu√© es lo que quiere que el funcionario haga (por ejemplo, patrocinar una medida, enviar una carta, votar por m√°s fondos). Sea claro, conciso y expl√≠cito.</li>\n<li>Siga la agenda. Para asegurarse de que todos sus puntos clave se traten durante el tiempo limitado que usted tiene, es sumamente importante que todos los participantes en la reuni√≥n se enfoquen en "el mensaje".</li>\n<li>Presente sus puntos de manera tan personal como le sea posible para que el funcionario o empleado de √©ste entienda el impacto que tendr√° una posici√≥n en particular para su programa y para la gente que usted sirve. Pero aseg√∫rese de balancear los elementos personales con los hechos. Si usted invita a estudiantes a la reuni√≥n, aseg√∫rese de llevar consigo trabajos art√≠sticos estudiantiles que pueda dejarle al funcionario  como un recordatorio de la reuni√≥n.</li>\n<li>Sea respetuoso del tiempo de la persona; tenga en cuenta que los  funcionarios y empleados gubernamentales siempre tienen calendarios muy apretados durante la sesi√≥n legislativa.</li>\n<li>Trate de llevar siempre informaci√≥n escrita a la reuni√≥n para dej√°rsela al funcionario o empleado.</li>\n<li>P√≠dale al funcionario que se comprometa. Si no hay un compromiso, d√≠gale el funcionario o al empleado que har√° un seguimiento en el futuro cercano para saber cu√°l es su posici√≥n; aseg√∫rese de hacer ese seguimiento.</li>\n<li>Responda honestamente si no sabe la respuesta a una pregunta y comprom√©tase a obtener la respuesta en los siguientes d√≠as.</li>\n<li>Haga un seguimiento por tel√©fono o carta conforme el asunto o legislaci√≥n contin√∫e en proceso. Siempre finalice la reuni√≥n con un agradecimiento, si no es por el apoyo, por el tiempo dedicado a encontrarse con usted y escuchar sus puntos de vista.</li>\n<li>Reporte a Families That Can lo que ocurri√≥ en la reuni√≥n, especialmente si hubo de por medio  un compromiso por parte del funcionario, si hubo preguntas que no pudo contestar o cualquier preocupaci√≥n expresada por el funcionario o empleado que pudiera ayudar a CCSA a afinar sus esfuerzos de cabildeo.</li>\n<li>No se desanime si se reuni√≥ con un empleado en lugar de un funcionario. Es probable que usted obtenga m√°s atenci√≥n por parte de un empleado asignado a esa tarea y que tenga conocimientos del tema.</li>\n<li>No incluya demasiados asuntos en la agenda. Si se limita a  tratar dos o tres asuntos es un n√∫mero razonable para que el funcionario o empleado pueda digerirlos en una reuni√≥n.</li>\n<li>*No se sienta intimidado por un funcionario o por los empleados gubernamentales. Usted es el experto en esta materia; el funcionario y su personal est√°n dispuestos a escucharlo para que usted los oriente y eduque con el fin de que ellos puedan tomar una decisi√≥n informada sobre la posici√≥n que adoptar√°n.</li>\n<li>No asuma que s√≥lo porque un funcionario lo apoy√≥ en el pasado, lo har√° nuevamente. A menos que √©l o ella se comprometan a apoyarlo desde el principio de la reuni√≥n, siempre exprese su mensaje como lo har√≠a con cualquier funcionario o empleado.</li>\n<li>No se comporte de manera hostil ni busque confrontaciones con el funcionario o sus empleados. Aunque el funcionario puede oponerse a usted en un asunto, puede apoyarlo en otros. Adem√°s, cualquier encuentro desagradable puede obstaculizar los esfuerzos de su equipo de cabildeo en Sacramento.</li>\n<li>No permita que un funcionario o empleado lo conduzca a una confrontaci√≥n. Escuche sus comentarios o haga preguntas para determinar las bases de la oposici√≥n. Responda a esas preocupaciones de manera respetuosa, usando hechos y datos, si es posible. Pregunte si hay informaci√≥n espec√≠fica o enmiendas que har√≠an que el funcionario cambiara su posici√≥n.</li>\n<li>No permanezca en una reuni√≥n hostil m√°s tiempo del necesario. Mantenga una conducta profesional, conteste las preguntas que le hagan, pero trate de terminar la reuni√≥n tan pronto como sea posible.</li>\n<li>No d√© por terminados sus esfuerzos con el funcionario una vez que la reuni√≥n haya concluido. Haga un seguimiento con √©l en su distrito.</li>\n<li>Ofrezca encontrarse nuevamente para una discusi√≥n m√°s a fondo durante los descansos legislativos e inv√≠telo a un recorrido para que conozca su programa. Y aseg√∫rese de hacer un seguimiento porque cuidar una relaci√≥n honesta y respetuosa con un funcionario es una estrategia de largo plazo que puede rendir buenos frutos en el futuro.</li>\n</ul>\n', 'C√≥mo Tener Una Reuni√≥n Legislativa Efectiva', '¬°Es importante prepararse antes de una reuni√≥n con su representante electo. Aprenda que hacer y que no hacer!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '74-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '', 74, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/74-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(783, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '<p>Si bien es vital estar actualizado con las informaciones de Families That Can y responder a todos los llamados para participar, es tambi√©n igualmente importante fortalecer el movimiento a trav√©s de una participaci√≥n constante a lo largo del a√±o.\nEl mantener a los encargados de elaborar las pol√≠ticas p√∫blicas comprometidos durante al a√±o los mantiene informados de la importancia del movimiento de las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter, as√≠ como de sus √©xitos y desaf√≠os. El contacto frecuente y consistente con su legislador construye una relaci√≥n importante y env√≠a un claro mensaje de que usted apoya su escuela, el movimiento de las escuelas ch√°rter y la reforma educativa.\nAqu√≠ le presentamos algunas sugerencias para ayudarle a usted, a su escuela y a sus partidarios a permanecer involucrados durante todo el a√±o.\nA√±o redondo:**  Agregue a su legislador a la lista de correo de su escuela para boletines de noticias y boletines electr√≥nicos; siga a sus legisladores en las redes sociales y env√≠eles anuncios, comunicados de prensa o cualquier aviso sobre logros importantes a sus oficinas de distrito locales.\nPor favor agregue communications@calcharters.org a su lista de distribuci√≥n para que pueda amplificar sus √©xitos y compartirlos con una audiencia mayor.\n<strong>Septiembre:</strong> Invite a su legislador a las ceremonias de corte de list√≥n para las nuevas escuelas o a las celebraciones del "Regreso a Clases" para las escuelas ya existentes.\n<strong>Octubre:</strong> Invite a su legislador a hablar en su escuela.\n<strong>Noviembre:</strong> Invite a su legislador a hacer una presentaci√≥n en clases de civismo o en reuniones de gobierno para estudiantes.\n<strong>Diciembre:</strong> Invite a su legislador a la recaudaci√≥n de alimentos enlatados de su escuela.\n<strong>Enero:</strong>  Invite a su legislador a las actividades de invierno de la escuela.\n<strong>Febrero:</strong> Invite a su legislador a hablar en la asociaci√≥n de padres de su escuela. Invite a su legislador a servir como Director por un D√≠a.\n<strong>Marzo:</strong> Invite a su legislador al Inicio de Clases en su escuela.\n<strong>Abril:</strong> Invite a su legislador  a leer a los estudiantes durante la Semana Nacional de la Lectura.\n<strong>Mayo:</strong> Invite a su legislador a la celebraci√≥n en su escuela de la Semana Nacional de las Escuelas Ch√°rter.\n<strong>Junio:</strong> Invite a su legislador a hablar en la ceremonia de fin de a√±o o de graduaci√≥n de su escuela.\n<strong>Julio:</strong> Visite a su legislador en su oficina de distrito.\n<strong>Agosto:</strong> Organice un grupo de estudiantes para un viaje de verano al Capitolio Estatal.</p>\n', 'Participe Durante Todo El A√±o: Calendario de Eventos', 'Si bien es vital estar actualizado con las informaciones de Families That Can y responder a todos los llamados para participar, es tambi√©n igualmente importante fortalecer el movimiento a trav√©s de una participaci√≥n constante a lo largo del a√±o.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '73-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '', 73, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/73-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(784, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '<p>La defensa comunitaria es un enfoque para la elaboraci√≥n de  pol√≠ticas p√∫blicas de abajo hacia arriba. En lugar de depender de un equipo de profesionales altamente calificados, de cabilderos registrados y de consultores para influenciar a la legislatura, la defensa comunitaria depende de los ciudadanos comunes y de los votantes para contactar directamente e influenciar  a los encargados de elaborar pol√≠ticas p√∫blicas.\nCreemos firmemente que sin el apoyo comunitario, el movimiento de las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter no tendr√° √©xito.\nComo partidarios de las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter debemos demostrar a quienes elaboran las pol√≠ticas p√∫blicas que las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter tienen un profundo apoyo en las comunidades que representan. Usted es un defensor comunitario de las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter y puede ayudar a impulsar el cambio en las pol√≠ticas animando a otras personas que usted conoce a que tambi√©n participen, entre ellas a las siguientes:\n- Sus familiares y amigos\n- Sus vecinos\n- Organizaciones a las que usted pertenezca, espec√≠ficamente grupos de padres en las escuelas\n- Los maestros de sus hijos, sus entrenadores o padres de los compa√±eros de sus hijos\n- Otras personas en su c√≠rculo social, tales como colegas y gente  de negocios y organizaciones en su comunidad o en su iglesia</p>\n\n<h3>¬øQui√©nes son sus funcionarios electos?</h3>\n\n<p>Los funcionarios electos, los encargados de elaborar pol√≠ticas p√∫blicas y de tomar decisiones son gente elegida para representarlo que puede estar en posici√≥n de influenciar las pol√≠ticas o la legislaci√≥n relacionada con las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter.  Por favor visite <a href="http://192.234.213.69/smapsearch/framepage.asp">estas p√°ginas de la Legislatura</a> para saber qui√©nes son sus representantes estatales.\nEjemplos de funcionarios nombrados y elegidos que nos representan:\n- Gobernador\n- Alcalde\n- Senadores estatales\n- Asamble√≠stas estatales\n- Miembros del Concejo de la Ciudad\n- Junta Estatal de Educaci√≥n\n- Junta de Educaci√≥n del distrito escolar\n- Junta de Educaci√≥n del condado</p>\n', '¬øQui√©nes son sus funcionarios electos?', 'La defensa comunitaria es un enfoque para la elaboraci√≥n de  pol√≠ticas p√∫blicas de abajo hacia arriba. Usted es un defensor comunitario de las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '72-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '2016-01-13 04:18:17', '', 72, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/72-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
