(883, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '<p>Our elected representatives make decisions every day that affect our schools and our students, from a state legislator who proposes a bill that will hurt charter schools to a local school board member who is deciding whether to let a new charter school open in that district.\n<strong>When it comes to charter schools, YOU are the expert.</strong> You have a great story to tell and speaking out really makes a difference - so how do you get your voice heard? It used to be you had to get the media\'s attention to write a story that would reach a lot of people. Nowadays, with the Internet, you have the power to reach people directly in so many different ways.\nThis page has more questions than answers. Our goal is to give you the right questions to ask so you can come up with a great strategy to support your school by speaking out online and sharing your story and getting other parents at your school to do the same!\nKey Questions:\n<strong>WHAT</strong> is your goal?\n<strong>WHO</strong> do you want to reach?\n<strong>WHAT</strong> do you want to say?\n<strong>WHERE</strong> are conversations taking place online?\n<strong>HOW</strong> do you best make your voice heard?\n<a href="/FTC_Communications_plan_template.pdf">Use this printable handout to guide you through developing a strategy for your online advocacy and outreach.</a>\nIt\'s important to work closely with your school leader and other parents and staff so that everyone is well-coordinated, knows what to say and understands their role in the plan. Your approach will vary depending on who you\'re trying to reach and for what purpose.\nDon\'t have a specific campaign underway at your school right now? There are still a lot of great things you can do to support your school and all charter schools.\nMore resources:\n- <a href="/2012/05/how-to-respond-to-criticism-online.html">How to Respond to Criticism of Your School Online</a>\n- <a href="/2012/05/how-to-write-a-letter-to-the-editor.html">How to Write a Letter to the Editor</a>\n- <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2011/07/how-to-use-patchcom-to-get-out-the-good-word-about-your-school.html">How to Use Patch.com to Get Out the Good Word About Your School</a>\n- <strong>Media Outreach:</strong> Do you need help reaching out to local reporters? Just send an email to <a href="mailto:contact@familiesthatcan.org">contact@familiesthatcan.org</a> and we\'re happy to lend a hand!</p>\n\n<h3>Get Inspired</h3>\n\n<p>Below, you will find a variety of examples of online communications from different charter schools across California.\n<strong>School Websites</strong>\nA professional website is key to establishing your school\'s brand. There are many companies that can help you design, post and maintain an attractive website at an affordable cost and without advanced technical skills.\nMake sure your website has both basic content that rarely changes such as an "About us" section, contact details and a list of board members, as well as space on your home page to highlight new content. Some schools have a news section on their front page like <a href="http://www.pucschools.org/">Partnerships to Uplift Communities</a>.\nYour website is a resource for many different audiences. The <a href="http://www.classicalacademy.com">Classical Academies web site</a> is made to be easy to navigate, with all the basic information front and center and a tab for current parents to find the updates relevant to them.\n<strong>Social Media</strong>\nSocial media refers to a wide variety of different websites, with seemingly new outlets popping up daily. What they share in common is they allow users to interact with the content and each other, facilitating online conversation. Having a presence on some of these sites can be a great way to raise awareness about your school and share good news with a broad audience.\nHere are some sites you might explore:\n- Facebook\n- Twitter\n- YouTube\n-  GreatSchools\n- MySpace\n- Yelp\n- Flickr\n- Utterli\n- Wikis\n- Meetup\n- Digg\nJust because you haven\'t heard of a site doesn\'t mean people in your community don\'t use it! Schools use social media in various ways.\nFor instance, Green Dot has links to <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/greendotschools">YouTube</a>, <a href="http://twitter.com/greendotschools">Twitter</a> and <a href="http://www.facebook.com/pages/Green-Dot-Public-Schools/89279457280">Facebook</a> prominently displayed on their <a href="http://www.greendot.org">web page</a>, including a box on the home page featuring the latest tweets.\n<a href="http://www.facebook.com/#!/pages/Synergy-Academies/194559103836">Synergy Academies</a> uses Facebook as a way to stay in touch with alumni, board members and supporters. They do a great job of posting lots of photos, links to news coverage of the school and other updates on a regular basis. You can see many more schools\' Facebook pages in the "Favorite Pages" section of <a href="http://www.facebook.com/calcharters">CCSA\'s Facebook page</a>.\n<a href="http://www.greatschools.org/news/3138-schools-using-social-media.gs?page=1">This article</a> details more creative ways that schools have used social media, like promoting school events or sending out the daily cafeteria menu.\n<strong>Video</strong>\nMany schools produce a video about their school, which can be a fun way to promote the school. Here are a few different videos from: <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QxZkHCAwup4">Larchmont Charter School in Los Angeles</a>, <a href="http://www.youtube.com/embed/Wjxi0snEu98">Envision Charter Schools in the Bay Area</a> and <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/cacharters#p/u/44/C-awbRJN3to">Watts Learning Center in Los Angeles</a>.\n<strong>Blogs</strong>\nA blog can also be a way to spread the good word and to integrate different voices from your school community. Blog are particularly well-suited to integrating photos and video or links to interesting news articles or web sites. You can write about any issue or success story at your school, or invite others to do so, including parents, students, teachers and boardmembers. This <a href="http://www.muellercharterschool.org/Blog/">blog from Mueller Charter School</a> in Chula Vista has posts from various people on a variety of subjects. The <a href="http://oxfordchampions.typepad.com/">blog for Oxford Preparatory Academy in Chino Valley</a> has lots of photos and updates on classroom projects. The <a href="http://schools20.rsed.org/">blog for Rocketship Education</a> has entries on a variety of hot topics in education reform.</p>\n', 'How To Get Your Voice Heard Online', 'Learn more about blogging and harnessing the power of social media as a parent advocate!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '109-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 109, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/109-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(884, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '<p>Online forums give you an opportunity to defend yourself, share more information and get the word out. In this day and age, people get information from many different sources, and engaging online is key for building awareness of your school and building support.\n<strong>Most importantly, if someone writes bad things about you on an online forum, RESPOND.<sup>*</sup></strong></p>\n\n<h3>Why should I respond to an online post about my school?</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Much of what is posted on the web stays there indefinitely. People searching the internet will continue to find forums that are years old and have incorrect information.</li>\n<li>Responding to a nasty post can help set the record straight. At the very least, the response sows seeds of doubt in the reader\'s mind about whether the author of the original post is trustworthy.</li>\n<li>It starts a conversation. Just as you engage with the community face-to-face, social media, blogs and websites are a way to educate people about charter schools and to build support for your school.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Tips for engaging online</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>If you are mentioned online, whether positive or negative, encourage members of your community - teachers, staff, parents, or high school students to post their own comments and responses. Your parents are your best advocates!</li>\n<li>If you personally respond, be transparent about your relationship to the school, i.e.: "I am a parent at X school..." or "I work at X school. I would encourage anyone who is interested to visit our school. Contact us at XXX-XXXX."</li>\n<li>Share links that allow people to find out more and that verify what you\'re saying. For example:</li>\n<li>A link to your school\'s website</li>\n<li>A link to <a href="/understanding/">info for the public about charter schools from CCSA\'s website</a></li>\n<li>A link to media coverage of your school or the topic of the discussion</li>\n<li>Go beyond the newspaper. Articles on traditional media sites are a good place to start, but conversations are happening in many corners of the internet. For example:</li>\n<li>Yahoo! groups</li>\n<li>Facebook (Sometimes local businesses or organizations have a large following in their neighborhoods)</li>\n<li>Twitter</li>\n<li>Blogs (<a href="http://technorati.com/">Technorati</a> is a good place to search.)</li>\n<li>Google your school. This is a great way to find out WHERE people are talking about your school online and WHAT they\'re saying about you.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>When you SHOULD NOT respond to a post</h4>\n\n<p><sup>*</sup> Before responding, look at the website or blog and find out more about the author of the post. Do they often write about charters or education? Is their coverage completely one-sided? Is the forum a space that is open to different viewpoints? If the author is extreme in his or her views, responding can sometimes only serve to incur more vitriol. This is a judgment call to make on a case by case basis.</p>\n', 'How to Respond to Criticism Online', 'Has someone posted negative comments about your school online? There are many ways to engage other parents at your school to respond.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '108-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 108, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/108-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(885, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '<p>Was there an article about your school or charter schools in the local newspaper? Did you feel the reporter didn\'t get it right or that there is more to the story?\nWriting a letter to the editor of your local publication is a great way to raise awareness about your school and set the record straight.\n- <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2011/04/letters-to-the-editor.html">See examples of letters written by parents and charter leaders.</a></p>\n\n<h3>Tips</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Be careful to keep a lid on your emotions, as a well-written and focused letter will be more likely to be published.</li>\n<li>All publications have a word maximum for submissions, generally between 150 and 200 words. Make sure you keep it short or the publication either won\'t run it or will edit your letter as they see fit.</li>\n<li>There are often opportunities to comment online immediately following an article on a publication\'s website. Go ahead and post your comments there, as well as submitting them to the editor.</li>\n<li>If you are responding to a story that already ran, also give the reporter who wrote the story a call or send an email to start building a relationship for future stories on local schools.</li>\n<li>Do you have more to say than what will fit in 150 words? Consider penning a guest editorial. The guest editorial or "op-ed" page is a coveted spot. Contact the editor of the publication, and discuss the potential for publishing your submitted story. A guest editorial should be succinct, well-researched, and timely. Publications will have a word maximum generally between 650 and 750 words per submission.</li>\n</ul>\n', 'How to Write a Letter to the Editor', 'Was there an article about your school or charter schools in the local newspaper? Writing a letter to the editor of your local publication is a great way to raise awareness about your school and set the record straight.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '107-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 107, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/107-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(886, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '<p>This Wednesday, you\'re invited to meet the current candidates for the Sacramento County Board of Education. Our elected representatives on the boards for school districts and county offices of education make major decisions affecting our local schools. Don\'t miss this chance to learn more and meet the candidates before the June 5 election!\n<strong>DATE</strong>: Wednesday, May 2\n<strong>TIME</strong>: 6 p.m.\nChild Care provided\n<strong>LOCATION</strong>: Fortune School\n6829 Stockton Blvd.\nSacramento, CA 95823\nAre you registered to vote? Your vote is your voice! It\'s easy - <a href="/2012/04/how-to-register-to-vote.html">find out how to register to vote today!</a></p>\n', 'May 2: Sacramento County Candidate Forum - You\'re invited!', 'This Wednesday, you\'re invited to meet the current candidates for the Sacramento County Board of Education.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '106-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 106, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/106-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(887, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="voting_red_check_mark_stock.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/04/voting_red_check_mark_stock-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>Registrarse para votar s√≥lo toma un par de minutos y le permite votar en las elecciones, cumplir con su deber como ciudadano Estadounidense y hacer que su voz sea escuchada.\nEs emocionante participar en las elecciones Presidenciales cada cuatro a√±os, pero no se olvide de que su voto tiene un tremendo impacto a nivel local. Afecta decisiones sobre las escuelas locales, as√≠ como  iniciativas de municipios y  condados.</p>\n\n<h3>Reg√≠strese</h3>\n\n<p>Usted puede <a href="https://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/register-to-vote/">registrarse para votar en l√≠nea</a> o puede tambi√©n recoger un formulario en la oficina electoral de su condado,  bibliotecas locales, u oficinas de correo.\nLas elecciones son administradas por el <a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/new-voter/spanish/">Secretario de Estado de California</a>. Visite su <a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/new-voter/spanish/">p√°gina web</a> para obtener m√°s informaci√≥n sobre c√≥mo registrarse para votar o para averiguar si ya est√° registrado.</p>\n\n<h3>Inf√≥rmese</h3>\n\n<p>Es importante aprender m√°s sobre los candidatos e iniciativas electorales en su √°rea. Usted puede encontrar una gran cantidad de informaci√≥n por Internet,en los medios de comunicaci√≥n locales, o asistiendo a eventos y foros de los candidatos o iniciativas.\nLa Sociedad de Mujeres Votantes (League of Women Voters) es una organizaci√≥n no partidista que <a href="http://vote411.org/">ofrece mucha informaci√≥n para los votantes</a>.</p>\n\n<h3>¬°Vote!</h3>\n\n<p>Este pendiente de las pr√≥ximas elecciones en su √°rea. Por lo general, hay varias elecciones que se llevan a cabo cada a√±o. Todos los votantes recibir√°n informaci√≥n por corr√©o antes de cada elecci√≥n sobre los candidatos e Iniciativas inclu√≠das en la boleta electoral, as√≠ como su lugar de votaci√≥n.\nLos votantes pueden obtener ayuda adicional en espa√±ol llamando gratis a la l√≠nea especial de la Secretar√≠a de Estado al (800) 232-VOTA (8682).\n<a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/new-voter/spanish/"><img src="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/bug/myvote-spanish.png" alt="Nuevo votante" width="178" height="74" /></a></p>\n', 'Como Registrarse Para Votar', '¬°Su voto es su voz!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '103-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '', 103, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/103-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(888, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="voting_red_check_mark_stock.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/04/voting_red_check_mark_stock-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>Registering to vote only takes a couple of minutes and allows you to be able to vote in elections, fulfill your duty as an American citizen and make your voice heard.\nIt\'s exciting to participate in presidential elections every four years, but don\'t forget that your vote has tremendous impact at the local level, from local schools to city government and county initiatives.</p>\n\n<h3>Get Registered</h3>\n\n<p>You can easily <a href="https://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/register-to-vote/">register to vote online</a> or by picking up a form at your county elections office, library, or U.S. Post Office.\nElections are handled by the <a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/elections_vr.htm">California Secretary of State</a>. Visit their <a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/elections_vr.htm">webpage</a> to learn more about how to register to vote or to find out if you\'re already registered.</p>\n\n<h3>Get Informed</h3>\n\n<p>It\'s important to learn more about the candidates and ballot initiatives in your area. You can find lots of great information online and in your local media or by attending events and candidates forums.\n<a href="http://vote411.org/">The non-partisan League of Women Voters is a one-stop shop for voter information. </a></p>\n\n<h3>Vote!</h3>\n\n<p>Keep an eye out for upcoming elections in your area. There are usually several elections each year. All voters receive information in the mail before each election about the candidates and initiatives they will be voting on and where to find their polling place.</p>\n', 'How to Register to Vote', 'Your vote is your voice!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '102-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '', 102, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/102-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(889, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '<p>En la √∫ltima semana de abril, los Subcomit√©s Presupuestarios  del Senado y la Asamblea Estatal discutir√°n muchos asuntos relacionados con el presupuesto de las escuelas ch√°rter. ¬°Los Legisladores necesitan <a href="http://www.votervoice.net/core.aspx?APP=GAC&amp;AID=828&amp;IssueID=28506&amp;SiteID=-1">escuchar su opini√≥n</a> sobre c√≥mo las decisiones que ellos toman impactan a las escuelas de sus hijos!\n- El Subcomit√© Presupuestario de la Asamblea hablar√° sobre la Educaci√≥n el martes 24 de abril.\n- El Subcomit√© Presupuestario del Senado hablar√° sobre la Educaci√≥n el jueves 26 de abril.\nEl Gobernador Jerry Brown dio a conocer su plan presupuestario este pasado mes de enero, el cual es el primer paso del proceso para aprobar el plan de gasto anual de California. El plan del Gobernador contiene reformas significativas dise√±adas para nivelar el terreno de juego entre los distritos y las escuelas ch√°rter mediante la racionalizaci√≥n y la ampliaci√≥n de una serie de apoyos financieros para las escuelas ch√°rter. La propuesta del Gobernador est√° supeditada a la aprobaci√≥n de su Iniciativa para aumentar varios impuestos, la cual est√° aparecer√° en la boleta electoral  en las elecciones del mes de noviembre.\nLa Legislatura Estatal continuar√° con el debate y la revisi√≥n del presupuesto hasta principios del oto√±o. Los mantendremos informados sobre c√≥mo las decisiones de los Legisladores afectar√°n a la escuela ch√°rter de sus hijos.\n¬°Necesitamos hablar hoy para apoyar las prospuestas relacionadas con las escuelas ch√°rter!\nEstos son los puntos claves para hablar con sus representantes electos:\n1.  Las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter reciben, como m√≠nimo, 7% menos financiamiento que otras escuelas p√∫blicas, lo cual es simplemente injusto y por ello, debe cambiar.\n2.  Despu√©s de a√±os de recortes y aplazamientos presupuestarios, actualmente resulta excepcionalmente dif√≠cil dirigir una escuela ch√°rter, situaci√≥n que empeora, ya que las escuelas ch√°rter no tienen la misma opci√≥n que las escuelas p√∫blicas de los distritos de poder pedir pr√©stamos con bajos intereses.\n3.  El plan presupuestario del Gobernador propone soluciones de bajo costo para ayudar a nivelar el campo de juego para las escuelas ch√°rter, entre ellas soluciones para mejorar el flujo de efectivo y reducir la burocracia.\nNuestro sistema facilita el env√≠o de cartas a los Legisladores. <a href="http://www.votervoice.net/core.aspx?APP=GAC&amp;AID=828&amp;IssueID=28506&amp;SiteID=-1">¬°Env√≠e una carta hoy mismo!</a>\n- Aprenda m√°s sobre el proceso Legislativo en nuestro <a href="/training/">Centro de Acci√≥n</a> .\n- <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2011/04/state-budget-update.html">Obtenga informaci√≥n detallada sobre el plan presupuestario actual.</a></p>\n', 'Presupuesto estatal - Exige una parte justa para las escuelas ch√°rter', 'En la √∫ltima semana de abril, los Legisladores estatales discutir√°n muchos asuntos relacionados con el presupuesto de las escuelas ch√°rter. ¬°Necesitan escuchar su opini√≥n!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '101-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '', 101, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/101-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(890, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '<p>In the last week of April, California\'s Senate and Assembly Budget Sub-Committees will discuss many charter school budget items. <a href="http://www.votervoice.net/core.aspx?APP=GAC&amp;AID=828&amp;IssueID=28506&amp;SiteID=-1">They need to hear from you about how their decisions impact your school! </a>\n- Assembly Budget Subcommittee on Education on Tuesday, April 24\n- Senate Budget Subcommittee on Education on Thursday, April 26\nThese are the key points to tell your elected representatives:\n- Charter public schools receive, at minimum, 7% less than other public schools - this is simply unfair and must be changed.\n- Years of funding cuts and deferrals have made it exceptionally difficult to run a charter public school, in part because charter schools don\'t have the same ability to borrow at low-cost like district public schools have.\n- The Governor\'s budget proposes low-cost solutions to help level the playing field for charter schools, like improving cash flow solutions and reducing bureaucracy.\nOur system makes it easy to send a letter to legislators - <a href="http://www.votervoice.net/core.aspx?APP=GAC&amp;AID=828&amp;IssueID=28506&amp;SiteID=-1">send a letter in support of the charter school items today</a>!\nGovernor Jerry Brown released his state budget proposal in January, the first step in California\'s annual budget process. His budget currently contains significant reforms designed to level the playing field between districts and charter schools by streamlining and expanding a number of financial supports for charter schools. The Governor\'s proposal is contingent on voter approval of his tax initiative on the November ballot.\nThe State Legislature will continue to debate and revise the budget through early fall. We\'ll keep you updated on how their decisions will affect your charter school.\n- Learn more about the legislative process in our <a href="/training/">Train for Action</a> section.\n- <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2011/04/state-budget-update.html">Get detailed information about the current budget proposal.</a></p>\n', 'State Budget: Demand A Fair Share for Charter Schools', 'Legislators are discussing many charter school budget items this week - they need to hear from you!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '100-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '', 100, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/100-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(891, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '<p>As a parent and supporter within the charter school movement, we are constantly reacting to legislative attacks targeting charter schools. All these attacks become even more personal to me last week after attending a Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) board meeting. My child\'s school, <a href="/2011/10/watts-learning-center-in-los-angeles.html">Watts Learning Center</a>, is one of the highest-performing charter schools in the state of California. This is a school with a proven track record of providing children in my South Los Angeles a great education. It is a school that demonstrates that African Americans and Latino children can learn. It\'s simply a school that we the people and community believe in.\nThis school was recently up for renewal with LAUSD and it would only make sense that if this school is providing a high-quality education for all children,  it should get renewed immediately. Unfortunately, this was not the case for our high-performing school.\nInstead, school board member Bennett Kayser <a href="/2012/04/parents-tell-boardmember-stop-attacking-charters.html">announced that he planned to vote against all charter school items</a>, including renewals. He set out to convince his colleagues on the board to vote "No" on this school that means so much to its community. We in the charter school and the greater community heard his message loud and clear: "No matter how great you might be in serving black and brown children, politics and money take precedence over your children\'s education."\nThis is the exact reason why families must continue to make their voices heard especially to those that aren\'t familiar with or don\'t care about charter schools. This is the reasons why families must continue to defend the rights of our children to receive a great, high-quality education.\nFortunately, the academic success of my children\'s school and the support of the community convinced the school board to approve our school for renewal with a 6-1 vote. Lesson learned: Don\'t wait until adversity knocks on your door, get engaged and inspired to defend the children of the charter school movement! <a href="/join">Sign up today to receive our free e-newsletter and action alerts!</a>. Your voices are needed in this movement!\nHas your school signed on to partner with Families That Can? <a href="/for-school-leaders/">Learn more!</a></p>\n', 'Why Charter Parents MUST Speak Out', 'K.W. Tulloss saw first-hand the importance of advocacy work when his child\'s school was recently up for renewal and ran into some political challenges that put the school\'s future in jeopardy.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '99-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '', 99, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/99-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(892, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '<p>Nac√≠ en Per√∫. Mi familia emigr√≥ a los Estados Unidos cuando yo ten√≠a 5 a√±os. Mis padres llegaron aqu√≠ con una sola meta en mente para mi hermana y para m√≠, que tuvi√©ramos una mejor educaci√≥n y mejores oportunidades. He vivido en Downey casi toda mi vida y siempre  asist√≠ a escuelas p√∫blicas hasta que complet√© mi bachillerato en mercadotecnia en la Universidad Estatal de  California en Los √Ångeles (CSULA), en 2008.\nSiempre he disfrutado ayudar a otras personas. Cuando me gradu√© de la preparatoria, me enter√© que una organizaci√≥n local no lucrativa llamada Crystal Stairs necesitaba ayuda durante las vacaciones. Trabaj√© ah√≠ durante los siguientes ocho a√±os como especialista en inscripci√≥n y en relaciones con la comunidad, como int√©rprete biling√ºe, como especialista de referencias  y como administradora de casos. Conectaba a las personas con programas estatales y federales que pod√≠an ayudarles con sus necesidades m√°s urgentes  como servicios para el cuidado de ni√±os y de salud.</p>\n\n<div class="figure embedded-image left"><a rel="lightbox" href="/assets_c/2012/03/fiorella_del_carpio-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___home_featured_primary-thumb-223x165-2526.jpg" title="fiorella_del_carpio.jpg (Homepage Featured Primary)"><img alt="fiorella_del_carpio.jpg (Homepage Featured Primary)" src="/assets_c/2012/03/fiorella_del_carpio-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___home_featured_primary-thumb-223x165-2526.jpg" width="223" height="165" class="mt-image-left" /></a></div>\n\n<p>Fue una experiencia agridulce. Tuve la oportunidad de interactuar uno a uno con los padres, lo cual fue muy satisfactorio. Al mismo tiempo, experiment√© de cerca los desaf√≠os que enfrenta la gente y la necesidad tan cr√≠tica que hay de contar con programas sociales para las familias, especialmente cuando alguien pierde su trabajo.\nCon la crisis estatal, muchos de estos programas se cerraron. Nos enfocamos entonces en ofrecer servicios para el cuidado infantil, pero las familias acud√≠an a nosotros en busca de una amplia variedad de servicios. Todo esto demand√≥ mucha cooperaci√≥n y confianza entre la comunidad y yo.\nLa primera vez que escuch√© sobre una escuela ch√°rter fue hace varios a√±os cuando una compa√±era de trabajo me dijo que estaba llevando a sus ni√±os a una escuela ch√°rter en Culver City, muy lejos de donde ella viv√≠a en South Gate. Me dio curiosidad y entr√© a Internet para averiguar m√°s. Las escuelas ch√°rter me recordaron c√≥mo era mi escuela primaria: clases peque√±as, mucho apoyo por parte de los maestros y una gran participaci√≥n por parte de los padres.\nMi mam√° siempre particip√≥ en mi escuela y estaba al pendiente de mi desempe√±o y de mis calificaciones. Me puedo identificar con la gente que viene aqu√≠ para que sus hijos tengan mejores oportunidades, porque fue lo que mis padres hicieron por mi hermana y m√≠. Ahora como adulta, puedo entender y apreciar todo. Si no hubiera sido por mis padres y por todo su apoyo, no estar√≠a donde estoy hoy. Ellos me ense√±aron que si uno es determinado, puede hacer todo.</p>\n', 'Conozca a Fiorella Del Carpio de Families That Can', 'Fiorella trabaja con padres y varias organizaciones comunitarias en Los Angeles.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '98-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '', 98, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/98-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(893, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="voting_red_check_mark_stock.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/04/voting_red_check_mark_stock-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>Registering to vote only takes a couple of minutes. With this uncomplicated process, you\'ll be able to vote in elections and fulfill your duty as an American citizen. Remember, your vote is your voice!\nIn 2012, you will have the opportunity to participate in the presidential election. However, your vote has even more impact on the local level, whether it\'s taxes, schools or city government initiatives. Those are even more reasons to be excited about getting registered.\nRegistering to vote gives you the power to affect how things are done in your neighborhood, your city, your state and nation. The question is simple: are you registered to vote? If the answer is no, get registered today!\nJust check out "<a href="/2012/04/how-to-register-to-vote.html">How to Vote</a>" in our Training section!</p>\n', 'Are you registered to vote?', 'The primary is coming up June 5 so register today. It only takes a couple of minutes!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '97-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '', 97, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/97-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(894, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '<p>El 4 de febrero de 2012, m√°s de 5,000 padres de m√°s de 100 escuelas ch√°rter llevaron a cabo una manifestaci√≥n en el Exposition Park en Los √Ångeles para exigir escuelas p√∫blicas de alta calidad en todas las comunidades, y un financiamiento justo e instalaciones adecuadas para todos los estudiantes de escuelas p√∫blicas. El Alcalde de Los √Ångeles, Antonio Villaraigosa, se dirigi√≥ a los padres en el evento "Schools We Can Believe In" (Las Escuelas Que Merecemos).\n*El Alcalde habla en espa√±ol a partir del minuto 13.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/3IQcP6uDpVg" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>"No puedo decirles cu√°nta inspiraci√≥n causa ver a miles de padres aqu√≠, hablando con una sola voz, diciendo "El fracaso no es una opci√≥n", y a familias que exigen cambios, que est√°n exigiendo las mejores escuelas posibles para sus hijos".\n"Ustedes son la clave. Sin los padres dedicados, nunca cambiaremos nuestro sistema escolar", dijo el Alcalde Villaraigosa, quien comparti√≥ su propia historia. Cont√≥ que cuando asist√≠a a la Preparatoria Roosevelt en el Este de Los √Ångeles en la d√©cada de los a√±os 1960s, la deserci√≥n escolar era del 75%.\n"Ten√≠a la sensaci√≥n de que la escuela hab√≠a renunciado a m√≠ y yo pude haberme dado por vencido. Mi historia pudo haber terminado en ese entonces. Yo pude haber sido una estad√≠stica m√°s, pero mi madre nunca se dio por vencida  conmigo  y ustedes tampoco se est√°n dando por vencidos con sus hijos", dijo Villaraigosa.\nEl Alcalde hizo notar que el n√∫mero de escuelas ch√°rter en Los √Ångeles se ha duplicado desde el 2005.\n"Cuando los padres tienen opciones, no tienen por qu√© aceptar escuelas que est√°n fracasando," dijo. "Porque ustedes tienen opciones, el n√∫mero de escuelas en el [Distrito Escolar] Unificado de Los √Ångeles que cumple con las metas estatales del √≠ndice de desempe√±o acad√©mico tambi√©n se ha duplicado".\nVillaraigosa se√±al√≥ que los padres necesitan recursos para poder tener un impacto positivo, como boletas de calificaciones escolares y leyes para promover reformas, como la llamada "Parent Trigger".\n"El saber es poder. Cuando los padres tienen buena informaci√≥n, pueden tomar buenas decisiones", dijo.\nSubray√≥ que todas nuestras escuelas p√∫blicas necesitan recibir m√°s fondos estatales. Pidi√≥ a los padres que se comuniquen con sus representantes electos, y que les digan sobre la necesidad de financiar justamente a las escuelas p√∫blicas, y para tambi√©n responsabilizar a nuestras escuelas a√∫n m√°s para que ofrezcan una buena educaci√≥n para todo estudiante.\n"Padres, yo creo en ustedes. Creo en sus hijos. El futuro de la educaci√≥n en Los √Ångeles depende de ustedes," finaliz√≥ el Alcalde Villaraigosa.</p>\n', 'El Alcalde de Los √Ångeles dice a los padres: "Ustedes son la clave"', 'El Alcalde se dirigi√≥ a m√°s de 5,000 padres que asistieron a una manifestaci√≥n para mejores escuelas en Los √Ångeles. Vea el video.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '96-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '2016-01-13 04:19:57', '', 96, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/96-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
