(917, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:10', '2016-01-13 04:22:10', '<iframe width="420" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/cAhoEipyKLo" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n\n<p>Cuando el plantel Citizens of the World Charter School se inaugur√≥ en Mar Vista hace un a√±o, los padres estaban particularmente entusiasmados por el compromiso de la escuela para celebrar la diversidad. M√°s de la mitad de los estudiantes no eran anglosajones y muchos de los padres eran inmigrantes, lo cual reflejaba  la demograf√≠a del vecindario.\nPor esa raz√≥n, los padres se sorprendieron cuando un peque√±o grupo de activistas contra los planteles ch√°rter encabez√≥ un  movimiento de oposici√≥n a la escuela, basado en la idea de que no representaba a la comunidad.  Los padres se sintieron atacados cuando leyeron <a href="http://laschoolreport.com/zimmer-lausd-culture-war-over-co-locations-on-the-west-side/">declaraciones p√∫blicas de Steve Zimmer, miembro de su propia junta escolar, acus√°ndolos de evitar la diversidad</a>.\nPara agravar las cosas, un error administrativo impuls√≥ al Distrito Escolar Unificado de L.A., a evitar que la escuela permaneciera en su ubicaci√≥n actual.  Los estudiantes se quedaron s√∫bitamente sin instalaciones para el siguiente a√±o escolar.\n¬øLos padres de Citizens of the World aceptaron esta dif√≠cil situaci√≥n? No.  Ellos defendieron a su escuela y a sus familias. Se presentaron en grandes n√∫meros en una junta del LAUSD y testificaron. El miembro de la Junta, Steve Zimmer, fue confrontado con un diverso y apasionado grupo de padres que dibuj√≥ un cuadro muy diferente de su escuela.\nUn padre, que a√±os atr√°s se hab√≠a graduado del LAUSD, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_FNMVFQ6bHI">dijo que hab√≠a elegido Citizens of the World precisamente porque la escuela aceptaba la diversidad</a>;  una madre <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qxOxD63X5Ro">comparti√≥ la historia del tremendo progreso acad√©mico de su hija</a>  durante el pasado a√±o; una madre <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cAhoEipyKLo">desminti√≥ la afirmaci√≥n del movimiento anticharter de que  la "gente blanca" estaba apoder√°ndose del vecindario</a>. Otro padre escribi√≥  <a href="http://laschoolreport.com/letter-to-editor-parent-finds-zimmer-comments-offensive/">una  poderosa carta personal que fue publicada en LA School Report, reprendiendo a Zimmer por sus acusaciones raciales</a>.\nFue una llamada de atenci√≥n para Zimmer y la junta. En los siguientes d√≠as, el distrito y los l√≠deres escolares trabajaron en un plan para que Citizens of the World se mudara a dos nuevos campus en el oto√±o. Estamos orgullosos de esos padres por defenderse a s√≠ mismos y recordarle a la junta del LAUSD que las familias de las escuelas ch√°rter proceden de distintos grupos y no pueden ser encasilladas o perseguidas.</p>\n', 'Padres pregonan la diversidad en escuelas ch√°rter de LA', 'Cuando un miembro de la junta escolar de L.A. acus√≥ a los padres de las ch√°rter de esquivar la diversidad recibi√≥ una llamada de atenci√≥n.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '288-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:10', '2016-01-13 04:22:10', '', 288, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/288-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(918, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<iframe width="420" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/cAhoEipyKLo" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n\n<p>When Citizens of the World Charter School in Mar Vista opened one year ago, parents were particularly excited about the school\'s commitment to celebrate diversity. More than half of the students were non-white, and many of the parents were immigrants - which mirrored the neighborhood demographics.\nSo parents were shocked when a small group of anti-charter activists stirred up opposition to the school, based on the idea that it wasn\'t reflective of the community. Then, parents felt attacked when they read <a href="http://laschoolreport.com/zimmer-lausd-culture-war-over-co-locations-on-the-west-side/">public statements by their own school board member, Steve Zimmer, accusing them of shunning diversity</a>.\nTo make matters worse, an administrative error prompted L.A. Unified to prevent the school from remaining in its current location. Students were suddenly without a home for the following school year.\nSo did Citizens of the World parents accept this difficult turn of events? Nope. They stood up for their school and their families. They packed an LAUSD board meeting and testified. Board member Zimmer was confronted with a truly diverse and passionate group of parents who painted a very different picture of their school.\nA dad, who years ago graduated from LAUSD, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_FNMVFQ6bHI">said he chose Citizens of the World precisely because the school embraced diversity</a>; a mom <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qxOxD63X5Ro">shared her daughter\'s tremendous academic progress</a> during the past year; another mom <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cAhoEipyKLo">disproved the anti-charter rallying cry that "white people" were taking over the neighborhood</a>. Another parent wrote a <a href="http://laschoolreport.com/letter-to-editor-parent-finds-zimmer-comments-offensive/">powerful, personal letter that was published on LA School Report, chiding Zimmer for his race-based accusations</a>.\nIt was a wake up call to Zimmer and the board. In the days that followed, the district and school leaders worked out a plan for Citizens of the World to move to two new campuses in the fall. We\'re proud of these parents for defending themselves and reminding the LAUSD board that charter school families come from all walks of life and cannot be pigeonholed or persecuted.</p>\n', 'Parents Tout Diversity at LA Charter School', 'When an L.A. school board member accused charter parents of shunning diversity, he got a wake up call.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '287-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 287, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/287-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(919, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<p><figure class="figure-full figure-border"></p>\n\n<div data-picture data-alt="Tyler_Whitmire.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)"><div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/twhitmire@calcharters.org-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-385xauto-4924.jpg"></div><div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/twhitmire@calcharters.org-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-612xauto-4924.jpg" data-media="(min-width: 481px)"></div><noscript><img src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/twhitmire@calcharters.org-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-385xauto-4924.jpg" alt="Tyler_Whitmire.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" /></noscript></div>\n\n<p></figure>\nTyler Whitmire joined California Charter Schools Association in November 2013 as Organizing Director. In this important role supporting charter school advocacy, Tyler oversees a team of Parent Organizers in California\'s charter school regions. Their goal is to help charter school parents become advocates for education and school choice.\nTyler is a strong supporter of the charter school movement and assuring California students have the opportunity to attend college. She has a holistic approach to organizing work and focuses her time on prioritizing the issues CCSA and the parents focus on, as well as write communication plans and designs onboarding training for parent organizers. Her work with the organizing program includes hiring and training new members of the organizing team, working with local staff to write and execute campaign plans, and overseeing the growth and issues of the entire organizing program. Meeting charter school parents and motivating them to take action to make positive change for kids especially energizes her.\nBefore joining CCSA, Tyler worked for Stand for Children for more than five years where she was a community organizer and Director of Organizing in Portland, Oregon. She also developed and launched Stand University for Parents where she developed family engagement programs in Chicago, Phoenix and Memphis. Tyler helped more than 2,000 parents graduate from the Stand University for Parents.\nTyler comes from a family that believed in the importance of education. Her own parents moved frequently in order for Tyler and her siblings to learn in the best possible public and private schools. This motivated her to make sure that choice and access to quality education was not dependent on where a family physically resides.\nWhen she is not advocating for public education, Tyler enjoys backpacking, camping and spending time outdoors with her husband and dog. She lives in Davis, California.</p>\n', 'Meet Our Team: Tyler Whitmire', 'The Organizing Director for CCSA has worked to enhance parent engagement across the country.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '286-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 286, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/286-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(920, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<p><em>The following two stories of \'14 graduates come to us from the Altus Network of Charter Schools:</em>\nThis time of year, graduation ceremonies across California celebrate student achievement. This important milestone serves as a rite of passage for every student receiving a diploma. For a young lady named Adriana, this year\'s graduation ceremony will hold an even deeper meaning.\nWhen Adriana walks across the stage at The Charter School of San Diego\'s 2014 graduation, it will be a momentous event. She will be the first person in her immediate family to graduate from high school.\nAdriana says, considering the neighborhood she comes from, her life is fairly average. In her community it\'s more likely to know someone who is incarcerated than someone planning to attend a college or university. Adriana lives in an environment where it is common to lose loved ones to violence. Adriana said that people who live in her neighborhood don\'t really have a focus on education. "They live everyday life not thinking about tomorrow." Weary of the instability of her home life, Adriana promised herself that she would break the cycle. "I want a career. I want to be secure and stable ... My environment has given me the drive to want to excel in everything I pursue," she said.\n"One of the hardest things in my life is my father being incarcerated," she said. "He isn\'t here to see me graduate this month, and he isn\'t going to see me graduate college. He wasn\'t the one to teach me how to drive like I had always envisioned growing up. I miss him in everyday life just as much as I will during special occasions." Among other hardships, Adriana has mourned the loss of another person in her life. "Just recently, my mother\'s boyfriend passed away," she said. "It\'s just hard trying to deal with the unknown. You just have to live life positively and hope for the best outcome that you can."\nAdriana\'s previous high school, which she attended for her freshman and sophomore years, still holds a special place in her heart. "I learned a lot there, academically, and outside of the school curriculum as well. I met a few teachers there who became like a second family to me," she said. "Some of my teachers really treated me as a person, not just another kid on their morning attendance call list." She was on a special track for students interested in social justice.\nUnfortunately, Adriana\'s satisfaction was short-lived. The administration started changing school policies, removing the special career tracks and instituting more restrictive guidelines. "I never cared for the student population there," Adriana said, "but the staff and way of teaching I respected dearly." Unhappy with the new changes, Adriana decided to choose a new path for herself and enrolled at The Charter School of San Diego (CSSD).\nAdriana\'s first teacher at CSSD, Mr. Domingo Agnas, gave her the freedom to pursue her own educational goals. "He was very inviting and helpful. He allowed me to have a voice in what I wanted out of CSSD," she said. Her second and most recent teacher, Mrs. Sandee Drake, made a significant impact on her future. Mrs. Drake is the one Adriana credits for her path to a four-year university. "She made me think of ideas not yet really thought of before," said Adriana. "I wanted to go to a community college after graduation, and then transfer to a university when I finished my general education. But when I became a student of Mrs. Drake, she pushed me to want more for myself. She saw the potential that I didn\'t really see in myself." Mrs. Drake had seen Adriana\'s transcripts, noting good grades and a strong work ethic. She encouraged Adriana to apply, "just to see what happens." In spite of her family background, Adriana stayed positive about the process. "I told myself that I would just make it possible."\n"Mrs. Drake thought a four-year university would be better for me ... to get that whole life experience," Adriana said. "I just decided to try something new." Without having an opportunity for school choice or the influence of Mr. Agnas and Mrs. Drake, Adriana may have taken a very different path.\nMrs. Drake is incredibly proud of Adriana\'s accomplishments. "She had a goal and she went after it," she said. "She fought through it - she didn\'t let things get in her way. Wherever that drive came from, it\'s amazing. It was great seeing her be such an inspiration to others, too."\nAdriana will be starting at University of California Riverside (UCR) this fall where she plans to major in psychology. She hopes to prepare for a career in social work. While Adriana has never lived outside of San Diego, she is eager to see what opportunities await her in the future. She knows that the rigorous college courses she\'s enrolled in will not be easy. But Adriana has an optimistic spirit. "I don\'t mind a challenge," she said. Her admission into UCR tops the list of her proudest achievements. "My greatest accomplishment so far has been getting accepted into 5 prestigious universities. I am completely amazed by this." Adriana was also accepted to CSU Long Beach, CSU Northridge, San Francisco State University, and San Diego State University.\n"My family is pretty proud of me," said Adriana. "I\'m so glad that Mrs. Drake pushed me to want more for myself because now I\'m doing what is best for me. I never in my wildest dreams thought that I would be able to accomplish something so outstanding."\n<figure class="figure-full figure-border"></p>\n\n<div data-picture data-alt="Adriana - Altus graduation.jpeg (Entry/Page Lead Image)"><div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/Ashlee - Altus graduation-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-385xauto-4914.jpg"></div><div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/Ashlee - Altus graduation-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-612xauto-4914.jpg" data-media="(min-width: 481px)"></div><noscript><img src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/Ashlee - Altus graduation-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-385xauto-4914.jpg" alt="Adriana - Altus graduation.jpeg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" /></noscript></div>\n\n<p class="caption">Adriana, 2014 graduate of the Charter School of San Diego (Altus Network of Charter Schools).</p>\n\n<p></figure>\nMeanwhile, at Audeo Charter School, an academic intervention program that primarily serves at-risk students, the graduation ceremony carries a special meaning. Many of its students have worked way beyond the norm to overcome what sometimes seem like insurmountable obstacles.\nAshlee is one of these students. Ashlee is bright, motivated, and determined to succeed despite her challenging background.\n"I\'ve been in the system for about eight years, going on nine," she said. Ashlee, 17 years old, is referring to the California Foster Care system.\nAshlee moved in with her foster mother, Bobbie Jo, about a year ago. She attended elementary school while she was still living with her biological mother and father. She attended a multitude of middle schools when she entered the foster care system.\n"I lived in a restrictive group home for four years," she explained. There was a school on site. It wasn\'t until she moved in with Bobbie Jo for her senior year and enrolled at Audeo Charter School that she realized the classes at her previous school were not preparing her for her future.\nAshlee\'s entrance credit audit at Audeo showed a 3.6 GPA, but the classes she had taken were not accredited. This would prove to be a major obstacle in her acceptance at a 4-year university. After the initial meeting with Audeo\'s staff, Bobbie Jo said the mood was grim. "I think we were all in shock," she said.\nAshlee\'s previous school was designed specifically for foster youth in group homes to encourage the youth to continue their education. "We didn\'t understand how this could happen," Ashlee said, "but I wasn\'t going to let it stop me. I was still going to go to a 4-year university." Fueled by determination, Ashlee and Bobbie Jo partnered with Audeo\'s teachers and staff to get Ashlee where she was resolved to go - a four-year university.\nThe Audeo staff created two optional educational plans for Ashlee. One track was designed for attending a four-year university, but this would involve retaking most of the core courses she had completed at her previous school. The second option was designed for attending a two-year program then transferring to a four-year university. Ashlee insisted on preparing for a four-year university.\nAshlee had a difficult road ahead of her.  Her previous school had little-to-no homework. For the first time in her life, Ashlee had to buckle down and deal with the rigor of her courses. "Ashlee\'s first teacher at Audeo, Ms. Jennifer Szohr, was sending me updates every Friday," Bobbie Jo said. "Ashlee was struggling. She had never had a high school experience."\nBut through it all, with the support of Audeo\'s teachers who are specially trained to move students forward academically, Ashlee made amazing progress. Even though she felt overwhelmed by the new pressures of schoolwork, Bobbie Jo was championing her success from the first moment. "I like to show her, \'Look, look what you\'ve already accomplished,\'" said Bobbie Jo. The day school at the group home was not challenging, Bobbie Jo said, and in no way could prepare Ashlee for the shock of dealing with a college curriculum. Audeo\'s course of study was rigorous, but the classroom gave Ashlee all the support she needed.\nThis June, Ashlee is graduating on time with the rest of her class. She will be attending California State University San Marcos in the fall. Her college acceptance is her proudest accomplishment to date. Ashlee is modest about her success. She gives credit to the phenomenal support system she has built around her. "This school provided me with everything I needed to graduate and go to a four-year," she said of Audeo Charter School. "And my teachers have been great -very caring and helpful."\nAshlee also credits the close group of trusted adults who have helped keep her in school. They have helped her remain on-track. Bobbie Jo, in particular, has been there for Ashlee in a way she has never experienced. "Actually living with someone," Ashlee said, "getting that \'Mom\' experience... I\'ve never had that."\nAt CSU San Marcos, Ashlee said she wants to pursue a major that will assist her in her quest to become an FBI agent. She specifically wants to work in forensic psychology or in a program that helps stop human trafficking. She is motivated to pursue this career by many of her personal experiences. "I\'ve seen a lot, and I want to help." Additionally, Ashlee said she is interested in helping women advocate for themselves. She said she is lucky to have had good role models and wants to ensure other women have the same opportunities.\n"I\'m really proud of her," said Bobbie Jo. "I tell everyone I have a daughter - a foster daughter - and she\'s graduating and going to college. She takes her opportunities; she doesn\'t let them go to waste."\nAshlee\'s current teacher, Ms. Vi Nguyen echoed Bobbie Jo\'s pride. "Ashlee is a very motivated and determined individual. It has been a privilege to teach her. She\'s inspiring. I know she will make a positive impact in her community."\nAshlee is currently working personally with members of the Price family (Price Family Charitable Fund) and the San Diego County of Education to assure that other foster youth do not find themselves in a similar unfortunate situation. They are working to support her previous school in offering courses that are accepted by the University of California and California State universities systems.</p>\n', 'Celebrating Our Graduates', 'Meet Adriana and Ashlee, two \'14 graduates who make us proud.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '284-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 284, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/284-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(921, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<p>Las escuelas ch√°rter de California est√°n probando cada vez m√°s que son una fuerte alternativa a las escuelas p√∫blicas tradicionales, de acuerdo con dos reportes recientes del Center for Research on Education Outcomes (CREDO) de la Universidad de Stanford. Los datos muestran que las escuelas ch√°rter son particularmente exitosas en ayudar a estudiantes que tradicionalmente han estado marginados.\nUn reporte estatal de CREDO descubri√≥ que los estudiantes de las escuelas ch√°rter de California hicieron grandes avances en lectura que superaron a sus compa√±eros de las escuelas tradicionales. Los resultados promisorios para estudiantes de bajos ingresos se est√°n teniendo en cuenta en el estado y las escuelas ch√°rter est√°n generando semanas y meses extra de aprendizaje para estudiantes afroamericanos, latinos, aprendices de ingl√©s y con necesidades de educaci√≥n especial. El estudio midi√≥ el desempe√±o de 393,492 alumnos en 994 escuelas ch√°rter en California en un periodo de m√°s seis a√±os. <a href="http://credo.stanford.edu/pdfs/ca_report_FINAL.pdf">Lea aqu√≠ el reporte completo de CREDO.</a>\nMientras tanto, los estudiantes que asisten a las escuelas ch√°rter de Los √Ångeles superan a sus compa√±eros de las escuelas tradicionales en lectura y matem√°ticas, de acuerdo con otro reciente reporte de CREDO enfocado en L.A. Los resultados para los estudiantes hispanos de las escuelas ch√°rter, especialmente aquellos en la pobreza, son particularmente notables. Esto explica en gran parte porqu√©  la demanda de los padres por las escuelas ch√°rter en Los √Ångeles ha llevado a que se tripliquen las inscripciones en los pasados seis a√±os. <a href="http://credo.stanford.edu/pdfs/Los_Angeles_report_2014_FINAL_001.pdf">Lea aqu√≠ el reporte completo de CREDO.</a></p>\n', 'Stanford: Las escuelas ch√°rter de California superan a las escuelas tradicionales', 'Las escuelas ch√°rter de California est√°n probando cada vez m√°s que son una fuerte alternativa a las escuelas p√∫blicas tradicionales, de acuerdo con dos reportes recientes de Stanford.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '283-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 283, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/283-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(922, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<p>Yesterday dozens of charter school parents converged on a meeting of the Oakland Unified School District board. Why? To demand fair funding for charter schools.\nA parcel tax called Measure G is raising $20 million a year for public schools, but OUSD is excluding charters from that revenue. So parents and their children rallied to make sure the school board knows that unequal funding is unacceptable - and that every public school student deserves a fair share of public eduction resources, not just some.\nDo you support fair funding for charter school students? <a href="https://www.votervoice.net/CCSA/Petitions/350/Respond">Sign the petition</a>.\n<figure class="figure-full figure-border"></p>\n\n<div data-picture data-alt="Oakland_Parents_June_11_Measure G.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)"><div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/Oakland parents June 11 Measure G-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-385xauto-4910.jpg"></div><div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/Oakland parents June 11 Measure G-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-612xauto-4910.jpg" data-media="(min-width: 481px)"></div><noscript><img src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/Oakland parents June 11 Measure G-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-385xauto-4910.jpg" alt="Oakland_Parents_June_11_Measure G.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" /></noscript></div>\n\n<p></figure></p>\n', 'Oakland Parents Unite for Charter Funding', 'Dozens of Oakland parents sent a clear message to the school board: Don\'t exclude charters from public funding.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '282-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 282, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/282-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(923, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<p>The leading NPR affiliate in Southern California, KPCC, has a <a href="http://www.scpr.org/blogs/education/2014/06/02/16743/poverty-has-been-found-to-affect-kids-brains-can-o/">great piece profiling a strong L.A. charter network</a>, Camino Nuevo. The story focuses on how the school helps kids succeed, despite the traumas and challenges of poverty. It\'s the first in a series called "Teaching Through Trauma."\nWe\'re proud that schools like Camino Nuevo are using innovation and passion to reach students where they\'re at and help them overcome their biggest obstacles. <a href="http://www.scpr.org/blogs/education/2014/06/02/16743/poverty-has-been-found-to-affect-kids-brains-can-o/">Check out the KPCC story!</a>\n<figure class="figure-full figure-border"></p>\n\n<div data-picture data-alt="Camino Nuevo kids from KPCC story.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)"><div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/Camino Nuevo kids from KPCC story-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-385xauto-4906.jpg"></div><div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/Camino Nuevo kids from KPCC story-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-612xauto-4906.jpg" data-media="(min-width: 481px)"></div><noscript><img src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2014/06/Camino Nuevo kids from KPCC story-cropped-proto-ccsa_families_theme___lead-thumb-385xauto-4906.jpg" alt="Camino Nuevo kids from KPCC story.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" /></noscript></div>\n\n<p></figure></p>\n', 'Public Radio Spotlights L.A. Charter', 'KPCC looks at how an L.A. charter school is helping students prevail over poverty.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '281-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 281, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/281-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(924, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<p>We know you want your child\'s school, and all charter schools, to receive the funding they need to help our students succeed. Will you please join us in taking action to ensure that Oakland charter schools receive their fair share of funding? <a href="https://www.votervoice.net/CCSA/Petitions/350/Respond">Sign the petition here.</a>\nA parcel tax called Measure G has provided $20 million annually in education funds to Oakland Unified School District (approximately $400 per student). These are public funds meant to help ALL public school students. However, the district is not sharing the Measure G parcel tax revenue with charter public schools. Our schools and our students are being excluded. In response, this week CCSA <a href="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/OUSD_Agenda_Parcel_Tax_Item_Request.pdf">submitted a resolution to OUSD calling for fair funding for charters</a>.\nLet\'s send a message loud and clear that charter public schools, and their students, cannot be denied local parcel tax revenue such as Measure G!\nSign the petition. Tell OUSD to support ALL public school students, not just some.</p>\n', 'Oakland Parents: Demand Fair Funding for Charters', 'Your voice matters! Tell Oakland Unified to provide charter school students with their fair share of funding from local parcel tax Measure G.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '279-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 279, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/279-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(925, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<p>Your vote matters! We need you to oppose SB 1263 TODAY. This legislation would impact facilities flexibility for your children\'s schools and take away the choice to find accessible non-district options. <a href="https://www.votervoice.net/CCSA/campaigns/36174/respond"><strong>Parents Take Action to Protect Your Children\'s Schools!</strong></a></p>\n', 'Parents: Take Action NOW to Protect Your Children\'s Schools!', 'We need you to oppose SB 1263 TODAY and protect facilities choices for our schools.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '278-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 278, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/278-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(926, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<p>This month, parents in L.A. proved that they are creative and relentless, especially when it comes to protecting their children and strengthening their education. Take the parents at Alliance College-Ready Middle Academy #4 in the Florence neighborhood. After three students being picked up and dropped off were injured by passing cars, parents decided that the area needed better signage - to ensure drivers would watch out for students. The school\'s CCSA Families team collected more than 1,500 petitions and then worked with the local neighborhood council, which helped get the attention of the local city councilmember. Before long, the city had built new "school zone" - reducing speed to 25 mph - and painted a new crosswalk too.\nMeanwhile, in West Adams, parents at two small Bright Star charter schools have been working to turn a vacant building into a new school that would house all the students under one roof. But the local neighborhood council has ignored their effort. So hundreds of CCSA Families members rallied and voted for new neighborhood council candidates who\'ve pledged support for the new school. In just one day, they elected four allies to the council and re-elected a fifth. Their effort to build a new school isn\'t over yet, but group of parents just overcame a serious obstacle with tenacity and creativity.</p>\n', 'L.A. Parents Take Action for Their Children\'s Schools', 'Sometimes a new crosswalk tells a bigger story about a community\'s power to make change.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '277-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 277, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/277-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(927, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '<p>It began in Sacramento, where the Assembly\'s Education Committee voted in favor of AB 1531, a bill that defied the spirit of the charter movement by requiring districts to appoint the majority of charter school board members.\nSan Diego parents, educators and advocates knew the bill threatened the independence of charter schools. They knew it would harm more than 17,000 charter school students in San Diego Unified. And they weren\'t about to just let the bill keeping moving forward.\nSo early on a Wednesday morning last month, they rallied outside the office of a local legislator, Assemblymember Lorena Gonzalez, who\'d supported the bill. They also praised Assemblymember Shirley Weber for voting against it. The rally sparked major media coverage and put the spotlight on all of the legislators who weren\'t putting students\' interests first.\nSoon after, the bill was stopped in its tracks; it\'s currently "in suspense" and advocates are optimistic it won\'t go any further. It was a powerful reminder that there\'s no power like parent power.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="520" height="293" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/1LSJm5kOa1M" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'San Diego Parents and Educators Rally to Stop Anti-Charter Bill', 'When a San Diego Assemblymember who voted for a bill that threatened charter schools showed up for work on a Wednesday morning, she found a group of parents, educators and advocates gathered to demand a different course of action.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '276-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '2016-01-13 04:22:11', '', 276, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/276-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(928, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>California charter schools are increasingly proving to be a strong alternative to traditional public schools, according to two recent reports by Stanford University\'s Center for Research on Education Outcomes (CREDO). The data shows that charters are particularly successful at helping historically underserved students.\nA statewide report by CREDO found that charter school students across California made larger gains in reading than their peers in traditional schools. Promising results for low-income students are playing out across the state, with charter schools generating extra weeks and months of learning for African-American, Latino, EL and special education students. The study measured the performance of 393,492 students in 994 charter schools across California over a six-year period. <a href="http://credo.stanford.edu/pdfs/ca_report_FINAL.pdf">Read the full CREDO report here</a>.\nMeanwhile, students attending Los Angeles charter schools outperform their peers in traditional schools in reading and math, according to another recent CREDO report focused on L.A. Results for Hispanic charter students, especially those in poverty, are particularly notable. This explains a great deal about why parent demand for charter schools in Los Angeles has led to enrollment tripling over the past six years. <a href="http://credo.stanford.edu/pdfs/Los_Angeles_report_2014_FINAL_001.pdf">Read the full CREDO report here</a>.</p>\n', 'Stanford: California Charter Schools Outperform Traditional Schools', 'You\'ve already seen charter schools help your children thrive. The latest reports by Stanford University confirm what you already know: charters are making gains and yielding strong outcomes for students.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '275-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 275, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/275-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(929, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>Este mes, padres de familia de L.A. demostraron que son creativos e implacables, especialmente en  lo que se refiere a proteger a sus hijos y a fortalecer su educaci√≥n. Ah√≠ est√°n, por ejemplo, los padres de Alliance College-Ready Middle Academy #4 en el vecindario de Florence. Despu√©s de que tres estudiantes a los que hab√≠an dejado en la escuela resultaron heridos por los veh√≠culos que pasaban, los padres decidieron que el √°rea necesitaba una mejor se√±alizaci√≥n para asegurar que los conductores tuvieran cuidado con los alumnos. El equipo de la escuela de CCSA Families reuni√≥ m√°s de 1,500 solicitudes y luego trabaj√≥ con el concejo del vecindario, que ayud√≥ a llamar la atenci√≥n del concejal local de la ciudad. Poco despu√©s, la ciudad construy√≥ una nueva "zona escolar" en la que el l√≠mite m√°ximo de velocidad es de 25 mph y pint√≥ un nuevo cruce.\nPor su parte, en West Adams, los padres de dos peque√±as escuelas ch√°rter Bright Star han estado trabajando para transformar un edificio vacante en una nueva escuela que pudiera albergar a todos los estudiantes bajo un solo techo. Pero el concejo del vecindario local ignor√≥ su esfuerzo. Por esta raz√≥n, cientos de miembros de CCSA Families protestaron y votaron por nuevos candidatos al concejo del vecindario que han prometido apoyar la nueva escuela. En solo un d√≠a, eligieron en el concejo a cuatro aliados y reeligieron a un quinto. Su esfuerzo para construir una nueva escuela a√∫n no ha finalizado, pero el grupo de padres super√≥ un serio obst√°culo con tenacidad y creatividad.</p>\n', 'Padres de L.A. Toman Acciones Para las Escuelas de Sus Hijos', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '280-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 280, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/280-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(930, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>Maybe you were one of more than 300 school leaders, teachers, parents, and students who assembled at the state Capitol on May 7th during CCSA\'s annual Advocacy Day. If you were, you saw the power of parents and educators coming together to advocate for policies that help charter schools thrive.\nParticipants met one-on-one with their legislators to share their personal charter school stories and talk about important charter school issues. Held in celebration of National Charter Schools Week, Advocacy Day was a great opportunity to grow and demonstrate the strength of the movement by connecting the charter community with lawmakers. It was also by far the largest CCSA Advocacy Day yet.\nThank you again to everyone who attended! If you weren\'t there, we hope you can join us next year in Sacramento.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="530" height="298" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/Ib-UXJ0lvBQ" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Advocacy Day Brings Charter School Parents and Leaders to State Capitol', 'Did you know that as a charter school parent, you can meet with your legislator face to face to talk about issues affecting your school? That\'s what Advocacy Day is all about.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '274-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 274, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/274-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(931, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>Approximately 350 people turned out for the <strong>CCSA Families LAUSD Board District Candidate Forum</strong>, held on Wednesday evening at Los Angeles\' Mt. Moriah Baptist Church. The forum featured four candidates vying for the Los Angeles Unified School District, Board District 1 seat. Speaking to Los Angeles-area charter school leaders, parents, teachers and others, the candidates addressed a number of issues affecting the charter school community, including support for LAUSD Superintendent John Deasy, support for the expansion of charter schools, and facilities and funding equity for charter schools.\n<a href="https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.816780378350372.1073741838.276454839049598&amp;type=3"><strong>See pictures of the Candidate Forum.</strong></a>\nWatch the entire Candidate Forum now!</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="450" height="253" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/TkPMH9aoMlg" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>The special election will coincide with the June 3 Statewide Primary Election, which is rapidly approaching. A lot is at stake in this election for our charter schools at both the state and local levels. A run-off will ensue if no one candidate captures 50%+1 of the vote. Visit the website of our sister organization, CCSA Advocates, to learn more about election issues and candidates\' positions.\nCandidates who attended included:\n- Genethia Hudley-Hayes\n- Alex Johnson\n- Rachel Johnson\n- George McKenna\nOmarosa Manigault was unable to attend due to illness, and Sherlett Hendy-Newbill and Hattie McFrazier were invited but did not attend.\n<strong>News coverage of the Candidate Forum</strong>\n- <a href="http://laschoolreport.com/mckenna-leading-school-board-race-john-deasy-lausd/">McKenna, leading in school board race, won\'t commit on Deasy</a>\n- <a href="http://laschoolreport.com/lausd-candidates-agree-on-value-of-public-charter-schools/">LAUSD candidates agree (!) on value of public charter schools</a></p>\n', 'Large Turnout for LAUSD BD 1 Candidate Forum', 'Hundreds of parents packed a South L.A. church to meet the candidates running for the LAUSD board district 1 seat, in an important special election being held June 3rd.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '271-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 271, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/271-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(932, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<h3>Reserve la fecha! Mi√©rcoles, 14 de mayo 2014</h3>\n\n<p>Siete miembros de la Junta Directiva Escolar del Distrito Escolar Unificado de Los √Ångeles toman decisiones cada d√≠a sobre el futuro de su hijo. Y en este momento, la mayor√≠a de estos miembros de la Junta escolar se enfocan m√°s en mantener escuelas excelentes fuera del alcance de nuestros hijos que en asegurar que todos nuestros ni√±os reciban una educaci√≥n excelente.\nEste mes de junio hay una elecci√≥n para la Junta Escolar del Distrito 1 que podr√≠a cambiar la din√°mica de la Junta a favor de los ni√±os y las escuelas, y no a los intereses especiales.\n¬øPuede usted participar con nosotros en un <a href="http://ccsa.nationbuilder.com/bd1forum_esp">Foro de Candidatos</a>, el mi√©rcoles 14 de mayo, para conocer a cinco de los candidatos confirmados y escuchar sus respuestas a las preguntas de nuestra comunidad acerca de su apoyo de excelentes escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter?\n¬øCu√°l candidato luchar√° m√°s a favor de  escuelas excelentes en cada c√≥digo postal? ¬øCu√°l candidato va a representar a los ni√±os y los padres, no lo mismo de siempre? ¬øCu√°l candidato apoyar√° maestros  excelentes en las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter y las escuelas p√∫blicas tradicionales por igual?\nTodo depende de nosotros. √önase a nuestro Foro el 14 de mayo.\n<a href="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/LAUSD%20BD%201%20Candidate%20Forum%20Flyer%20%28Spanish%29.pdf">Descargue el folleto para el evento.</a>\n<a href="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/LAUSD_BD1_Brochure_SPA_Web_FNL.pdf">Descargue el folleto con las declaraciones de los candidatos.</a>\n<strong>Evento</strong>\nForo de Candidatos para representar el Distrito 1 en la Junta Directiva del Distrito Escolar Unificado de Los √Ångeles\nCandidatos confirmados:\n- Genethia Hudley Hayes\n- Alex Martin Johnson\n- Rachel C. Johnson\n- Omarosa O. Manigault\n- George J. McKenna, III\n<strong>Fecha</strong>\nMi√©rcoles14 de Mayo del