(933, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>Hay gran cantidad de informaci√≥n p√∫blica sobre nuestras escuelas p√∫blicas, desde los resultados de las pruebas hasta las tasas de graduaci√≥n y el n√∫mero de alumnos por maestro. ¬øPero cu√°l es el dato m√°s importante? ¬øQu√© preguntas deben hacer los padres?\nCreemos que los padres saben mejor que nadie cu√°l es la mejor escuela para sus hijos. Tambi√©n creemos que ellos merecen tener la informaci√≥n que necesitan para ver cu√°l es el desempe√±o de las escuelas locales. Ya sea que usted est√© buscando una escuela para su hijo o tratando de encontrar informaci√≥n sobre su actual escuela ch√°rter, esta gu√≠a le ayudar√° a encontrar y entender algunos de los datos m√°s importantes sobre las escuelas.\nLa informaci√≥n sobre las escuelas es particularmente importante para cuando su escuela est√°:\n- Reclutando a nuevos estudiantes\n- Buscando el permiso de renovaci√≥n\n- Solicitando un permiso para abrir una escuela adicional o para ampliarse y servir a estudiantes de m√°s grados\n- Tratando de contactar a funcionarios electos, medios de comunicaci√≥n o a la comunidad para compartir el √©xito de su escuela\nMostrar los resultados positivos acad√©micos puede ayudarle a contar la historia de su escuela.</p>\n\n<h2>¬øQu√© deben buscar los padres?</h2>\n\n<p>Aun cuando tengo gran cantidad de informaci√≥n sobre una escuela, ¬øc√≥mo puedo saber si est√° haciendo un buen trabajo? ¬øCu√°les son las estad√≠sticas que realmente importan?\nHay aqu√≠ algunas preguntas claves que se tienen que hacer:</p>\n\n<h3>¬øEst√° la escuela cumpliendo con sus metas acad√©micas?</h3>\n\n<p><a href="http://www.cde.ca.gov/ta/ac/ap/">El √çndice de Desempe√±o Acad√©mico (API)</a> es el principal indicador de las escuelas p√∫blicas de California incluyendo las escuelas ch√°rter. El API se basa en muchas cosas diferentes, entre ellas los resultados de las pruebas de los estudiantes,  la asistencia de √©stos y la participaci√≥n de los padres. La meta para todas las escuelas p√∫blicas de California es tener un API de 800. Se recomienda de manera especial que si el API de su escuela es menor de 700, le pregunte al director qu√© piensa hacer para mejorarlo y rastrear si el API de su escuela va hacia abajo o hacia arriba cada a√±o.\nUsted puede haber o√≠do que California se cambiar√° a un nuevo sistema de ex√°menes estatales para estudiantes en el a√±o escolar 2015 como parte de la transici√≥n a la Common Core y ha dejado de dar la mayor√≠a de los ex√°menes CST de 2014. El estado a√∫n no ha informado c√≥mo se utilizar√° los nuevos ex√°menes para determinar el rendimiento de las escuelas en comparaci√≥n con otras escuelas en el estado. <a href="/2013/10/que-es-common-core-recursos-para-padres.html">Aprenda m√°s sobre Common Core y mant√©nganse al d√≠a con lo √∫ltimo en lo que significa para su escuela.</a></p>\n\n<h3>¬øC√≥mo se compara su escuela con otras?</h3>\n\n<p>En su vecindario, es posible que haya una mezcla de escuelas - escuelas ch√°rter, escuelas tradicionales de distrito y escuelas privadas. Podr√≠a haber tambi√©n escuelas magnet o escuelas alternativas. Busque la misma informaci√≥n para m√∫ltiples escuelas para ver c√≥mo se compara una escuela con:\n- Otras escuelas en el mismo vecindario\n- Escuelas que atienden a estudiantes similares\nLa Asociaci√≥n de las Escuelas Ch√°rter de California ha creado la Medida de Estudiantes Similares para que el p√∫blico pueda comparar c√≥mo se desempe√±a una escuela con otra que atiende a estudiantes similares, ya sea en base a su ingreso familiar, etnicidad, niveles de educaci√≥n de los padres y la forma en que muchos estudiantes aprenden el ingl√©s como segundo idioma.\n- <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/advocacy/accountability/portraitofthemovement/ssm-map.html">Use este mapa para ver c√≥mo se comparan las escuelas en su vecindario.</a>\n<a href="http://www.greatschools.org">GreatSchools - "Buenas escuelas"</a> hace m√°s f√°cil encontrar una lista de escuelas en su √°rea. Tambi√©n tienen una escala de 10-puntos para comparar escuelas en cuanto a su desempe√±o acad√©mico y para permitir que los padres califiquen las escuelas en base a su experiencia personal.</p>\n\n<h3>¬øSe est√°n graduando los estudiantes y est√°n preparados para ir a la universidad?</h3>\n\n<p>El primer paso es checar la tasa de graduaci√≥n de su escuela para asegurarse que la mayor√≠a de los estudiantes se est√° graduando. El segundo paso es ver si los estudiantes est√°n preparados para tener √©xito en la universidad.\nPara ser admitido en una universidad del estado de California - University of California (UC) o California State University (CSU) -  los estudiantes deben completar los requisitos A-G, que son una serie de clases de preparatoria o high school, con un promedio de C, por lo menos. Aunque los estudiantes aprueben suficientes materias para graduarse de la high school, si no completan las clases A-G, no pueden ir directamente a una universidad estatal de cuatro a√±os. Las escuelas deben reportar cu√°ntos estudiantes completaron los cursos A-G.</p>\n\n<h3>Otros recursos</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/2011/03/que-es-una-escuela-charter-1.html">Hoja de datos: C√≥mo escoger la escuela correcta para su hijo</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>C√≥mo usar la informaci√≥n para defender su escuela</h2>\n\n<p>A las escuelas ch√°rter se les piden cuentas en muchas formas. Como son escuelas de elecci√≥n, son llamadas a rendir cuentas por los padres que deciden si quieren inscribir ah√≠ a sus hijos y que pueden cambiar a sus hijos a otra escuela si no est√°n contentos. Tambi√©n tienen que rendir cuentas ante su autorizador.  Todas las escuelas ch√°rter empiezan con una petici√≥n, que es un plan detallado de la escuela en el que se incluyen promesas a la comunidad acerca de  lo que la escuela ofrecer√°. La petici√≥n debe ser aprobada por un autorizador, que es usualmente el distrito escolar local, algunas veces es la oficina de educaci√≥n del condado o la Junta de Educaci√≥n del Estado.\nCada cinco a√±os, el autorizador decide si renueva el permiso de la escuela ch√°rter. Si la escuela no obtiene la renovaci√≥n, debe cerrar sus puertas. El periodo de renovaci√≥n es un tiempo importante para compartir la  historia de su escuela e incluir los datos positivos del desempe√±o de la escuela.\n- <a href="/2013/07/una-guia-para-los-padres-como-defender-la-solicitud-de-renovacion-de-su-escuela-charter.html">Gu√≠a para los Padres para Defender el Permiso de Renovaci√≥n de su Escuela</a></p>\n\n<h3>Principales consejos para compartir informaci√≥n</h3>\n\n<h4>Menos es m√°s - Enf√≥quese en lo que es m√°s importante</h4>\n\n<p>Probablemente su escuela es admirable y usted quiere compartir todas las estad√≠sticas impresionantes, desde los resultados de las pruebas hasta las tasas de graduaci√≥n y los porcentajes de aceptaci√≥n en la universidad. Ya sea que usted vaya a hacer una presentaci√≥n ante la junta escolar o un volante para padres potencialmente interesados, elija s√≥lo unas cuantas estad√≠sticas para presentar sus argumentos.</p>\n\n<h4>Utilice un lenguaje simple</h4>\n\n<p>API, CST, AYP...¬°Hay muchas abreviaciones y palabras confusas en el mundo de la educaci√≥n! Aunque usted se est√© convirtiendo r√°pidamente en un experto en informaci√≥n educativa, aseg√∫rese de explicar la informaci√≥n de su escuela de manera que los dem√°s puedan entenderla.\nPor ejemplo, en lugar de decir: "Nuestra escuela tiene un API de 840 y 80% de los estudiantes son competentes o tienen un promedio mayor en Lenguaje de Ingl√©s", puede decir: "Estamos muy entusiasmados porque nuestra escuela tiene una calificaci√≥n API de 840, arriba de la meta del estado, que es de 800. Tambi√©n, el 80 % de nuestros estudiantes tiene un nivel adecuado de lectura".</p>\n\n<h4>Sea veraz</h4>\n\n<p>Su escuela podr√≠a estar haciendo muy buen trabajo en algunas √°reas, pero necesita mejorar en otras. Sea honesto acerca de c√≥mo se est√° desempe√±ando su escuela y comparta los planes para mantener el mejoramiento. Esto es de particular importancia cuando usted est√° presentando la informaci√≥n a los autorizadores.</p>\n\n<h4>Relate una historia</h4>\n\n<p>Como humanos, aprendemos y nos comunicamos a trav√©s de historias. Es nuestra naturaleza. Usted tendr√° m√°s impacto si comparte una historia real de un estudiante en lugar de 20 estad√≠sticas acerca de su escuela. Use ambas e incluya no s√≥lo el "qui√©n" y el "qu√©" sino tambi√©n el "por qu√©" y el "c√≥mo".\nSi su escuela est√° creciendo a pasos agigantados cada a√±o, d√≠gale a la gente lo que ustedes est√°n haciendo para tener √©xito. Si se est√°n graduando muchos estudiantes, d√≠gales qui√©n fue el primero en su familia en ir a la universidad, incluya un estudiante en su presentaci√≥n y d√©jelo que hable acerca de c√≥mo su escuela tuvo un impacto en su vida.</p>\n\n<h2>D√≥nde encontrar informaci√≥n de la escuela</h2>\n\n<h3>CCSA Tarjeta del Reporte de la Responsabilidad Acad√©mica</h3>\n\n<p>California Charter Schools Association (CCSA) ha creado una serie de reportes f√°ciles de usar para ayudar al p√∫blico a entender de manera m√°s profunda el desempe√±o de las escuelas p√∫blicas ch√°rter de California. Usted puede ver la informaci√≥n acad√©mica detallada de cualquier escuela ch√°rter y puede sacar un reporte instant√°nea de m√∫ltiples escuelas en la misma regi√≥n.\n- <a href="http://snapshots.ccsa.org/">View los Reportes Instant√°neas</a></p>\n\n<h3>Informe Escolar de Rendici√≥n de Cuentas (SARC)</h3>\n\n<p>Todas las escuelas p√∫blicas de California tienen que ofrecer cada a√±o informaci√≥n a la comunidad para que el p√∫blico pueda comparar el aprovechamiento de los estudiantes, el ambiente, los recursos y la demograf√≠a. Usted puede pedir una copia del reporte de su escuela en la oficina escolar; esta informaci√≥n tambi√©n debe estar en la p√°gina web de la escuela. <a href="http://www.cde.ca.gov/ls/pf/c11/documents/parentguide2011-12spa.pdf">Muchas escuelas tambi√©n tienen un enlace con la p√°gina web del Departamento de Educaci√≥n de California, que incluye una gu√≠a para padres.</a></p>\n\n<h3>Tablero de Desempe√±o Escolar de USC</h3>\n\n<p>Investigadores de la Universidad del Sur de California <a href="http://www.usc.edu/dept/education/cegov/products/csi-interactive/index.html#">califican a todas las escuelas ch√°rter de California en base a 12 medidas</a> entre ellas recursos financieros, calidad de la escuela, desempe√±o de los estudiantes y productividad acad√©mica y nombran a las 10  mejores escuelas ch√°rter cada a√±o.</p>\n\n<h3>B√∫squeda de Datos del Departamento de Educaci√≥n de California (CDE)</h3>\n\n<p>El CDE tiene gran cantidad de informaci√≥n sobre escuelas en su p√°gina web.\n- <a href="http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/">Acceso al sistema total de b√∫squeda de datos</a>\n- Visite la "<a href="http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/DQP.asp">P√°gina de Padres</a>."</p>\n', 'Gu√≠a para los Padres Sobre C√≥mo Entender y Usar la Informaci√≥n de Escuelas', 'Hay gran cantidad de informaci√≥n p√∫blica sobre nuestras escuelas p√∫blicas, desde los resultados de las pruebas hasta las tasas de graduaci√≥n y el n√∫mero de alumnos por maestro. ¬øPero cu√°l es el dato m√°s importante? ¬øQu√© preguntas deben hacer los padres?\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '270-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 270, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/270-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(934, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>President Barack Obama is inviting K-12 students to participate in the first White House Student Film Festival, whose finalists will have their short films shown at the White House. Films must be 3 minutes or less in length and uploaded onto <a href="http://www.youtube.com">YouTube</a> or <a href="http://www.vimeo.com/">Vimeo</a>. Students should address how they currently use technology in their classrooms or the role technology will play in education in the future. Submissions must have been created on or after November 25, 2013, and are due by January 29, 2014.\n<a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/filmfestival">Learn more about how to enter. </a></p>\n', 'External Opportunity: Deadline Jan. 29 for the White House Student Film Festival', 'President Barack Obama is inviting K-12 students to participate in the first White House Student Film Festival, whose films must focus on technology in education.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '269-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 269, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/269-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(935, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>The California Charter Schools Association has published a new in-depth fact sheet for parents about how charter schools serve students with special needs.\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2010/11/charter-schools-and-special-education-frequently-asked-questions-and-answers-for-families.html">Read "Charter Schools and Special Education: FAQs for Families."</a></p>\n', 'Charter Schools and Special Education: FAQs for Families', 'Check out the new fact sheet!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '268-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 268, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/268-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(936, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>La Asociaci√≥n de Escuelas Ch√°rter de California (CCSA) ha publicado una nueva hoja informativa para las familias sobre como las escuelas ch√°rter sirven a los estudiantes con necesidades especiales.\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2013/12/escuelas-charter-y-educacion-especial-preguntas-y-respuestas-para-familias.html">Lea "Escuelas Ch√°rter y Educaci√≥n Especial."</a></p>\n', 'Escuelas Ch√°rter y Educaci√≥n Especial: Preguntas y Respuestas para Familias', 'Lea la nueva hoja informativa\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '267-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 267, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/267-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(937, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>There is lots of public data about our public schools from test scores to graduation rates to teacher-pupil ratios. But what data is the most important? What questions should parents ask?\nWe believe parents know best what school is the right fit for their children. We also believe they deserve to have the data they need to see how their local schools are doing. Whether you are looking for a school for your child or trying to find information about your current charter school, this guide helps walk you through some of the most useful school data and where to find it.\nSchool data is particularly important for advocacy when your school is:\n- Recruiting for new students\n- Going up for renewal\n- Putting in a new petition to open an additional school or to expand to serve more grades\n- Reaching out to elected officials, the media or the community to share your school\'s success\nShowing your school\'s positive results can help you tell your story.</p>\n\n<h2>What should parents look for?</h2>\n\n<p>Even if I have lots and lots of data about a school, how do I know it\'s doing a good job? What statistics really matter?\nHere are some key questions to ask:</p>\n\n<h3>Is the school meeting its academic goals?</h3>\n\n<p>The <a href="http://www.cde.ca.gov/ta/ac/ap/">Academic Performance Index (API)</a> is the main measure for California public schools, including charter schools. The API is based off many different things, including student test scores, attendance and parent involvement. The goal is for every California public school is an 800 API. Especially if your school\'s API is lower than 700, ask your principal how they plan to improve and track whether your school\'s API is going up or down each year.\nYou may have heard that California will be moving to a new testing system in the 2015 school year as part of the transition to Common Core and has stopped much of the CST testing for 2014. The state has not yet reported how the new testing will be used to determine a school\'s performance compared to other schools in the state. <a href="/2013/10/what-is-common-core-resources-for-parents.html">Learn more about Common Core and keep up with the latest on what it means for your school.</a></p>\n\n<h3>How does the school compare to other schools?</h3>\n\n<p>In your neighborhood, there are likely a mix of schools - charter schools, traditional district schools and private schools. There might also be magnet schools or alternative schools. Look at the same data for multiple schools to see how a school compares to:\n- Other schools in the same neighborhood\n- Schools serving similar students\nThe California Charter Schools Association has created the Similar Students Measure so that the public can compare how a school performs compared to another school serving students that are similar - whether based on family income, ethnicity, parent education levels and how many students are learning English as a second language.\n- <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/advocacy/accountability/portraitofthemovement/ssm-map.html">Use this map to see how schools in your neighborhood compare.</a>\n<a href="http://www.greatschools.org">Great Schools</a> makes it easy to find a list of schools in your area. They also have a 10-point scale for comparing schools on academic performance and allow parents to rate schools based on their personal experience.</p>\n\n<h3>Are students graduating and are they prepared for college?</h3>\n\n<p>The first step is to check the graduation rate at your school to make sure that the majority of students are graduating. The second step is to see whether students are prepared for success in college.\nIn order to be admitted to a University of California campus or a California State University, students must complete the A-G requirements -  a series of high school classes - with an average of C or better. Students might pass enough classes to graduate from high school, but if they don\'t complete A-G, they can\'t go directly to a 4-year state university. Schools must report how many students complete A-G.</p>\n\n<h3>Other Resources</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://www.ccsa.org/understanding/families/">Fact Sheet: How to Choose the Right School for Your Child</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>How to Use Data to Advocate for Your School</h2>\n\n<p>Charter schools are held accountable in many ways. As schools of choice, they are held accountable by parents who decide whether they want to enroll their children and who can switch to another school if they aren\'t happy. They are also held accountable by their authorizer. Every charter school starts with a petition - a detailed plan for the school including promises to the community about what the school will achieve. The petition must be approved by an authorizer - usually the local school district, sometimes the county office of education or the State Board of Education.\nEvery five years, the authorizer decides whether to renew the charter school. If the school isn\'t renewed, it must close. Renewal is an important time to share the story of your school, including the positive data that shows how your school is doing.\n- <a href="/2013/07/a-parents-guide-to-advocating-for-your-charter-schools-renewal.html">A Parent\'s Guide to Advocating for Your School\'s Renewal</a></p>\n\n<h3>Top Tips for Sharing Data</h3>\n\n<h4>Less is more - Focus on what matters most</h4>\n\n<p>Maybe your school is absolutely amazing and you want to share all the great statistics - from test scores to graduation rates to college acceptance. Whether you are presenting to the school board or making a flyer for prospective parents, choose just a few statistics to make your point.</p>\n\n<h4>Put it in plain English</h4>\n\n<p>API, CST, AYP, program improvement...There are lots of confusing abbreviations and words in the education world! Even though you are quickly becoming an expert on school data, make sure you explain your school\'s data in ways that others can understand.\nFor example, instead of saying: "Our school has an API of 840 and 80% of students are proficient or above in English Language Arts," you could say "We are excited to say that our school has an API score of 840, above the state-wide goal of 800. Also, 80 percent of our students are reading at grade level!"</p>\n\n<h4>Be truthful</h4>\n\n<p>Your school might be doing very well on some goals, but have room to improve in other areas. Be truthful about how your school is currently doing and share what you plan to do to keep improving. This is particularly important when you are presenting information to authorizers.</p>\n\n<h4>Tell a story</h4>\n\n<p>As humans, we learn and communicate through stories. It\'s our nature. You will have more impact sharing the real story of a student than twenty statistics about your school. Use both and include not only the "who" and "what", but the "why" and "how."\nIf your school is growing by leaps and bounds each year, tell people what you\'re doing that is working. If you are graduating many students who are the first in their family to go to college, include a student in your presentation and have him or her talk about how your school made an impact.</p>\n\n<h2>Where to Find School Data</h2>\n\n<h3>CCSA Academic Accountability Report Card</h3>\n\n<p>The California Charter Schools Association (CCSA) has created a series of easy-to-use reports to help the public more deeply understand the performance of California charter schools. You can see detailed academic information about any charter school and you can pull a Snapshot with multiple schools in the same region.\n- <a href="http://snapshots.ccsa.org/">View the Snapshots.</a></p>\n\n<h3>School Accountability Report Card (SARC)</h3>\n\n<p>All California public schools are required to provide information to the community every year so that the public can compare schools for student achievement, environment, resources and demographics. You can ask for a copy of your school\'s report card at the school office and it should also be posted on the school website. <a href="http://www.cde.ca.gov/ta/ac/sa/">Many are also linked on the California Department of Education web page, which also includes a parent guide.</a></p>\n\n<h3>USC School Performance Dashboard</h3>\n\n<p>Researchers at the University of Southern California <a href="http://www.usc.edu/dept/education/cegov/products/csi-interactive/index.html#">rate all California charter schools on 12 measures</a> including financial resources, school quality, student performance; and academic productivity and name the top 10 charter schools each year.</p>\n\n<h3>California Department of Education (CDE) Dataquest</h3>\n\n<p>The CDE has lots and lots of data about schools on its website.\n- <a href="http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/">Access the full Dataquest system.</a>\n- Visit the "<a href="http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/DQP.asp">Parents\' Page</a>."</p>\n', 'A Parent\'s Guide to Understanding and Using School Data', 'There is lots of public data about our public schools from test scores to graduation rates to teacher-pupil ratios. But what data is the most important? What questions should parents ask?\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '266-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 266, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/266-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(938, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '<p>On Wednesday, December 11th, from 6-8pm at the CA African American Museum, ExED and Families That Can are co-sponsoring an event for South LA parents and community members featuring Dr. Howard Fuller, one of our nation\'s most inspiring and provocative speakers on educational excellence.\nIn addition to a passionate, amazing speaker, there will be a school resource fair. Over 25 LAUSD pilot and magnet schools as well as charter middle and high schools from the South Los Angeles area will host an information table with applications for their school. Come hear about these programs and get on waiting lists early!\nChildcare for children 10 and under available with RSVP. Parking at Exposition Park costs $10 and there is nearby street parking available,\n- <a href="http://www.eventbrite.com/e/parents-as-partners-excellent-schools-for-all-children-tickets-9185513117?aff=eorg">Use this link to RSVP</a> or you can call 323-725-7888 to RSVP as well.\n- <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=waRM0vlbs0g">See an example of Dr. Fuller\'s speeches.</a></p>\n', 'Dec. 11: Free Speaking Event with Howard Fuller and School Resource Fair', 'On December 11th at the CA African American Museum, ExED and Families That Can are co-sponsoring an event for South LA parents and community members featuring passionate speaker Dr. Howard Fuller and a school resource with information tables from over 25 Los Angeles schools.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '264-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '2016-01-13 04:22:12', '', 264, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/264-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(939, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="Sacramento_screening.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2013/11/1391914_591633634236093_1409567125_n-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>Parents, teachers, and community leaders gathered outside of the Guild Theater in Sacramento on a warm Saturday in November. Most of them were from the local neighborhoods, but some had driven many miles to Sacramento\'s Oak Park neighborhood. They were drawn together to attend the screening and follow-up discussion of <em>We The Parents</em>, a documentary chronicling the first attempt to use <a href="http://www.parentsunion.org/content/basic-overview">California\'s parent trigger law</a>.\nThe film is an informative and emotionally charged story of how <a href="http://parentrevolution.org">Parent Revolution</a>, a California-based organization working to empower parents to improve their children\'s education, led a group of Compton parents in an effort to turn around McKinley Elementary, a chronically low-performing neighborhood school. The film begins in 2010, following local parents and community organizers as they walk door-to-door to gather the signatures needed to force change. It goes on to chronicle the community debate, public hearings, and legal battles that followed. While they were ultimately not successful, one thing is clear: No matter what his or her background might be, a parent is the most powerful advocate for improving public schools.\n<a href="https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.591631634236293.1073741831.102530249813103&amp;type=3">See photos from the event.</a>\nThe documentary did not deliver a Cinderella ending, but the insightful interviews with dozens of participants - a neighborhood priest, a single mother, the school principal, the pro-bono attorney - were thought-provoking. The movie set the stage for a lively discussion after the screening, narrated by Dr. Aisha Lowe, the director of Mayor Kevin Johnson\'s education non-profit STAND UP. Parents lined up to talk to the panel of parent organizers featured in the film with questions like: <em>What would you do differently? Why was creating a charter school the solution? What\'s happening at the school today?</em>\nPeople left the Guild Theater with one unifying thought: There are too many communities with schools like McKinley Elementary, and we can make a difference. That\'s why Families That Can and the California Charter Schools Association joined with Parent Revolution, Students First, Teach for America, STAND UP and other education reform organizations to bring We The Parents to Sacramento.</p>\n', 'Parent Power Highlighted at Film Screening in Sacramento', 'Parents, teachers, and community leaders gathered outside of the Guild Theater in Sacramento to attend the screening and follow-up discussion of We The Parents, a documentary chronicling the first attempt to use California\'s parent trigger law.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '263-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '', 263, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/263-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(940, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '<p>Do you have a child in a Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) school? The LAUSD school board wants to hear from parents about your priorities for funding. Respond before Oct. 31!\nTake the <a href="http://www.budgetrealities.lausd.net">LAUSD Budget Priorities Survey</a>.\nThe survey will go off-line on Oct. 31.</p>\n', 'LAUSD wants to know: What are your budget priorities?', 'The LAUSD school board wants to hear from parents about your priorities for funding. Respond to the LAUSD Budget Priorities Survey before Oct. 31!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '262-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '', 262, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/262-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(941, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '<div class="figure embedded-image center"><img alt="Awards 2.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2013/10/Awards 2-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></div>\n\n<p>On October 18, 2013, the Los Angeles Wave newspaper honored the most influential African-Americans of Los Angeles at an event at the California African American Museum.\nReverend K.W. Tulloss, Director of Family and Community Engagement, LA and Fellows Program for Families That Can, was honored with the award for Los Angeles Most Influential Leader under 40. He is a pastor and long-time community activist and is the  National Action Network Los Angeles leader. This award was presented to him in recognition of his diligent and devoted service he\'s provided to the Los Angeles community. Los Angeles County Supervisor Mark Ridley-Thomas received the Vanguard Award, Los Angeles City Council President Herb Wesson received the Mervyn Dymally Award and Community Activist Najee Ali received the Willis Edwards Award.\n"The Wave asked a list of top African-American academics, artists, civic organizations and leaders to ultimately select the most impactful African-American individuals in the City of Angels," Publisher Pluria Marshall Jr. said.</p>\n', 'KW Tulloss Honored as Most Influential Leader Under 40', 'Reverend K.W. Tulloss, Director of Family and Community Engagement, LA and Fellows Program for Families That Can, was honored with the award for Los Angeles Wave\'s Most Influential Leader under 40.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '261-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '', 261, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/261-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
