s Inteligente) en el a√±o escolar 2014-15. El nuevo examen, que es un proyecto piloto este a√±o escolar, refleja los nuevos est√°ndares estatales.\nLos estudiantes tomar√°n el nuevo examen en computadoras para aprovechar la tecnolog√≠a del siglo 21, que es m√°s precisa y eficiente que los ex√°menes en papel. Las evaluaciones van m√°s all√° de las preguntas de elecci√≥n m√∫ltiple e incluyen respuestas por escrito y tareas que permiten a los estudiantes demostrar su capacidad de resoluci√≥n de problemas reales.\n- <a href="http://www.smarterbalanced.org/parents-students/como-ayudar-a-todos-los-estudiantes-a-que-tengan-exito/">Informacion sobre Smarter Balanced Assessments</a>\n- <a href="http://www.smarterbalanced.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Smarter_Parents_Spanish.pdf">Hoja de Datos para Padres: Smarter Balanced Assessments</a>\n<strong>¬øC√≥mo puedo ayudar a mi hijo?</strong>\nTrabaje m√°s de cerca con los maestros y el personal de su escuela ch√°rter para aprender m√°s sobre c√≥mo van a implementar los nuevos est√°ndares. Por ejemplo, desde leer a sus ni√±os en casa m√°s libros que no sean de ficci√≥n hasta trabajar con ni√±os en Internet para desarrollar su confianza de usar la tecnolog√≠a de manera regular, las actividades en las que participan los padres pueden ser de muchas formas.\n- <a href="http://www.ccsesa.org/index/documents/T11-407Spanish.doc">Manual para padres de familia</a>\n- <a href="http://www.pta.org/parents/content.cfm?ItemNumber=3701">Este gu√≠a tiene informaci√≥n sobre lo que los estudiantes tienen que aprender en cada grado seg√∫n los nuevos est√°ndares.</a></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/51947947" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>&lt;</p>\n\n<p>p><a href="http://vimeo.com/51947947"></p>\n', '¬øQu√© es "Common Core"? Recursos para padres', 'Las escuelas p√∫blicas de California, entre ellas las escuelas ch√°rter, est√°n en el proceso  de implementar un  nuevo conjunto de est√°ndares para ingl√©s  y matem√°ticas llamado Est√°ndares Estatales Esenciales Comunes (Common Core State Standards).\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '260-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '', 260, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/260-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(943, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '<p>Corri Ravare and Diana Carranza of Families That Can joined two fellow charter parents, Maria and Edith, on Oct. 5 for Univision\'s Feria de Educacion. The goal was to increase awareness and visibility of Families That Can and share information about charter schools with our parent peers. The event was huge--thousands of parents and students participate in this event annually.  The university president opened the event with remarks and the Consulate General from Mexico also addressed the participants. Gabriela Tessier from Univision was the MC for the event.\nCorri shared this field report from the event:\n"We had a few hundred parents come to our table who asked questions about Families That Can and charter schools and signed up to become members.  Parents seemed to like the idea of a network of parents working collectively and many parents expressed their desire for more charter schools throughout Los Angeles and beyond including communities such as Bellflower, Azusa and quite a few parents mentioned their desire for more quality charters in Long Beach.  We also saw a few of our own charter parents from Magnolia, Celerity, KIPP, and many more schools. Charter schools had their own tables as well, including Alliance College-Ready Public Schools and Urban Village were there.  They were happy to see us out in the community with them."</p>\n', 'Charter Parents Spread the Word at Feria de la Educacion', 'Corri Ravare and Diana Carranza of Families That Can joined two fellow charter parents, Maria and Edith, on Oct. 5 for Univision\'s Feria de Educacion.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '259-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '', 259, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/259-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(944, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '<p>California public schools, including charter schools, are in the process of implementing a new set of standards for English and Math called Common Core State Standards. Schools are already making adjustments to their curriculum. In 2014-15, schools will fully transition to new state tests.</p>\n\n<h4>What are the Common Core State Standards?</h4>\n\n<p>Educational standards describe what students should know and be able to do in each subject in each grade. In California, the State Board of Education decides on the standards for all students, from kindergarten through high school. The California Department of Education helps schools make sure that all students are meeting the standards.\nSince 2010, 45 states have adopted the same standards for English and math. These standards are called the Common Core State Standards (CCSS). Having the same standards helps all students get a good education, even if they change schools or move to a different state. Teachers, parents, and education experts designed the CCSS to prepare students for success in college and the workplace. California adopted Common Core standards in 2010.\nAlthough California\'s 1997 academic standards for English and mathematics share many similarities in content and design with the new CCSS, it will take several years to implement the new standards.\n- <a href="http://www.cde.ca.gov/re/cc/">California Department of Education (CDE) Resources About Common Core</a></p>\n\n<h3>What are Smarter Balanced Assessments?</h3>\n\n<p>To help students meet the new goals, California will replace current state tests in English and mathematics with a new Smarter Balanced Assessment in the 2014-15 school year. The new test, which is being piloted this school year, reflects the new Common Core state standards.\nStudents will take the new test on computers to take advantage of 21st century technology, which is more precise and efficient than paper tests. Smarter Balanced assessments will go beyond multiple-choice questions and include written responses and tasks that allow students to demonstrate real-world problem solving.\n<a href="http://www.smarterbalanced.org/parents-students/">Learn more about Smarter Balanced Assessments.</a>\n<strong><em>Printable Fact Sheets</em></strong>\n- <a href="http://www.smarterbalanced.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/Smarter-Balanced-Parents-Factsheet.pdf">Fact Sheet: Smarter Balanced Assessments</a>\n- <a href="http://www.smarterbalanced.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/Smarter-Balanced-Benefits.pdf">Fact Sheet: What Will Smarter Balanced Assessments Mean for Me?</a>\nHow can I help my child?\nWork closely with teachers and staff at your charter school to learn more about how your school is implementing the new standards. For example, from reading more non-fiction to their children at home to working with children online to develop confidence in using technology on a regular basis, parent-involved activities can take many forms\n- <a href="http://www.ccsesa.org/index/sp_CommonCoreStandards.cfm">California\'s Common Core Parent Guide</a>\n- <a href="http://pta.org/parents/content.cfm?ItemNumber=2583">This nation-wide guide outlines what students should be learning at each grade-level according to the Common Core standards.</a></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/51933492" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>&lt;</p>\n\n<p>p><a href="http://vimeo.com/51933492"></p>\n', 'What is Common Core? Resources for Parents', 'California public schools are in the process of implementing a new set of standards for English and Math called Common Core State Standards. Learn what this means for you!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '258-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '', 258, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/258-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(945, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '<p>Have you ever heard someone say something about charter schools that is simply untrue? Did you speak up? LA charter school parents recently did!\nOn Oct. 2, Diane Ravitch appeared on <a href="http://www.scpr.org/programs/airtalk/2013/10/02/34017/in-reign-of-error-diane-ravitch-makes-the-argument/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+kpccAirTalk+(KPCC%3A+AirTalk)">Airtalk with Larry Mantle on KPCC 89.3 FM in Los Angeles</a> to promote her new book criticizing charter schools. She said many negative and inaccurate things about charter schools during the discussion. Fortunately, charter school parents called in to the show and shared their powerful personal stories. A parent from the West Adams neighborhood said that all the nearby schools were low-performing so her daughter would ride a bus more than an hour each way to a different school. She joined with other parents in her neighborhood to found a charter school that opened this fall and is excited to have a high-quality option in her own community.\nThese are some of the comments that parents posted:</p>\n\n<h3>Josie V</h3>\n\n<p>Charter schools are the best thing that happened to my family and to my community. It\'s so sad to see someone attacking them. Thanks to a charter school my younger sister got in to Brandeis University with a full scholarship. In the meantime myself and my other 2 siblings who went to a traditional public high school got lost in the system because there wasn\'t anyone to guide us. I\'m a proud parent of a 1st grader who attends a Charter School and I plan to keep her in there until she graduates from High School.</p>\n\n<h4>Anna</h4>\n\n<p>I have 2 sons both of whom have been in Public Charter schools in the LA county area. I chose charter schools primarily because of class size and a creative learning process. I don\'t think all kids learn the same way and having an art background myself, I felt strongly that I wanted my children\'s creativity to be stimulated as well as academics.</p>\n\n<h4>Joanne Ahola</h4>\n\n<p>Wow, that was difficult to listen to especially as a charter school parent. From today\'s radio program Ravitch believes charter schools are not public schools but private institutions. She believes charter schools kick out kids with low test scores, that they don\'t accept students with disabilities, and that they don\'t accept English language learners. What she is claiming about charter schools is absolutely illegal and charter schools are not allowed to choose students who are or are not accepted. If the number of applications exceeds the number of seats in a classroom, a random lottery takes place to determine which students get in or if they are put on a waiting list. Our family was put on the waiting list and we had to wait for a spot to open before we could get into the public charter we selected for our children.\nRavitch doesn\'t believe education should be a choice for parents and that it\'s more of a civic duty that education is provided. I absolutely disagree. Parents and children are the stakeholders and deserve a say in their children\'s education whether that\'s traditional or charter public education. I\'m a parent with two children in charter schools in Sacramento county. What better person than a parent or guardian to decide the best educational approach for their child? Simply adding arts back into traditional public education as Ravitch recommends, is not going to solve traditional school system woes and bring charter school parents back to traditional schools. Many charter schools offer alternative programs not offered in traditional schools. I know the alternative approach we selected for our son was the best approach for his learning needs. I\'m thankful I had a choice. Additionally, I know friends who have children in traditional schools and are thankful for the school their children are in. The key here is parent choice!\nRavitch also claimed teachers and students are leaving the traditional system and going into charter schools because they are fed up with standardized tests. This makes no sense because charter schools have to give the same tests as traditional schools. That\'s not the reason they are leaving. They\'re leaving because they\'re finding options that fit their children\'s learning needs better.\nMy question for Diane Ravitch is have you been to a charter school? Have you sat down with charter administrators and talked to them about what they actually do at their schools? Have you looked at data from the charter schools that are serving in poor neighborhoods to see how well they are serving these children? My guess is she hasn\'t. Also, where are your solutions?\nOne area where I agreed with Ravitch is she stated charter schools and traditional schools should collaborate and share ideas. That was the intention of charter policy, however, that bridge hasn\'t been created. We need to create this bridge.\nThe information she is disseminating is scary because she reaches a large audience and she is speaking untruth about charter schools.</p>\n', 'Parents call in to radio show to bust charter school myths', 'Have you ever heard someone say something about charter schools that is simply untrue? Did you speak up? LA charter school parents recently did!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '257-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '', 257, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/257-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(946, 3, '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '<p>Latonya Hamilton, a parent at <a href="http://www.vincentacademy.org">Vincent Academy</a> charter school in west Oakland, believes that parents need choices when it comes to their children\'s education. "Too many legislators don\'t understand what charter schools are," says Latonya.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/2OMzH0GLNos?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>Latonya encourages parents to do their research and find the best school. "Don\'t believe everything you hear; do your research," said Latonya. Vincent Academy opened in fall 2011.  Find the best school for your child using the <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/schools/">"Find a Charter School" map</a>.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/ZYuMJbBwHgc?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'VIDEO: Advice for Parents: "Do your research"', 'Latonya Hamilton, a parent at Vincent Academy charter school in west Oakland, believes that parents need choices when it comes to their children\'s education. She also shares some advice for parents who are looking for a school.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '256-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '2016-01-13 04:22:13', '', 256, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/256-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
